opment Authority has developed a new HIG Housing Complex near TV Tower, as a part of its \"DDA Housing Scheme-2008\".<ref>{{cite news |title=DDA launching new housing scheme soon  |url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/08/02/stories/2008080253840400.htm |publisher=The Hindu |date=2 Aug 2008 }}</ref>\n\nPitampura also attracts people from all over Delhi for shopping due to many high-class brands present and the presence of Netaji Subhash Place, Pitampura, a place to hang out. It is also a hub to many jewelry shops like Tanishq, Kalyan jewelers, PC Jewelers, etc.\n\n==Attractions==\nThe various major attractions of the region are-\n* [[Dilli Haat]] Pitam Pura\n* [[Pitampura TV Tower]]\n* District Park\n* [[Pitampura Club]]\n* Netaji Subhash Place\n* [[Hotel City Park]]\n* [[Fun Cinemas]](Now Cinepolis)\n* [[Max Hospital]]\n* Premsay Bakers (JD Market)\n* Samosa Junction\n* Shake Eat Up\n* Velocity Fitness Clinic\n* Pahwa Buildcon Pvt. Ltd.\n* Sai Baba Mandir\n* Kali Mata Mandir\n* Pitampura village\n* Gopal Mandir\n* Movie Time Pitampura\n* Kalyan Jewelers\n* Barbeque-Nation\n* SU block houses\n*Laser toners ( treasure enterprises)\n\n==Education==\n\n[[File:Delhi School of Business - A Leading PGDM College.jpg|thumb|Delhi School of Business - A Leading PGDM College in Delhi]]\n\nSeveral schools, colleges and vocational training institutes are growing in number here. One of those big ones is [[Sri Guru Gobind Singh College of Commerce]], popular for Bachelor of Business Economics (BBE), Bachelor of Commerce and Bachelor of Economics and [[Keshav Mahavidyalaya]], popular for Bachelor of Psychology & Bachelor of Business Studies (BBS) and the other is [[Kasturba Polytechnic For Women]]. Students across the country come here for higher studies.\n\n* Delhi School of Business (VIPS Technical Campus)\n* Management Studies:Magnum Opus School of Business Studies, Netaji Subhash Place\n* Jagannath Institute of Management Studies \n* Schools: [[Rukmini Devi Public School]], [[Maharaja Agrasen Model School]], [[St.Stephens School Pitampura]], [[Kendriya Vidyalaya|Kendriya Vidyalaya TP Block Pitampura]], [[D.A.V. Public School, Pushpanjali Enclave]], [[Apeejay School, Pitampura, Delhi]], [[Maxfort School, pitampura, Delhi]] [[Bal Bharati Public School|Bal Bharati Public School,Pitampura]], [[S.D public school]], [[Darbari Lal DAV Model School]], [[Guru Nanak Public School]], [[KIIT World School]], [[Sachdeva Public School]], [[Abhinav public school]], Delhi Public School, Rohini, VMC, FIITJEE, Career Launcher, Aakash Institute, Clat Possible and many more.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://delhigovt.nic.in/newdelhi/schoolsinn.html |title=Schools in North Delhi |access-date=29 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111023235224/http://delhigovt.nic.in/newdelhi/schoolsinn.html |archive-date=23 October 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Govt. of Delhi]]\n\n==Shopping and entertainment==\nWith the advent of shopping malls and retail outlets of world-renowned [[brands]] and [[designer labels]], like Gold Souk, Pacific Mall, M2K Cinemas, [[PVR Cinemas|PVR]], Fun Republic, Pitampura has developed really well, resulting in a skyrocketing of the real estate prices in the area. Pitampura also has some High-Class hotels like \"Hotel City Park\" and even otherwise. Also, Netaji Subash Place (NSP), which is a hangout hub for Delhiites comes under Pitampura. There is a local market in Pitampura which is called Rani Bagh market where people generally shop for fresh produce of fruits and vegetables, along with clothes and things needed at home, like utensils. It is a crowded place but the goods are really affordable.\n\n==Dilli Haat (Pitampura)==\n{{main|Dilli Haat}}\nDilli Haat at Pitam Pura, north-west Delhi, near the TV Tower, is the second of its kind project of Delhi Tourism and Transport Development Corporation. The success of the Dilli Haat at the INA market encouraged the DITDC to open another, bigger and better Dilli Haat, at Pitampura.\n\nThe Pitampura Haat, like its progenitor at the INA market, will showcase tribal art and craft, culture, cuisine, music, as well as the essence of street culture. The gateway to the Haat will serve as a street plaza. Vendors selling everything from paper toys and balloons to popcorn will get space on the walkway, giving a feel of Delhi\u2019s street culture.\n\nThere is to be a spice court that will allow shoppers to pick up authentic spices. Right next to it is the art court comprising an exhibition and art gallery space. The craft shops have been organized in two blocks along a central axis. At the rear of the Haat there is an amphitheater and food court, but to reach the food court you will have to walk through the craft stores. It is a clever way of attracting people to buy as these food stalls attract the maximum crowd.\n\n[[File:Pitampura TV tower as seen from Dilli Haat,Pitampura,New Delhi.jpg|thumb|Pitampura TV tower as seen from Dilli Haat, Pitampura, New Delhi]]\n\n==Accessibility==\nAs many as three [[Delhi Metro]] Stations - [[Netaji Subhash Place (Delhi Metro)|Netaji Subhash Place]], [[Kohat Enclave (Delhi Metro)|Kohat Enclave]] and [[Pitam Pura (Delhi Metro)|Pitampura]], cover this locality.\n\nIt is very close to [[Rohini Sub City|Rohini]], [[Rani_Bagh,_Delhi | Rani Bagh]], [[Model Town (Delhi)|Model Town]], [[Shalimar Bagh, Delhi|Shalimar Bagh]], [[Punjabi Bagh]], [[Ashok Vihar]], Lawrence Road areas. Pitampura has many housing colonies like SD-Tower Apartments (known for the largest Super HIG flats by DDA and also for its nearness to Netaji Subhash district center and TV Tower), Vaishali, Saraswati Vihar (the largest colony of Pitampura), Lok Vihar, [[Ajay Apartments]], Apna Ghar Society, Bank Vihar, I.D.P.L. Colony, [[Kohat Enclave]], Rohit Kunj, Sandesh Vihar, Jhulelal Apartments, Engineer's Enclave, Harsh Vihar, Kapil Vihar, Vishakha Enclave, Maurya Enclave etc. These societies have various facilities like community centers, central parks and parking lots.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://maps.google.co.in/maps?pq=pitampura&hl=en&cp=15&gs_id=o&xhr=t&q=pitampura+delhi&client=firefox-a&hs=IOH&rls=org.mozilla:en-US:official&gs_upl=&bav=on.2,or.r_gc.r_pw.&biw=1440&bih=765&um=1&ie=UTF-8&hq=&hnear=0x390d03d5b0619f3f:0x2208402cf282fb02,Pitampura,+New+Delhi,+Delhi&gl=in&ei=V2-ETvYeoZmJB_OK-aoP&sa=X&oi=geocode_result&ct=title&resnum=1&sqi=2&ved=0CCcQ8gEwAA Pitampura] at [[Google Maps]]\n* [http://wikimapia.org/153608/Pitampura-Metro-Station Pitam Pura Metro Station] at [[wikimapia]]\n* [http://www.delhitourism.gov.in/delhitourism/tourist_place/pitampura.jsp Dilli Haat Pitam Pura] at [[Delhi Tourism]]\n\n{{Neighborhoods of Delhi}}\n\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Delhi]]\n[[Category:North West Delhi district]]\n", "name_user": "171.50.170.140", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAttractions)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pitam_Pura"}
{"title_page": "1953 in literature", "text_new": "{{Year nav topic5|1953|literature|poetry}}\n\nThis article presents lists of literary events and publications in '''1953'''.\n<!-- Redlinks will be removed. They make no sense in a list. Add pages as you write them. -->\n==Events==\n*[[January 5]] \u2013 ''[[Waiting For Godot]]'', a play by the [[Irish people|Irish]] writer [[Samuel Beckett]], has its first public stage performance, in French as ''En attendant Godot'', at the Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de Babylone in [[Paris]]. Beckett's novel ''[[The Unnamable (novel)|The Unnamable]]'' is also published in French this year.\n*[[January 22]] \u2013 ''[[The Crucible]]'', a historical drama by [[Arthur Miller]] written as an [[allegory]] of [[McCarthyism]], opens on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] at the [[Martin Beck Theatre]].\n*[[February 19]] \u2013 The State of [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] approves the first [[literature]] [[censorship]] board in the United States.\n*[[April 13]] \u2013 The face of popular literature changes with the publication of [[Ian Fleming]]'s novel ''[[Casino Royale (novel)|Casino Royale]]'', introducing the British spy character [[James Bond]].\n*May \u2013 The semi-autobiographical ''[[Go Tell It on the Mountain (novel)|Go Tell It on the Mountain]]'' by [[James Baldwin (writer)|James Baldwin]] is published. In 2001, it will be named as one of the 100 best English-language novels of the 20th century by the editors of the American Modern Library.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/books/news/9807/21/top.100.reax/index.html |title=The Top 100? 100 best novels list draws heavy dose of criticism |publisher=[[CNN]] |first=Jamie |last=Allen |date=1999-05-06}}</ref>\n*[[June 17]] \u2013 [[Bertolt Brecht]] continues uninterrupted with rehearsals for the first production of [[Erwin Strittmatter]]'s ''Katzgraben: Szenen aus dem Bauernleben'', with the [[Berliner Ensemble]] during the [[Uprising of 1953 in East Germany]]. The incident inspires [[G\u00fcnter Grass]]'s ''Die Plebejer proben den Aufstand'' (\"The Plebeians Rehearse the Uprising\", [[1966 in literature|1966]]).\n*[[July 13]] \u2013 The first [[Stratford Shakespeare Festival|Stratford Shakespearean Festival of Canada]] opens in [[Stratford, Ontario]].\n*[[September 9]] \u2013 The [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] decision in ''Rumely v. United States'' affirms that indirect [[History of lobbying in the United States|lobbying in the United States]] by distribution of books intended to influence opinion is a public good and not subject to regulation by [[United States Congress|Congress]].<ref>345 U.S. 41 (1953).</ref>\n*October \u2013 The [[literary magazine]] ''[[Encounter (magazine)|Encounter]]'' begins publication in London under the editorship of the American political journalist [[Irving Kristol]] and the English poet [[Stephen Spender]], with covert sponsorship by the [[Central Intelligence Agency]].\n*[[October 21]] \u2013 Shortly after being made a [[Knight Bachelor]], English actor Sir [[John Gielgud]] is convicted of \"persistently importuning male persons for an immoral purpose\" ([[cottaging]]) in [[Chelsea, London]].<ref>{{Cite news |work=[[The Times]] |location=London |date=22 October 1953 |issue=52759 |page=5 |title=Fine For \"Persistently Importuning\" |quote=Described on the charge sheet as a clerk}}</ref>\n*[[November 5]] \u2013 [[Dylan Thomas]], on a poetry reading tour of the United States, is admitted to [[St. Vincent's Hospital, Manhattan]] in a coma, which continues until his death on November 9. Early versions of his play for voices ''[[Under Milk Wood]]'' have been given in the United States this year, but it is not broadcast in its final form until 1954.\n\n''Uncertain dates''\n*[[Ronald Harwood]] becomes Sir [[Donald Wolfit]]'s dresser.\n*[[John Dickson Carr]] writing as Carter Dickson publishes his final [[Sir Henry Merrivale]] [[Mystery fiction|mystery]] novel.\n*After five years as an English teacher, [[Frederick Buechner]] moves to [[New York City]] to become a full-time writer.\n*[[Federico Garc\u00eda Lorca]]'s ''Obras Completas'' (Complete Works) are published in Spain as a prohibition on his work is lifted there.\n*The American novelist [[Howard Fast]] is awarded the [[Lenin Peace Prize|Stalin Peace Prize]].\n*[[Brian O'Nolan]] is obliged to retire from a senior post in the [[Civil Service of the Republic of Ireland]] on grounds of alcoholism and impoliteness to senior politicians.<ref>{{Cite news |last=O'Toole |first=Fintan |authorlink=Fintan O'Toole |title=The Fantastic Flann O'Brien |work=[[The Irish Times]] |location=Dublin |date=2011-01-01 |accessdate=2011-10-02 |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper |quote=A combination of his gradually deepening alcoholism and his habit of making derogatory remarks about senior politicians in his newspaper columns led to his forced retirement from the civil service in 1953. (He departed, recalled a colleague, \"in a final fanfare of f***s\".)}}</ref>\n*French journalist Jean Borel's article \"''Zola a-t-il \u00e9t\u00e9 assassin\u00e9?''\" in ''[[Lib\u00e9ration (newspaper, 1941-1964)|Lib\u00e9ration]]'' suggests that [[\u00c9mile Zola]]'s death in [[1902 in literature|1902]] was not accidental.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Mounier-Kuhn |first=Ang\u00e9lique |title=L'asphyxie d'\u00c9mile Zola |work=[[Le Temps]] |date=2014-08-08 |pages=8\u20139}}</ref>\n*[[City Lights Bookstore]] is established in [[San Francisco]] by [[Lawrence Ferlinghetti]] and [[Peter D. Martin]].\n\n==New books==\n<!-- (''Title of published book translation''), (\"Title of published poem/story translation\"), (Literal translation of title) -->\n===Fiction===\n*[[Ilse Aichinger]] \u2013 ''Der Gefesselte'' (The Bound Man, short stories)\n*[[Sholom Aleichem]] \u2013 ''[[Adventures of Mottel the Cantor's Son]]'' (translation)\n*[[Phyllis Shand Allfrey]] \u2013 ''[[The Orchid House (novel)|The Orchid House]]''\n*[[Mulk Raj Anand]] \u2013 ''[[The Private Life of an Indian Prince]]''\n*[[Isaac Asimov]] \u2013 ''[[Second Foundation]]''\n*[[Nigel Balchin]] \u2013 ''[[Sundry Creditors]]''\n*[[James Baldwin (writer)|James Baldwin]] \u2013 ''[[Go Tell It on the Mountain (novel)|Go Tell It on the Mountain]]''\n*[[Saul Bellow]] \u2013 ''[[The Adventures of Augie March]]''\n*[[Alfred Bester (author)|Alfred Bester]] \u2013 ''[[The Demolished Man]]''\n*[[Zealia Bishop]] \u2013 ''[[The Curse of Yig (book)|The Curse of Yig]]''\n*[[Heinrich B\u00f6ll]] \u2013 ''[[And Never Said a Word]] (Und sagte kein einziges Wort)''\n*[[Ray Bradbury]]\n**''[[Fahrenheit 451]]''\n**''[[The Golden Apples of the Sun]]''\n*[[Gwendolyn Brooks]] \u2013 ''[[Maud Martha]]''\n*[[William S. Burroughs]] (as William Lee) \u2013 ''[[Junkie (novel)|Junkie]]''\n*[[John Dickson Carr]] (as Carter Dickson) \u2013 ''[[The Cavalier's Cup]]''\n*[[Raymond Chandler]] \u2013 ''[[The Long Goodbye (novel)|The Long Goodbye]]''\n*[[Agatha Christie]]\n**''[[After the Funeral]]''\n**''[[A Pocket Full of Rye]]''\n*[[Arthur C. Clarke]]\n**''[[Against the Fall of Night]]''\n**''[[Childhood's End]]''\n*[[Beverly Cleary]] \u2013 ''[[Otis Spofford]]''\n*[[Ivy Compton-Burnett]] \u2013 ''[[The Present and the Past]]''\n*[[A. J. Cronin]] \u2013 ''[[Beyond This Place]]''\n*[[Roald Dahl]] \u2013 ''[[Someone Like You (collection)|Someone Like You]]'' (short stories)\n*[[Roald Dahl]] \u2013 \"[[Nunc Dimittis (short story)|Nunc Dimittis]]\"\n*[[L. Sprague de Camp]]\n**''[[The Continent Makers and Other Tales of the Viagens]]''\n**''[[Sprague de Camp's New Anthology of Science Fiction]]''\n**''[[The Tritonian Ring and Other Pusadian Tales]]''\n*[[L. Sprague de Camp]] and [[Fletcher Pratt]] \u2013 ''[[Tales from Gavagan's Bar]]''\n*[[Lloyd C. Douglas]] \u2013 ''[[The Robe]]''\n*[[Islwyn Ffowc Elis]] \u2013 ''Cysgod y Cryman'' (Shadow of the Sickle)\n*[[Ian Fleming]] \u2013 ''[[Casino Royale (novel)|Casino Royale]]''\n*[[C. S. Forester]] \u2013 ''[[Hornblower and the Atropos]]''\n*[[Ernest K. Gan