ne]]''\n*[[Wolfgang Koeppen]] \u2013 ''Das Treibhaus (The Hothouse)''\n*[[Camara Laye]] \u2013 ''L'Enfant noir''\n*[[Ira Levin]] \u2013 ''[[A Kiss Before Dying (novel)|A Kiss Before Dying]]''\n* [[Audrey Erskine Lindop]] \u2013 ''[[The Singer Not the Song (novel)|The Singer Not the Song]]''\n*[[Virgilio Rodr\u00edguez Macal]] \u2013 ''[[Carazamba]]''\n*[[Angus MacVicar]] \u2013 ''[[The Lost Planet (novel)|The Lost Planet]]''\n*[[James A. Michener]] \u2013 ''[[The Bridges at Toko-Ri]]''\n*[[Roger Nimier]] \u2013 ''[[Nothing to Make a Fuss About]]''\n*[[Flannery O'Connor]] \u2013 \"[[A Good Man Is Hard to Find (short story)|A Good Man Is Hard to Find]]\" (short story)\n*[[Zoe B. Oldenbourg]] \u2013 ''The Cornerstone''\n*[[Alan Paton]] \u2013 ''[[Too Late the Phalarope]]''\n*[[Mervyn Peake]] \u2013 ''[[Mr Pye]]''\n*[[Barbara Pym]] \u2013 ''[[Jane and Prudence]]''\n*[[Ellery Queen]] \u2013 ''[[The Scarlet Letters]]''\n*[[Marjorie Kinnan Rawlings]] \u2013 ''The Sojourner''\n*[[Mary Renault]] \u2013 ''[[The Charioteer]]''\n*[[Karl Ristikivi]] \u2013 ''Hingede \u00f6\u00f6'' (The Night of Souls)\n*[[Alain Robbe-Grillet]] \u2013 ''Les Gommes'' (The Erasers)\n*[[Juan Rulfo]] \u2013 ''[[El Llano en llamas]]'' (''The Burning Plain'', short stories)\n*[[J. D. Salinger]] \u2013 ''[[Nine Stories (Salinger)|Nine Stories]]''\n*[[Samuel Shellabarger]] \u2013 ''Lord Vanity''\n*[[Wilmar H. Shiras]] \u2013 ''[[Children of the Atom]]''\n*[[Rex Stout]] \u2013 ''[[The Golden Spiders]]''\n*[[Theodore Sturgeon]] \u2013 ''[[More Than Human]]''\n*[[Jim Thompson (writer)|Jim Thompson]] \u2013 ''[[Savage Night]]''\n*[[Leon Uris]] \u2013 ''[[Battle Cry (Leon Uris novel)|Battle Cry]]''\n*[[Boris Vian]] \u2013 ''[[Heartsnatcher]]''\n*[[A. E. van Vogt]] \u2013 ''[[The Universe Maker]]''\n*[[John Wain]] \u2013 ''Hurry on Down''\n*[[Evelyn Waugh]] \u2013 ''[[Love Among the Ruins. A Romance of the Near Future|Love Among the Ruins]]''\n*[[Ben Ames Williams]] \u2013 ''[[The Unconquered (novel)|The Unconquered]]''\n*[[John Wyndham (writer)|John Wyndham]] \u2013 ''[[The Kraken Wakes]]''\n\n===Children and young people===\n*[[Viola Bayley]] \u2013 ''White Holiday''\n*[[Richard Hough|Bruce Carter]] \u2013 ''Speed Six!''\n*[[Roger Lancelyn Green]] \u2013 ''[[King Arthur and His Knights of the Round Table]]''\n*[[C. S. Lewis]] \u2013 ''[[The Silver Chair]]'' (fourth in ''[[The Chronicles of Narnia]]'' series of seven books)\n*[[Elinor Lyon]] \u2013 ''Run Away Home''\n*[[Joan Phipson]] \u2013 ''Good Luck to the Rider''\n*[[Joan G. Robinson]] \u2013 ''Teddy Robinson''\n*[[Miriam Schlein]] \u2013 ''When Will the World Be Mine?'' (non-fiction)\n*[[Geoffrey Willans]] (illustrated by [[Ronald Searle]]) \u2013 ''Down with Skool! A Guide to School Life for Tiny Pupils and their Parents'' (first in the [[Nigel Molesworth]] series of four books)\n\n===Drama===\n<onlyinclude>\n*[[Arthur Adamov]] \u2013 ''Professor Taranne (Le Professeur Taranne)''\n*[[Robert Anderson (playwright)|Robert Anderson]] \u2013 ''[[Tea and Sympathy (play)|Tea and Sympathy]]''\n*[[Samuel Beckett]] \u2013 ''[[Waiting for Godot]] (En attendant Godot)''\n*[[Ugo Betti]] \u2013 ''[[The Fugitive (Ugo Betti play)|The Fugitive]]'' (''La Fuggitiva'', premiered posthumously)\n*[[Agatha Christie]] \u2013 ''[[Witness for the Prosecution (play)|Witness for the Prosecution]]''\n*[[Max Frisch]] \u2013 ''[[The Fire Raisers (play)|The Fire Raisers]]'' (''Biedermann und die Brandstifter'', originally for radio)\n*[[Witold Gombrowicz]] \u2013 ''[[The Marriage (Gombrowicz play)|The Marriage]]'' (''\u015alub'', Polish version published)\n* [[N.C. Hunter]] \u2013 ''[[A Day by the Sea]]''\n*[[Arthur Miller]] \u2013 ''[[The Crucible]]''\n*[[Erwin Strittmatter]] \u2013 ''Katzgraben''\n*[[Vernon Sylvaine]] \u2013 ''[[As Long as They're Happy (play)|As Long as They're Happy]]''</onlyinclude>\n*[[Emlyn Williams]] \u2013 ''[[Someone Waiting]]''\n\n===Poetry===\n*''[[The Faber Book of Twentieth Century Verse]]'' edited by [[John Heath-Stubbs]] and [[David Wright (poet)|David Wright]]\n\n===Non-fiction===\n*[[George Dangerfield]] \u2013 ''[[The Era of Good Feelings]]'' ([[Bancroft Prize]])\n*[[L. Sprague de Camp]] \u2013 ''[[Science-Fiction Handbook]]''\n*[[Gerald Durrell]] \u2013 ''[[The Overloaded Ark]]''\n*[[Lawrence Durrell]] \u2013 ''Reflections on a Marine Venus''\n*[[Geoffrey Elton]] \u2013 ''The Tudor Revolution in Government''\n*[[Heinrich Harrer]] \u2013 ''[[Seven Years in Tibet]]''\n*Clarence C. Hulley \u2013 ''[[Alaska 1741-1953|Alaska 1741\u20131953]]''\n*[[Nancy Mitford]] \u2013 ''Madame de Pompadour''\n*[[Roger Peyrefitte]] \u2013 ''Les Cl\u00e9s de saint Pierre'' (The Keys of St Peter)\n*[[K. M. Panikkar]] \u2013 ''Asia and Western Dominance''\n*[[Sebastian Snow]] \u2013 ''My Amazon Adventure''\n*[[R. W. Southern]] \u2013 ''The Making of the Middle Ages''\n*[[John Summerson]] \u2013 ''Architecture in Britain: 1530\u20131830''\n*[[Ludwig Wittgenstein]] \u2013 ''[[Philosophical Investigations]]''\n\n==Births==\n*[[January 7]] \u2013 [[Dionne Brand]], Canadian poet\n*[[February 5]] \u2013 [[Giannina Braschi]], Puerto Rican-born poet and novelist\n*[[February 10]] \u2013 [[John Shirley]], American science fiction and horror writer\n*[[February 18]] \u2013 [[Peter Robinson (poet)|Peter Robinson]], English poet\n*[[March 12]] \u2013 [[Carl Hiaasen]], American journalist and novelist\n*[[March 25]] \u2013 [[John Tierney (journalist)|John Tierney]], American journalist\n*[[March 26]] \u2013 [[George Dyson (science historian)|George Dyson]], American science historian\n*[[April 3]]\n**[[Pieter Aspe]] (Pierre Aspelag), Belgian crime writer\n**[[Sandra Boynton]], American humorist and children's writer\n*[[April 20]] \u2013 [[Sebastian Faulks]], English novelist\n*[[April 23]] \u2013 [[Roberto Bola\u00f1o]], Chilean-born fiction writer (died [[2003 in literature|2003]])\n*[[May 10]] \u2013 [[Christopher Paul Curtis]], American children's writer\n*[[May 12]] \u2013 [[Neil Astley]], English author, poet and academic\n*[[May 19]] \u2013 [[Victoria Wood]], English comedian and writer (died [[2016 in literature|2016]])\n*[[July 29]] \u2013 [[Frank McGuinness]], Irish dramatist, poet and novelist\n*[[August 1]] \u2013 [[Howard Kurtz]], American journalist and author\n*[[August 10]] \u2013 [[Mark Doty]], American poet and memoirist\n*[[August 17]] \u2013 [[Korrie Layun Rampan]], Indonesian writer (died [[2015 in literature|2015]])\n*[[September 5]] \u2013 [[Herman Koch]], Dutch fiction writer and actor\n*[[September 10]] \u2013 [[Pat Cadigan]], American science fiction author\n*[[September 23]] \u2013 [[Nicholas Witchell]], English television journalist\n*[[November 5]] \u2013 [[Joyce Maynard]], American memoirist and fiction writer\n*[[November 18]] \u2013 [[Alan Moore]], English comic-book and graphic-novel scriptwriter\n*[[December 15]] \u2013 [[Doug Lucie]], English dramatist\n\n''Uncertain date''\n*[[Gary Taylor (scholar)|Gary Taylor]], American Shakespearean scholar\n\n==Deaths==\n*[[April 4]] \u2013 [[Rachilde]] (Marguerite Vallette-Eymery), French author (born [[1860 in literature|1860]])\n*[[April 6]] \u2013 [[Idris Davies]], Welsh poet in Welsh and English (abdominal cancer, born [[1905 in literature|1905]])\n*[[April 9]] \u2013 [[C. E. M. Joad]], English philosopher and broadcaster (born [[1891 in literature|1891]])\n*[[April 13]] \u2013 [[Alice Milligan]], Irish poet (born [[1865 in literature|1865]])\n*[[April 24]] \u2013 [[Alfred Vierkandt]], German sociologist (born [[1867 in literature|1867]])\n*[[June 5]] \u2013 [[Moelona]], Welsh-language novelist and translator (born [[1877 in literature|1877]])\n*[[June 25]] \u2013 [[Richard Jebb (journalist)|Richard Jebb]], English journalist (born [[1874 in literature|1874]])\n*[[June 30]] \u2013 [[Elsa Beskow]], Swedish children's author and illustrator (born 1874)\n*[[July 6]] \u2013 [[Julia de Burgos]], Puerto Rican poet in Spanish (pneumonia, born [[1914 in literature|1914]])\n*[[July 16]] \u2013 [[Hilaire Belloc]], English humorous poet, essayist and travel writer (born [[1870 in literature|1870]])\n*[[August 12]] \u2013 [[J. H. M. Abbott]], Australian novelist and poet (born 1874 in literature|1874]])\n*[[August 30]] \u2013 [[Maurice Nicoll]], English psychiatrist and writer on psychology (born [[1884 in literature|1884]])\n*[[November 8]]\n**[[Ivan Bunin]], Russian-born writer and Nobel laureate (born [[1870 in literature|1870]])\n**[[John van Melle]], South African author (born [[1887 in literature|1887]])\n*[[November 9]] \u2013 [[Dylan Thomas]], Welsh poet and author (pneumonia, born [[1914 in literature|1914]])\n*[[November 27]]\n**[[Eugene O'Neill]], American playwright (born [[1888 in literature|1888]])\n**[[T. F. Powys]], English novelist (born [[1875 in literature|1875]])\n*[[November 30]] \u2013 [[Francis Picabia]], French poet and painter [[1879 in literature|1879]])\n*[[December 8]] \u2013 [[Claude Scudamore Jarvis]], writer, Arabist and naturalist (born [[1879 in literature|1879]])\n\n''Uncertain dates''\n**[[Mae Virginia Cowdery]], African American poet (suicide, born [[1909 in literature|1909]])\n**[[Gordon Hall Gerould]], American philologist (born [[1877 in literature|1877]])\n**[[Eirik Vandvik]], Norwegian classicist and translator (born [[1904 in literature|1904]])\n**[[Tan Khoen Swie]], Indonesian publisher (year of birth uncertain)\n\n==Awards==\n*[[Carnegie Medal in Literature|Carnegie Medal]] for [[children's literature]]: Edward Osmond, ''[[A Valley Grows Up]]''\n*[[Christopher Award]]: [[Marie Killilea]], ''Karen''\n*[[Governor General's Awards|Governor General's Award]] for Poetry or Drama: [[Douglas LePan]], ''The Net and the Sword'' <ref>[http://www.canadacouncil.ca/NR/rdonlyres/E22B9A3C-5906-41B8-B39C-F91F58B3FD70/0/cumulativewinners2010rev.pdf \"Cumulative List of Winners of the Governor General's Literary Awards\"], Canada Council. Web, February 10, 2011</ref>\n*[[James Tait Black Memorial Prize]] for fiction: [[Margaret Kennedy]], ''Troy Chimneys''\n*[[James Tait Black Memorial Prize]] for biography: [[Carola Oman]], ''[[John Moore (British Army officer)|Sir John Moore]]''\n*[[National Book Award]] for Fiction: [[Ralph Ellison]], ''[[Invisible Man (novel)|Invisible Man]]''\n*[[Newbery Medal]] for [[children's literature]]: [[Ann Nolan Clark]], ''[[Secret of the Andes]]''\n*[[Nobel Prize for Literature]]: [[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Leonard Spencer Churchill]]\n*[[Premio Nadal]]: [[Luisa Forrellad]], ''Siempre en capilla''\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Drama]]: [[William Inge]], ''[[Picnic (play)|Picnic]]''\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Fiction]]: [[Ernest Hemingway]], ''[[The Old Man and the Sea]]''\n*[[Pulitzer Prize for Poetry]]: [[Archibald MacLeish]], ''Collected Poems 1917-1952''\n*[[Queen's Gold Medal for Poetry]]: [[Arthur Waley]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1953 In Literature}}\n\n{{Year in literature article categories}}\n[[Category:1953 books| ]]\n[[Category:Years of the 20th century in literature]]\n", "name_user": "Bmcln1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1953_in_literature"}
{"title_page": "Wollo Province", "text_new": "[[File:Wello in Ethiopia (1943-1987).svg|thumb|right|Location of Wollo within the [[Ethiopian Empire]]]]\n'''Wollo''' ([[Amharic language|Amharic]]: \u12c8\u120e, well\u00f2) is a historical region and province in the northeastern part of [[Ethiopia]], with its capital city at [[Dessie]]. The name \"Wello\" is from Oromo Language and belong to the Kereyu oromo clan leader who first invaded Bete Amhara including Midre-Gegn.\n\nThe province formerly and historically was called Bete-Amhara. Its name was changed to Wollo in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries following the invasion of Bete-Amhara by an Kereyu Oromo Clan by the leader Wollo.  \nPeasant rebellions rocked the province, which included the [[Woyane rebellion]] in 1943, and revolts of the [[Yejju]] in 1948 and 1970.<ref>Sarah Vaughan, [http://www.ihasa.org/documents/special-reports/ethnicity-in-ethiopia.pdf \"Ethnicity and Power in Ethiopia\"] (University of Edinburgh: Ph.D. Thesis, 2003), p. 126</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of [[TPLF]]'s rule of [[Ethiopia]] (between 1991 and 2018), Raya (i.e. [[Lasta]] & [[Wag (district)|Wag]]) and [[Welkait]] were taken away from the  [[Welo]] and [[Begemder]] [[Provinces of Ethiopia|provinces]] respectively and given to Tigray.<ref>This list of provinces is based on the map in Bahru Zewde, ''A History of Modern Ethiopia'' (London: James Currey, 1991), p. 86.</ref> Therefore, until the 1995 administrative reorganization, Raya was part of [[Welo]] [[Provinces of Ethiopia|province]]. Raya was then split into two parts once [[ethnic federalism]] was established in Ethiopia (on 1995). One of the two parts with an Amhara majority ([[Kobo, Ethiopia|Kobo]]) went to the new [[Amhara Region]], the other ([[Raya Azebo]]) which had a majority of ([[Tigrayans]]) was given to [[Tigray Region]]  <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.academia.edu/12012872/DMT_-_One_and_the_same_as_Queen_Yodits_Damot|title= Bernard Leeman, THE REALM OF D\u2019MT - ONE AND THE SAME AS QUEEN YODIT\u2019S DAMOT?}} </ref><ref name=\"Thurstan612\">{{citation | last=Shaw | first=Thurstan | year=1995 | title=The Archaeology of Africa: Food, Metals and Towns | publisher=Routledge | isbn=978-0-415-11585-8 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TmUwjhQX-rcC&pg=PA612 | page= 612}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/pdf/KingdomOfAksum_TeachersNotes.pdf |title=The British Museum, \"The wealth of Africa:- The kingdom of Aksum\"}}</ref>,.<ref>Bereket Habte Selassie, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/744683 \"Constitutional Development in Ethiopia\", ''Journal of African Law''], '''10''' (1966), p. 79.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.era.lib.ed.ac.uk/bitstream/id/1299/vaughanphd.pdf |title=Sarah Vaughan, \"Ethnicity and Power in Ethiopia\", PhD dissertation, p. 123, 2003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The 1994 Population and Housing Census of Ethiopia Results for Tigray Region|last=|first=|publisher=Central Statistical Authority|year=1995|isbn=|volume=1|location=Addis Ababa|pages=70}}</ref>\n\nWith the adoption of the [[1995 Constitution of Ethiopia|1995 constitution]] & the establishment of [[ethnic federalism]] system in [[Ethiopia]], parts of the expanded Wollo province, which were mostly inhabited by [[Afar people]] were given to the new [[Afar Region]]. The new [[Amhara Region]] absorbed the remainder of the province in the [[Ethiopian Highlands]] and kept the name Wollo for its two new zones ([[South Wollo Zone]] & [[North Wollo Zone]]). In fact both North and South Wollo Provinces do not represent south and north parts of Wollo, they are central even today.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{First-level administrative divisions of Ethiopia}}\n\n{{coord|11|30|N|40|00|E|display=title|region:ET_type:adm1st_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n[[Category:Afar Region]]\n[[Category:Amhara Region]]\n[[Category:Provinces of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1995]]\n[[Category:Tigray Region]]\n\n{{Tigray-geo-stub}}\n{{Afar-geo-stub}}\n{{Ethiopia-hist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Wello in Ethiopia (1943-1987).svg|thumb|right|Location of Wollo within the [[Ethiopian Empire]]]]\n'''Wollo''' ([[Amharic language|Amharic]]: \u12c8\u120e, well\u00f2) is a historical region and province in the northeastern part of [[Ethiopia]], with its capital city at [[Dessie]]. The name \"Wello\" in Amharic means 'one-third', it is a form of measurement.\n\nThe province formerly and historically was called Lakomelza. Its name was changed to Wollo following the foundation of modern Ethiopia in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries. \nPeasant rebellions rocked the province, which included the [[Woyane rebellion]] in 1943, and revolts of the [[Yejju]] in 1948 and 1970.<ref>Sarah Vaughan, [http://www.ihasa.org/documents/special-reports/ethnicity-in-ethiopia.pdf \"Ethnicity and Power in Ethiopia\"] (University of Edinburgh: Ph.D. Thesis, 2003), p. 126</ref>\n\nAt the beginning of [[TPLF]]'s rule of [[Ethiopia]] (between 1991 and 2018), Raya (i.e. [[Lasta]] & [[Wag (district)|Wag]]) and [[Welkait]] were taken away from the  [[Welo]] and [[Begemder]] [[Provinces of Ethiopia|provinces]] respectively and given to Tigray.<ref>This list of provinces is based on the map in Bahru Zewde, ''A History of Modern Ethiopia'' (London: James Currey, 1991), p. 86.</ref> Therefore, until the 1995 administrative reorganization, Raya was part of [[Welo]] [[Provinces of Ethiopia|province]]. Raya was then split into two parts once [[ethnic federalism]] was established in Ethiopia (on 1995). One of the two parts with an Amhara majority ([[Kobo, Ethiopia|Kobo]]) went to the new [[Amhara Region]], the other ([[Raya Azebo]]) which had a majority of ([[Tigrayans]]) was given to [[Tigray Region]]  <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.academia.edu/12012872/DMT_-_One_and_the_same_as_Queen_Yodits_Damot|title= Bernard Leeman, THE REALM OF D\u2019MT - ONE AND THE SAME AS QUEEN YODIT\u2019S DAMOT?}} </ref><ref name=\"Thurstan612\">{{citation | last=Shaw | first=Thurstan | year=1995 | title=The Archaeology of Africa: Food, Metals and Towns | publisher=Routledge | isbn=978-0-415-11585-8 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TmUwjhQX-rcC&pg=PA612 | page= 612}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/pdf/KingdomOfAksum_TeachersNotes.pdf |title=The British Museum, \"The wealth of Africa:- The kingdom of Aksum\"}}</ref>,.<ref>Bereket Habte Selassie, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/744683 \"Constitutional Development in Ethiopia\", ''Journal of African Law''], '''10''' (1966), p. 79.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.era.lib.ed.ac.uk/bitstream/id/1299/vaughanphd.pdf |title=Sarah Vaughan, \"Ethnicity and Power in Ethiopia\", PhD dissertation, p. 123, 2003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=The 1994 Population and Housing Census of Ethiopia Results for Tigray Region|last=|first=|publisher=Central Statistical Authority|year=1995|isbn=|volume=1|location=Addis Ababa|pages=70}}</ref>\n\nWith the adoption of the [[1995 Constitution of Ethiopia|1995 constitution]] & the establishment of [[ethnic federalism]] system in [[Ethiopia]], parts of the expanded Wollo province, which were mostly inhabited by [[Afar people]] were given to the new [[Afar Region]]. The new [[Amhara Region]] absorbed the remainder of the province in the [[Ethiopian Highlands]] and kept the name Wollo for its two new zones ([[South Wollo Zone]] & [[North Wollo Zone]]).\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{First-level administrative divisions of Ethiopia}}\n\n{{coord|11|30|N|40|00|E|display=title|region:ET_type:adm1st_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n[[Category:Afar Region]]\n[[Category:Amhara Region]]\n[[Category:Provinces of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in 1995]]\n[[Category:Tigray Region]]\n\n{{Tigray-geo-stub}}\n{{Afar-geo-stub}}\n{{Ethiopia-hist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "175.159.123.133", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wollo_Province"}
{"title_page": "Shan'ge, the \"Mountain Songs\"", "text_new": "\u1ea6{{italictitle}}\n'''''Shan'ge, the \"Mountain Songs\"''''' is a non-fiction book by {{ill|\u014cki Yasushi|ja|\u5927\u6728\u5eb7}}<!--\u014cki is the family name--> and Paolo Santangelo, published in 2011 by [[BRILL]], discussing [[shan'ge]]. It is a part of the \"Emotions and States of Mind in East Asia\" series.\n\n==Background==\n\u014cki is a professor of Chinese literature at the [[University of Tokyo]].<ref name=Refnews>{{cite journal |last= |first= |date=June 2011 |title=Shan'ge, the 'mountain songs'; love songs in Ming China. |work=[[Reference and Research Book News]] |publisher= |publication-place=|volume=26|issue=3 |page= |url= |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= }}</ref> He had researched Shan'ge for more than twenty years.<ref name=Hsup470>Hsu, p. 470.</ref> Santangelo is a professor of East Asian History at [[Sapienza University]].<ref name=Refnews/> The volume's series as a whole is aiming to illustrate life in the [[Ming Dynasty]] and [[Qing Dynasty]].<ref name=Hsup469>Hsu, p. 469.</ref>\n\n==Content==\nThe volume includes a translation from Chinese to English, done by \u014cki, of ''Shan'ge'', a collection of [[Feng Menglong]]'s songs.<ref name=Hsup469/> A total of 340 songs are included.<ref name=Hsup471>Hsu, p. 471.</ref> Both co-authors inserted their commentary.<ref name=Hsup469/> The final three chapters of ''Shan'ge'' are not included.<ref>Hsu, p. 470-471.</ref> Santangelo wrote the glossary, which takes up the remaining 50% of the book.<ref name=Hsup469/>\n\n41 illustrations are present to show particular objects appearing in songs.<ref name=Hsup471/>\n\nThe book is dedicated to Feng Menglong's songs.<ref name=Refnews/>\n\n==Reception==\nHsu concluded that the book is \"is a tremendous contribution to\" various area students and \"global anthropological history.\"<ref name=Hsup469/> Hsu stated that the prose was \"scholarly yet reader-friendly\" and that there was \"rigorous translation and analysis\" from both co-authors.<ref name=Hsup469/> Hsu stated that there were Simplified characters and some typographical errors in the initial printing of the book.<ref>Hsu, p. 472.</ref>\n\n==References==\n* {{cite journal |last=Hsu |first=Pi-Ching |year= 2010|title=Shan\u2019ge, the \u201cMountain Songs\u201d: Love Songs in Ming China (review)  |work=[[China Review International]] |publisher=[[University of Hawai'i Press]] |publication-place=|volume=17 |issue=4|page=469-473|page= |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/482705 |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |doi=10.1353/cri.2010.0105|jstor=23733339}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Lowry |first=Katherine |year= |title=Shan'ge, the Mountain Songs: Love Songs in Ming China |work=[[Chinese Literature, Essays, Articles, Reviews]] |publisher= |publication-place=|volume=34 |page=175-178 |url= |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= }}\n* {{cite journal |last=McLaren |first=Anne E. |date=July 2012 |title= Shan'ge, the mountain songs: love songs in Ming China|work=[[International Journal of Asian Studies]] |publisher= |publication-place= |volume=9|issue=2|page=240 |url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/international-journal-of-asian-studies/article/emotion-and-the-language-of-intimacy-in-ming-china-the-shange-of-feng-menglong/71AB36051A1077DDF9464A6AF8196A27 |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |doi=10.1017/S1479591412000046}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Zeitlin |first=Judith |year=2013 |title= Shan'ge, the 'mountain songs': love songs in Ming China|work=[[Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies]] |publisher= |publication-place= |volume=76|issue=1|page=165-166 |url= |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= }}\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* ''[https://brill.com/view/title/19163 Shan'ge, the \"Mountain Songs\"]'' - [[BRILL]]\n[[Category:Books about China]]\n[[Category:2011 books]]\n{{china-stub}}\n{{book-stub}}\n", "text_old": "\u1ea6{{italictitle}}\n'''''Shan'ge, the \"Mountain Songs\"''''' is a non-fiction book by {{ill|\u014cki Yasushi|ja|\u5927\u6728\u5eb7}}<!--\u014cki is the family name--> and Paolo Santangelo, published in 2011 by [[BRILL]], discussing [[shan'ge]]. It is a part of the \"Emotions and States of Mind in East Asia\" series.\n\n==Background==\n\u014cki is a professor of Chinese literature at the [[University of Tokyo]].<ref name=Refnews>{{cite journal |last= |first= |date=June 2011 |title=Shan'ge, the 'mountain songs'; love songs in Ming China. |work=[[Reference and Research Book News]] |publisher= |publication-place=|volume=26|issue=3 |page= |url= |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= }}</ref> He had researched Shan'ge for more than twenty years.<ref name=Hsup470>Hsu, p. 470.</ref> Santangelo is a professor of East Asian History at [[Sapienza University]].<ref name=Refnews/> The volume's series as a whole is aiming to illustrate life in the [[Ming Dynasty]] and [[Qing Dynasty]].<ref name=Hsup469>Hsu, p. 469.</ref>\n\n==Content==\nThe volume includes a translation from Chinese to English, done by \u014cki, of ''Shan'ge'', a collection of [[Feng Menglong]]'s songs.<ref name=Hsup469/> A total of 340 songs are included.<ref name=Hsup471>Hsu, p. 471.</ref> Both co-authors inserted their commentary.<ref name=Hsup469/> The final three chapters of ''Shan'ge'' are not included.<ref>Hsu, p. 470-471.</ref> Santangelo wrote the glossary, which takes up the remaining 50% of the book.<ref name=Hsup469/>\n\n41 illustrations are present to show particular objects appearing in songs.<ref name=Hsup471/>\n\nThe book is dedicated to Feng Menglong's songs.<ref name=Refnews/>\n\n==Reception==\nHsu concluded that the book is \"is a tremendous contribution to\" various area students and \"global anthropological history.\"<ref name=Hsup469/> Hsu stated that the prose was \"scholarly yet reader-friendly\" and that there was \"rigorous translation and analysis\" from both co-authors.<ref name=Hsup469/> Hsu stated that there were Simplified characters and some typographical errors in the initial printing of the book.<ref>Hsu, p. 472.</ref>\n\n==References==\n* {{cite journal |last=Hsu |first=Pi-Ching |year= 2010|title=Shan\u2019ge, the \u201cMountain Songs\u201d: Love Songs in Ming China (review)  |work=[[China Review International]] |publisher=[[University of Hawai'i Press]] |publication-place=|volume=17 |issue=4|page=469-473|page= |url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/482705 |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |doi=10.1353/cri.2010.0105|jstor=23733339}}\n* {{cite journal |last=McLaren |first=Anne E. |date=July 2012 |title= Shan'ge, the mountain songs: love songs in Ming China|work=[[International journal of Asian studies]] |publisher= |publication-place= |volume=9|issue=2|page=240 |url= |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= |doi=10.1017/S1479591412000046}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Zeitlin |first=Judith |year=2013 |title= Shan'ge, the 'mountain songs': love songs in Ming China|work=[[Bulletin of the School of Oriental and African Studies]] |publisher= |publication-place= |volume=76|issue=1|page=165-166 |url= |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Lowry |first=Katherine |year= |title=Shan'ge, the Mountain Songs: Love Songs in Ming China |work=[[Chinese Literature, Essays, Articles, Reviews]] |publisher= |publication-place=|volume=34 |page=175-178 |url= |accessdate= |isbn= |issn= |oclc= }}\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* ''[https://brill.com/view/title/19163 Shan'ge, the \"Mountain Songs\"]'' - [[BRILL]]\n[[Category:Books about China]]\n[[Category:2011 books]]\n{{china-stub}}\n{{book-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WhisperToMe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shan%27ge,_the_%22Mountain_Songs%22"}
{"title_page": "Sandi Toksvig", "text_new": "{{short description|Danish-British comedian, writer and activist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sandi Toksvig\n| honorific_suffix   = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100|OBE}}\n| image              = Sandi Toksvig - Secret Comedy Podcast - 2013 (9468814916) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Sandi Toksvig in 2013\n| birth_name         = Sandra Birgitte Toksvig\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1958|5|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| citizenship        = [[Denmark|Danish]] (1958\u2013present) <br /> [[United Kingdom|British]] (2013\u2013present)\n| alma_mater         = [[Girton College, Cambridge]]\n| residence          = [[Wandsworth, London]], England \n| parents            = [[Claus Toksvig]]<ref name=FreeBMDmarriages>{{cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=xxUQIHdkk0koDBTrSGpSig&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=5 August 2015|work=FreeBMD. Marriage registered Q2 1954 in Surrey, England|publisher=ONS}}</ref><br /> Julie Anne Toksvig (n\u00e9e Brett)\n| occupation         = Author, radio and television presenter, co-founder of [[Women's Equality Party]] and Comedian. \n| party              = [[Women's Equality Party]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Debbie Toksvig|2007}}\n| children           = 3\n}}\n'''Sandra Birgitte Toksvig''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t|\u0252|k|s|v|\u026a|\u0261}}, {{IPA-da|\u02c8s\u00e6nti \u02c8ts\u02b0\u028cks\u02ccvi\u02c0}}; born 3 May 1958)<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2007-12-01|title=Toksvig, Sandra Birgitte, (Sandi), (born 3 May 1958), writer and comedian|journal=Who's Who|language=en|publisher=Oxford University Press|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.37818}}</ref> is a [[Scandinavian_migration_to_Britain#Contemporary_migration|British-Danish]] writer, comedian, broadcaster, actor, and producer on British radio, stage, and television. She is also a political activist, having co-founded the [[Women's Equality Party]] in 2015. She has written plays, novels, and books for children. In 1994, she [[coming out|came out]] as a lesbian.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\">{{cite news |last1=Reporters |first1=Telegraph |title=Sandi Toksvig: 'Coming out was terrifying. We had death threats and had to go into hiding with the children for two weeks' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/life/sandi-toksvig-i-knew-from-the-earliest-time-that-i-was-gay/ |accessdate=17 January 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=1 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Toksvig took over from [[Stephen Fry]] as host of the BBC television quiz show ''[[QI]]'', having previously spent ten years hosting ''[[The News Quiz]]'' on [[BBC Radio 4]]. From 2017-2020 she was co-presenter of ''[[The Great British Bake Off]]'', alongside comedian [[Noel Fielding]]. In 2020, she stepped down and will be replaced by [[Matt Lucas]].<ref>{{cite news\n | last = Ross\n | first = Alice\n | title = Noel Fielding and Sandi Toksvig to host new Great British Bake Off\n | pages =\n | newspaper = The Guardian\n | location = London\n | date = 16 March 2017\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/mar/16/noel-fielding-and-sandi-toksvig-to-host-new-great-british-bake-off}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |title=The Great British Bake Off: Sandi Toksvig to leave after three years |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51133199 |accessdate=16 January 2020 |agency=BBC |date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nToksvig was installed as [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the [[University of Portsmouth]] in October 2012, and is the president of the [[Women of the Year Lunch]]. She was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[2014 New Year Honours]] for services to broadcasting.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=60728 |supp=y|page=14|date=31 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nToksvig was born in Denmark. Her father, [[Claus Toksvig]], was a Danish journalist, broadcaster, and foreign correspondent, so Toksvig spent most of her youth outside Denmark, mostly in New York City. Her mother, Julie Anne Toksvig (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' Brett), is British.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13127990.Sandi_Toksvig_minds_her_manners/|first=Rebecca|last=McQuillan|title=Sandi Toksvig minds her manners |work = The Herald Scotland |date=18 October 2013 |accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref> She has an older brother, Nick, who is a journalist, and a younger sister, Jenifer, a [[Libretto|librettist]], who was born when Sandi was 12. When Sandi was 24, she was appointed Jenifer's legal guardian.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Coleman |first1=Pamela |title=Relative values: Sandi Toksvig and her sister Jeni |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/relative-values-sandi-toksvig-and-her-sister-jeni-qm378b57hhp |accessdate=18 December 2019 |work=The Sunday Times |date=9 November 2003 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/how-we-met-1599365.html|title=HOW WE MET|date=1995-09-03|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref> In 1969, her father covered the [[Apollo 11|landing of the first man on the moon]] from mission control. Toksvig was holding the hand of [[Neil Armstrong|Neil Armstrong's]] secretary during the landing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-09-17/sandi-toksvig-qi-bake-off-mp-politics-gender-pay/|title=Sandi Toksvig: 'Standing as an MP? I'm not going to say no to anything'|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> She attended [[Tormead School]], an independent girls' school near [[Guildford]], when her father was based in London. Her first job, at the age of 18, was a position as a [[follow spot]] operator for the musical ''[[Jesus Christ Superstar]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|date=24 January 2013|title=The Chain Of Curiosity |url=https://books.google.com/?id=guobYpUxBj8C&pg=PT113&lpg=PT113&dq=sandi+toksvig+jesus+christ+superstar#v=onepage&q=sandi%20toksvig%20jesus%20christ%20superstar&f=false|location=London, UK|publisher=[[Hachette (publisher)|Hachette UK]]|isbn=9781405527231|accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3670221/Sandi-Toksvig-All-the-worlds-backstage.html|title=Sandi Toksvig: All the world's backstage|last1=Tokvsig |first1=Sandi |date=30 December 2007 |work= [[The Sunday Telegraph]] |accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nShe read law, archaeology and anthropology at [[Girton College, Cambridge]], graduating with a [[first-class degree]] and receiving two prizes for outstanding achievement (The Raemakers and the Theresa Montefiore Awards).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2012/jan/23/sandi-toksvig-chancellor-portsmouth-university|title=Sandi Toksvig becomes chancellor of Portsmouth University|last=Press Association|date=23 January 2012|work=The Guardian|accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref> One of her law supervisors was [[Lord Denning]].<ref name=\"comedy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/qi/episodes/9/8/|title=QI \u2013 Series I \u2013 Inequality \u2013 British Comedy Guide|publisher=comedy.co.uk|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{Quote box |quote=When I see comedian\u2014and \u2018comedienne\u2019, of course I hate it\u2014I think \u2018Oh, really?\u2019 because I think of myself as a writer and broadcaster. Sometimes it's funny but I\u2019ve just done a piece for [[BBC Radio 3|Radio 3]] all about [[Mary Wollstonecraft]], and there's not a joke in it. |source=''[[The Times]]''<ref name=dougary/>|width=25em |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |quoted=true |salign=center}}\n\n[[File:Toksvig 2008.jpg|thumb|right|Toksvig performing in 2008]]\n\n===Beginnings===\nToksvig began her comedy career at Girton, where she wrote and performed in the first all-woman show at the [[Footlights]]. She was there at the same time as fellow members [[Stephen Fry]], [[Hugh Laurie]], [[Tony Slattery]], and [[Emma Thompson]], and wrote additional material for the [[Perrier award]]-winning [[Cambridge Footlights Revue|Footlights Revue]]. She was also a member of the university's [[Cambridge University Light Entertainment Society|Light Entertainment Society]].\n\nShe started her television career on [[children's television|children's series]], presenting ''[[No. 73]]'' (1982\u20131986), the ''Sandwich Quiz'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vivienneclore.com/artist-details/sandi-toksvig/ |title=Artist Management |publisher=Vivienne Clore |date= |accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Saturday Starship]]'', ''[[Motormouth]]'', ''[[Gilbert the Alien|Gilbert's Fridge]]'', for [[Television South]], and  factual programmes such as ''Island Race'' and ''The Talking Show'', produced by [[Open Media]] for [[Channel 4]]. She also appeared as a guest presenter in 2000 on ''[[Time Team]]'' at a dig in York (season 7 episode 3).\n\n===Comedy===\nIn the comedy circuit, Toksvig performed at the first night of the [[The Comedy Store, London|Comedy Store]] in [[London]], and was once part of [[The Comedy Store Players|their Players]], an [[improvisational comedy]] team.<ref>[http://www.comedystoreplayers.com/history.html Comedy Store Players Official Site \u2013 History] -retrieved on 16 May 2008</ref>\n\nIn television, she appeared as a panellist in comedy shows such as ''[[Call My Bluff (UK game show)|Call My Bluff]]'' (a regular as a team captain), ''[[Whose Line Is It Anyway? (UK TV series)|Whose Line Is It Anyway?]]'', ''[[Mock the Week]]'', ''[[QI]]'', and ''[[Have I Got News for You]]'', where she appeared on the first episode in 1990.<ref>[http://www.tv.com/have-i-got-news-for-you/show/2627/episode_listings.html?season=1&tag=nav_bar;1 Have I Got News For You episode guide] at TV.com&nbsp;\u2014 retrieved on 16 May 2008</ref> She was also the host of ''[[What the Dickens]]'', a [[Sky Arts]] [[quiz show]].\n\nOn radio, she is a familiar voice for BBC Radio 4 listeners, having appeared on ''[[I'm Sorry I Haven't a Clue]]'', [[The Unbelievable Truth (radio show)|''The Unbelievable Truth'']], and as the chair of ''[[The News Quiz]]'', where she replaced [[Simon Hoggart]] in September 2006, but left in June 2015 in order to enter politics to champion women's rights. Her final show was first broadcast on 26 June. She presented Radio 4's travel programme ''Excess Baggage'' until it was axed in 2012.\n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wanderlust.co.uk/magazine/news/bbc-radio-4s-excess-baggage-decommissioned|first=|last=|title=Radio 4's Excess Baggage to be axed|work=Wanderlust|date=2012-03-20|accessdate=2016-01-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202101608/http://www.wanderlust.co.uk/magazine/news/bbc-radio-4s-excess-baggage-decommissioned|archivedate=2 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Drama and factual===\nIn 1993, Toksvig wrote a musical, ''Big Night Out at the Little Sands Picture Palace'', for [[Nottingham Playhouse]], co-starring with [[Anita Dobson]] and [[Una Stubbs]]. In 2002, it was re-written, with [[Dilly Keane]], for the [[Watford#Watford Palace Theatre|Watford Palace Theatre]], in which they appeared with [[Bonnie Langford]].<ref>[http://www.whatsonstage.com/index.php?pg=207&story=E8821025025538 Review of ''Big Night Out'' in What's On Stage] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616055325/http://www.whatsonstage.com/index.php?pg=207&story=E8821025025538 |date=16 June 2011 }}; retrieved 23 February 2009.</ref>\n\nToksvig and Elly Brewer wrote a Shakespeare deconstruction, ''The Pocket Dream'', which Toksvig performed at the [[Nottingham Playhouse]] and which transferred to the [[West End theatre|West End]] for a short run. The pair also wrote the 1992 TV series ''[[The Big One (TV series)|The Big One]]'', in which she also starred. She has appeared in a number of stage plays, including ''[[Androcles and the Lion (play)|Androcles and the Lion]]'', ''[[Much Ado About Nothing]]'', and ''[[The Comedy of Errors]]''.\n\nIn 1996, she narrated the ''Dragons!'' interactive CD-ROM published by Oxford University Press and developed by Inner Workings, along with [[Harry Enfield]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Television graphics around the world | url = http://www.meldrum.co.uk/mhp/testcard/around_world.html | website = meldrum.co.uk | date = 29 March 2000 | access-date = 26 April 2013 }}</ref> The software was primarily aimed at children and featured songs and poems about dragons. She also narrated the ''Winnie the Witch'' CD-ROM. She appeared in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' audio drama ''[[Red (Doctor Who audio)|Red]]'' by [[Big Finish Productions]], released in August 2006. In December 2006, she hosted and sang at the [[London Gay Men's Chorus]] sold-out Christmas show, ''Make the Yuletide Gay'', at the [[Barbican Arts Centre|Barbican Centre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barbican.org.uk/music/event-detail.asp?ID=4705|first=|last=|title=Music Event Detail|date=|accessdate=2016-01-26}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Over Christmas and New Year 2007/2008, she narrated the [[pantomime]] ''Cinderella'' at the [[Old Vic Theatre]]. In October 2011, she narrated the new musical ''[[Soho Cinders]]'' at the [[Queen's Theatre]], London. In 2011 she hosted a second season of [[BBC Two]]'s ''Antiques Master''.\n\nToksvig wrote a play entitled ''[[Bully Boy]]'' which focused on [[post-traumatic stress]] among British servicemen. The play premi\u00e8red at the [[University of Southampton#Highfield Campus|Nuffield Theatre]] in Southampton in May 2011, and starred [[Anthony Andrews]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sandi Toksvig on Bully Boy|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/brighton-theatre/news/05-2011/sandi-toksvig-on-bully-boy_8993.html|website=WhatsOnStage|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref> The play then launched the debut season of [[The Other Palace|St James Theatre]] in September 2012, the first new West End theatre to open in 30 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=St James Theatre in London's West End opens|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-19636447|accessdate=17 March 2017|work=BBC News|date=18 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2013 Christmas Special of BBC's ''[[Call the Midwife]]'', Toksvig made a cameo appearance as grumpy ward nurse Sister Gibbs.<ref>{{cite news | last = O'Donovan | first = Gerard |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/10531223/Call-the-Midwife-Christmas-special-review.html |title=''Call the Midwife'', Christmas special, review |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=25 December 2013 |accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Walker-Arnott | first = Ellie |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-12-04/call-the-midwife-christmas-special---first-look-preview |title=''Call the Midwife'' Christmas special \u2014 first look preview |work=[[Radio Times]] |date=14 December 2013 |accessdate=31 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn 28 April 2015, it was announced that Toksvig would leave BBC Radio 4's ''The News Quiz'' in June at the end of the 28th series, which was scheduled to begin on 15 May of that year. She said: \"I have decided it is time to move on and, of course, I feel sad but I think it's the right moment. The show is in great shape and, like a good house guest, you should always depart when people still wish you'd stay a bit longer.\" The BBC said Toksvig had made the \"difficult decision\" to leave in order \"to embark on a new and exciting stage of her career\".<ref name=\"BBC News 28 April 2015\">{{cite news |title= Sandi Toksvig steps down from Radio 4's ''News Quiz'' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-32495153 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 28 April 2015 |work=[[BBC News Online]] | publisher = BBC |accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref> On 30 April 2015, Toksvig announced that her decision to quit ''The News Quiz'' had been made in order to allow her to help set up a new political party named the [[Women's Equality Party]].<ref name=\"Topping\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/apr/30/sandi-toksvig-quit-radio-4-news-quiz-set-up-womens-rights-political-party |title=Sandi Toksvig reveals she quit Radio 4 to set up women's rights political party |last1=Topping |first1=Alexandra |date=30 April 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=30 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Furness\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/bbc/11574333/Sandi-Toksvig-quit-The-News-Quiz-for-Womens-Equality-Party.html|title=Sandi Toksvig quit ''The News Quiz'' for Women's Equality Party |first=Hannah |last=Furness |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=30 April 2015 |accessdate=3 May 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, Toksvig was a guest of [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]''. Her choices included [[Joe Nichols]] (\"[[What's a Guy Gotta Do]]\"), [[Gustav Winckler]], [[The Weather Girls]], [[Barbra Streisand]], and [[Bonnie Langford]]. Her book choice was ''[[The Ashley Book of Knots]]'', and her luxury item was an endless supply of the ''[[Daily Mail]]''.<ref name=island>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06qg1ls |title=BBC Radio 4 \u2013 Desert Island Discs, Sandi Toksvig |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=29 November 2015|accessdate=4 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nHer most recent play ''[[Silver Lining (play)|Silver Lining]]'' opened at the Rose Theatre Kingston on 11 February 2017, before touring to Portsmouth, Oxford, Cambridge, Ipswich, Keswick, York, and Salford. It centres around five elderly ladies and a young carer in a retirement home which is about to be flooded by a storm. It stars [[Rachel Davies]], [[Keziah Joseph]], Maggie McCarthy, [[Joanna Monro]], [[Sheila Reid]], and [[Amanda Walker]]. Toksvig's son, [[Theo Toksvig-Stewart]], made his professional stage debut in the play.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sandy Toksvig's Silver Lining|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/first-look-sandi-toksvig-silver-lining_42841.html|website=WhatsOnStage|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 June 2019, Toksvig appeared on former Prime Minister of Australia [[Julia Gillard]]'s podcast. Notably, Toksvig states \"Wikipedia is a marvelous idea and the idea is that it is a crowd sourced encyclopedia of knowledge, what a fantastic notion. But what's happening is that women are disappearing so 90% of Wikipedia's content is about ''men'' and their achievements and 9% is about ''women''. 1% are still making up their mind. So that proportion is completely out of kilter and we desperately need to do something about it. Part of the problem is that it is edited by volunteers but there are about 350,000 \"uber\" volunteers that tend, no offence to them, to be the same kind of guy who has the time to sit and do it and doesn't have laundry to do and are actively editing women out. There are two issues: 1) women's achievements are not being inputted and 2) women are actively being edited out... I am intent on trying to change this if we can.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://podcasts.apple.com/au/podcast/a-podcast-of-ones-own-with-julia-gillard/id1466658814|title=A Podcast of One's Own with Julia Gillard on Apple Podcasts|website=Apple Podcasts|language=en-au|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n\n===Writing===\nToksvig has written more than twenty fiction and non-fiction books for children and adults, starting in 1994 with ''Tales from the Norse's Mouth'', a fiction tale for children. In 1995, she sailed around the coast of Britain with [[John McCarthy (journalist)|John McCarthy]], who had been held hostage in [[Beirut]]. In 2003, she published ''Gladys Reunited: A Personal American Journey'', about her travels in the USA retracing her childhood. She writes regular columns for ''[[Good Housekeeping]]'', the ''[[Sunday Telegraph]]'' and ''[[The Lady (magazine)|The Lady]]''. In October 2008, she published ''Girls Are Best'', a [[women's history|history book for girls]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/sandi-toksvig-interview-the-history-woman-1-1148798|title=Sandi Toksvig interview: The history woman|work = The Scotsman|date=27 November 2008|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, her collected columns for ''The Sunday Telegraph'' were published in book form as ''The Chain of Curiosity''. In 2012, she published her book, ''Valentine Grey'', an historical novel set in the [[Boer War]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/fictionreviews/9558294/Valentine-Grey-by-Sandi-Toksvig-review.html|first=Lucy|last=Beresford|title=Valentine Grey by Sandi Toksvig: review |work = The Telegraph |date=27 September 2012 |accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref> Her 2015 young adult book, ''Hitler's Canary''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/feb/20/hitlers-canary-sandi-toksvig-review|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=www.amazon.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> is a Holocaust story told by a boy named Bamse and his family. The characters are based on Toksvig's own father and grandmother; the heroism of the story closely resembles the story's own experiences during the war.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kveller.com/great-british-baking-show-host-sandi-toksvigs-grandparents-were-holocaust-heroes/|title='Great British Baking Show' Host Sandi Toksvig's Grandparents Were Holocaust Heroes|date=2020-01-09|website=Kveller|language=en|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> Her memoir \"Between the Stops: The View of My Life from the Top of the Number 12 Bus\" was published on October 29, 2019.\n\n===Television presenter===\nIn 2012\u201313 Toksvig presented ''[[1001 Things You Should Know]]'' for [[Channel 4]] daytime. Toksvig began presenting the revival edition of the daytime game show ''[[Fifteen-to-One]]'' in April 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-04-02/fifteen-to-one-returns-behind-the-scenes-with-sandi-toksvig|title=Fifteen to One returnos: behind the scenes with Sandi Toksvig|first=Emma|last=Daly|work=Radio Times|date=2 April 2014|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> It is an hour long instead of the original half-hour edition presented by [[William G. Stewart]]. After two series had been broadcast, in June 2015, Channel 4 announced that a further three would be made, hosted by Toksvig.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsonnews.com/story/080615-620|title=Channel 4 Commits to Sandi Toksvig's Fifteen to One|website=News on News|date=8 June 2015|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nToksvig took over from [[Stephen Fry]] as host of ''[[QI]]'', making her \"the first female presenter of a British mainstream TV comedy panel show\", a fact she found extraordinary in 2016.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Julia Llewellyn |title=Sandi Toksvig: 'Women support each other in comedy, men worry about the size of their manhoods' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2016/10/09/sandi-toksvig-women-support-each-other-in-comedy-men-worry-about/ |accessdate=17 January 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=9 October 2016}}</ref> She hosted the first episode of the show's series \"N\", which was broadcast on 21 October 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2016/10/21/qi-sandi-toksvig-triumphs-in-her-first-appearance-as-host|title=QI Sandi Toksvig triumphs in her first appearance as host|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=21 October 2016|accessdate=21 October 2016|last1=Power|first1=Ed}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2017 she was announced as the new co-presenter of ''[[The Great British Bake Off]]'' on [[Channel 4]], alongside [[Noel Fielding]]. They replaced the previous hosts, [[Sue Perkins]] and [[Mel Giedroyc]]. In January 2020, she announced she was leaving the show to focus on other work commitments.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n==Politics and activism==\nToksvig first came to wider public prominence in 1994, when the charity [[Save the Children]] dropped her services as compere of its 75th anniversary celebrations after she [[Coming out|came out]],<ref name=dougary/> but following a direct action protest by the [[Lesbian Avengers]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/lesbians-protest-over-charity-ban-1440911.html|title=Lesbians protest over charity ban|work=The Independent|date=5 October 1994|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> the charity apologised.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/charity-apologises-to-comic-1444805.html |title=Charity apologises to comic |date=25 October 1994 |work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=David|first=Smith|title=Comedian and actress Sandi Toksvig, a well-known face on the popular comedy improvisation TV show, ''Whose Line is it Anyway'', came out as a lesbian in the pages of the Sunday Times and Daily Mirror|work=Gay Times|issue=194|publisher=Millivres|date=November 1994|issn=0950-6101}}</ref>\n\nToksvig supports the charity and pressure group [[Liberty (pressure group)|Liberty]], hosting its 2012 awards ceremony.<ref>{{cite web | title = Liberty honours inspirational human rights leaders | url = http://www.liberty-human-rights.org.uk/media/press/2012/liberty-honours-inspirational-human-rights-leaders-in-an.php | website = liberty-human-rights.org.uk | date = 20 November 2012 | access-date = 26 April 2013 }}</ref> She was appointed president of the [[Women of the Year Lunch]].<ref name=\"Women of the Year\">{{cite web | title= The President | url= http://www.womenoftheyear.co.uk/the-board-council/the-presidents-message/ | author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | website= Women of the Year | accessdate= 7 May 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150125075401/http://www.womenoftheyear.co.uk/the-board-council/the-presidents-message/ | archivedate= 25 January 2015 | df= dmy-all }}</ref> An atheist and [[secular humanism|humanist]], Toksvig is a patron of [[Humanists UK]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://humanism.org.uk/about/our-people/patrons/sandi-toksvig/ | title = Sandi Toksvig | website = humanism.org.uk | publisher = [[Humanists UK]] | accessdate = 13 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, as the scale of the [[Jimmy Savile sexual abuse scandal]] became apparent, and amid claims that during the 1960s, 1970s, and 1980s, there was a culture within the BBC which [[Criticism of the BBC#Jimmy Savile sexual abuse allegations|tolerated sexual harassment]], Toksvig stated that she was groped by a \"famous individual\" on air in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-19861688 |title=Sandi Toksvig claims she was groped while broadcasting |date=7 October 2012 |work=[[BBC News Online]] |accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/oct/07/sandi-toksvig-i-was-groped-on-air |title=Sandi Toksvig: 'I was groped on air in the 1980s' |date=7 October 2012 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=9 October 2012 }}</ref> Toksvig said the allegations of inappropriate behaviour at the BBC \"did not surprise me at all\". In September 2018, as the [[BBC gender pay gap controversy]] continued to unfold, Toksvig reported that she was only paid 40% of what Fry, her predecessor, had received. Toksvig had earlier told the ''[[Radio Times]]'' it would be \u201cabsurd\u201d if she did not receive the same salary as him  for chairing ''QI.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/sep/08/sandi-toksvig-reveals-60-qi-pay-gap-from-stephen-fry|title=Sandi Toksvig sparks new gender pay row over QI fee|last=Thorpe|first=Vanessa|last2=Graham-Harrison|first2=Emma|date=2018-09-08|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 she stood as a candidate in the election for the [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]]ship of the [[University of Oxford]], supporting a campaign against [[Top-up fees|student fees]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/education/2793657.stm | title= Toksvig enters chancellor race |work=[[BBC News]] | publisher = BBC | date=24 February 2003|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> She was defeated in the first round of voting, achieving 1,179 first-place votes out of about 8,000 cast.<ref name=\"urlPatten wins Oxford prize| higher news|EducationGuardian.co.uk\">{{cite news | last = Curtis | first = Polly | title = Patten wins Oxford prize | url = http://education.guardian.co.uk/higher/news/story/0,9830,915896,00.html?=rss | date = 17 March 2003 | work = [[The Guardian]] | accessdate = 24 May 2008| location = London, UK }}</ref> The election was won by [[Chris Patten]]. Almost a decade later she succeeded [[Sheila Hancock]] as Chancellor of the [[University of Portsmouth]].<ref>{{cite news | title = BBC News \u2013 Sandi Toksvig made Portsmouth University Chancellor | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-20141782 | work = [[BBC News]] | publisher = BBC | date = 31 October 2012 | access-date = 26 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\nToksvig's party-political sympathies have developed over the years. She was part of [[Red Wedge]]'s comedy tour in the 1980s, which supported the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Party. By [[2004 United Kingdom elections|the 2004 elections]], she was a high-profile celebrity supporter of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]].<ref name=\"liberalengland.blogspot.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://liberalengland.blogspot.co.uk/2013/02/time-for-sandi-toksvig-to-give-up-news.html | title = Liberal England: Time for Sandi Toksvig to give up The News Quiz | website = liberalengland.blogspot.co.uk | publisher = Liberal England (blog) | accessdate=13 April 2015| date = 2 February 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Screen stars join election race | work = [[BBC News]] | publisher = BBC | date = 25 May 2004 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3745121.stm | accessdate = 16 October 2008 | quote = The celebrity bug has bitten the other major parties with the Lib Dems claiming the support of [...] broadcaster Sandi Toksvig. }}</ref> She has received some criticism for joking about the Tories in 2011 (they've \"[[Cunt#Linguistic variants and derivatives|put the 'N' into cuts]]\" to [[child benefit]]),<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news | last = Blake | first = Heidi | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/8557822/BBC-in-decency-row-over-obscene-joke-by-Sandi-Toksvig.html | title = BBC in decency row over obscene joke by Sandi Toksvig | work = Daily Telegraph |accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref> but has said Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] is \"a good person\".<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> She has also joked about [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]] leader [[Nigel Farage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2015/05/sandi-toksvig-makes-hitler-jibe-about-nigel-farage/|title=Sandi Toksvig makes Hitler jibe about Nigel Farage - Coffee House|date=26 May 2015|work=The Spectator}}</ref> In 2012, she said in an interview that \"I don't think there's a party that represents anything I believe in\".<ref>{{cite news | last = Saner | first = Emine | title = Sandi Toksvig: 'I don't understand boredom' | work = The Guardian | date = 26 August 2012 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/aug/26/sandi-toksvig-interview | accessdate = 26 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Women's Equality Party===\nIn April 2015, Toksvig chaired the first, informal, conference of a new political party, the [[Women's Equality Party]],<ref>{{cite news | last = Cocozza | first = Paula | title = Women's Equality party founders: 'It needed doing. So we said, \"Let's do it\"' | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/aug/28/womens-equality-party-founders-it-needed-doing-so-we-said-lets-do-it-sandi-toksvig | work = [[The Guardian]] | publisher = [[Guardian Media Group]] | date = 28 August 2015 | accessdate = 21 September 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/londoners-diary-womens-party-is-ready-to-be-a-player-10189809.html | title = Londoner's Diary: Women's party is ready to be a player | work = [[London Evening Standard]] | date = 20 April 2015 | accessdate = 23 April 2015}}</ref> and then left her job as presenter of ''The News Quiz'' to formally co-found it.<ref name=Topping/><ref name=Furness/> She later explained that she had decided that it was \"not too late to fight the good fight, after all\".<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/may/25/sandi-toksvig-trolls-womens-equality-party-bbc-abuse | title = Sandi Toksvig: trolls are already out over plans to form Women's Equality party | work = [[The Guardian]] | first = Jessica | last = Elgot | publisher = [[Guardian Media Group]] | date = 25 May 2015 | accessdate = 27 May 2015 }}</ref> In September the same year she announced the dates for a comedy tour to raise funds for the party.<ref>{{cite news | last = Duffy | first = Nick | title = Sandi Toksvig launches comedy tour to raise funds for new political party | url = https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/09/29/sandi-toksvig-launches-comedy-tour-to-raise-funds-for-new-political-party/ | work = [[PinkNews]] | publisher = | date = 29 September 2015 | access-date = 29 September 2015 }}</ref><ref name=Times_290915>{{cite news | last = Nixey | first = Catherine | title = Sandi Toksvig on swapping The News Quiz for the Women's Equality Party | url = http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/article4570067.ece | work = [[The Times]] | publisher = [[News UK]] | url-access = subscription | date = 29 September 2015 | access-date = 29 September 2015 }}</ref> The party's full set of policies were launched at [[Conway Hall]], 20 October 2015.<ref name=Policy_launch>{{cite web | title = Women's Equality Party announces first policies and campaigns | url = http://www.womensequality.org.uk/policy_launch_announcement | publisher = [[Women's Equality Party]] | date = 20 October 2015 | accessdate = 21 October 2015 }}</ref><ref name=Guardian_211015a>{{cite news | last = Minter | first = Harriet | title = The Women's Equality Party launch is not a moment too soon | url = https://www.theguardian.com/women-in-leadership/2015/oct/21/the-womens-equality-party-launch-is-not-a-moment-too-soon | work = [[The Guardian]] | publisher = [[Guardian Media Group]] | date = 21 October 2015 | accessdate = 21 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAs an eleven-year-old, Toksvig was present with her father, a leading Danish foreign affairs journalist, at [[NASA]] [[Christopher C. Kraft Jr. Mission Control Center|Mission Control Center]] in Houston, Texas during the [[Apollo 11|first Moon landing]].<ref>QI XL. Series N;10. Nature/Nurture, BBC. UK Broadcast 30 Dec 2016</ref><ref>Kerr, Alison (29 November 2008). \"Sandi Toksvig interview: The history woman\". ''[[The Scotsman]]''. Retrieved 4 Jan 2017</ref> In an appearance on BBC 1 show ''[[The TV That Made Me]]'', she stated she held the hand of [[Neil Armstrong]]'s nervous secretary to calm the woman down during the final moments. She also said she had a lifetime fear of children's television puppet [[Basil Brush]], so she wrote a 2002 episode of ''[[The Basil Brush Show]]'' entitled \"Molly Christmas\".\n\n{{Quote box |quote=I wouldn\u2019t care if they came from Tesco. I don\u2019t care about the blood thing. They call me Mummy and I earned it. We love each other. You can\u2019t do better than that. Lots of families don\u2019t.|source=Toksvig commenting on her children<br>in ''[[The Times]]''<ref name=\"no secrets\">{{cite news | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article1169426.ece | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110604214412/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article1169426.ece | archivedate = 4 June 2011 | work = [[The Times]]|location=London | title = I have no secrets | date = 11 October 2002 | accessdate =16 March 2012 | first = Penny | last = Wark }}</ref>|width=25em |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |quoted=true |salign=center }}\n\nToksvig is the mother of two daughters (Megan and Jesse) and a son (Theo).<ref name=timeslife>{{cite news | url = http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/the_way_we_live/article3040129.ece | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110615194302/http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/the_way_we_live/article3040129.ece | archivedate = 15 June 2011 | work = [[The Times]] | title = A Life in the Day: Sandi Toksvig | last = Scott | first = Caroline | date=16 December 2007|location=London, UK|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/Sandi-Toksvig-interview-The-history.4737671.jp|title=Sandi Toksvig interview: The history woman|date=29 November 2008| work= [[The Scotsman]] |last=Kerr|first=Alison}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2016/feb/20/jesse-toksvig-stewart-my-two-mums-were-trailblazers|title=Jesse Toksvig-Stewart: My two mums were trailblazers|last=Moorhead|first=Joanna|date=2016-02-20|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref> The children were carried by her then-partner, Peta Stewart, from whom she separated in 1997,<ref name=\"no secrets\"/> and were conceived through [[artificial insemination]] by [[Sperm donor|donor]] Christopher Lloyd-Pack,<ref name=dougary>{{cite news |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/stage/comedy/article6942389.ece|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615084301/http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/stage/comedy/article6942389.ece|archivedate=15 June 2011|title=Sandi Toksvig on her Christmas cracker|work =[[The Times]]|author=Ginny Dougary|date=5 December 2009|location=London, UK|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> younger brother of the actor [[Roger Lloyd-Pack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=DgGjrBYSdR2j54Ol8PP2wg&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=1 December 2013|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Coveney |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jan/16/roger-lloyd-pack |title=Roger Lloyd Pack obituary &#124; Television & radio |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2014-01-16 |accessdate=2016-08-07}}</ref>\n\nIt was having three young children that made her decide to [[Coming out|come out]], because, to the best of her knowledge, there were no out lesbians in British public life, and she did not want her children to grow up ashamed of [[LGBT parenting|having two mothers]]. Toksvig was warned she might never work again, and the family faced [[death threat]]s and had to go into hiding.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\"/>\n\nShe lives on a [[houseboat]] in [[London Borough of Wandsworth|Wandsworth]]<ref name=\"Rucki\">{{cite news | last = Rucki | first = Alexandra | url = http://www.wandsworthguardian.co.uk/news/10904614.Eighteen_people_make_New_Year_s_Honours_list_in_Wandsworth/?ref=nt | title=Eighteen people make New Year's Honours list in Wandsworth | work = Wandsworth Guardian |date=31 December 2013 |accessdate=31 December 2013 | location = London, UK}}</ref> with psychotherapist Debbie Toksvig,<ref name=timeslife/> whom she joined in a [[civil partnership in the United Kingdom|civil partnership]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | url = http://www.itv.com/news/update/2014-03-29/sandi-toksvig-renews-wedding-vows-in-public-event | title = Sandi Toksvig renews wedding vows in public event | work = ITV news |publisher=ITV | date=29 March 2014 | accessdate=1 April 2014}}</ref> They renewed their vows on 29 March 2014, the day [[same-sex marriage in the United Kingdom|same-sex marriage]] was introduced in England and Wales,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/04/01/sandi-toksvig-gay-marriage-this-morning_n_5069139.html | title = Sandi Toksvig Praises New Gay Marriage Legislation On 'This Morning': 'It's About Love And Equality' | work = [[The Huffington Post|Huffington Post]] | date = 1 April 2014 | accessdate = 1 April 2014 }}</ref> and in December 2014, their [[civil partnership]] was converted into a marriage.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/sandi-toksvig-marries-partner-debbie-in-third-ceremony-tomorrow-i-will-love-her-even-more-9918231.html | title = Sandi Toksvig marries partner Debbie in third ceremony: 'Tomorrow, I will love her even more' | work = The Independent | date = 11 December 2014 | accessdate = 12 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nToksvig became a British citizen in 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/uk/article3843025.ece | title = Citizen Dane | first = Patrick |last=Kidd |work=The Times|date=15 August 2013|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> She describes her \"[[Received Pronunciation|posh]]\" accent as being the result of a deliberate attempt to copy the voice of [[Celia Johnson]] in ''[[Brief Encounter]]'', after being ostracised at boarding school for having an American accent.<ref name=island/>\n\nIn her late 50s, she lost a significant amount of weight on medical advice, and credits this with giving her the confidence to go back to television.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n*1997 \u2013 The [[Grand Order of Water Rats]] Show Business Personality of the Year\n*2007 \u2013 Political Humourist of the Year at the [[Channel 4]] Political Awards<ref>{{cite web | title = Behind the scenes at the Channel Four Political Awards | url = http://admin.channel4.com/blogs/page/newsroom?entry=behind_the_scenes_at_the | publisher = Channel 4 Newsroom Blog | access-date = 16 May 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://archive.is/20120527004938/http://admin.channel4.com/blogs/page/newsroom?entry=behind_the_scenes_at_the | archivedate = 27 May 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> and 2007 \u2013 Radio Broadcaster of the Year by the [[Broadcasting Press Guild]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.broadcastingpressguild.org/?page_id=101 | title = 2007 Broadcasting Press Guild Awards | publisher = Broadcasting Press Guild | access-date = 16 May 2008 }}</ref>\n*2007 \u2013 Read it or Else Award from Coventry Inspiration Book Awards for ''Hitler's Canary''\n*2008 \u2013 Broadcaster of the Year at the [[Stonewall Awards]]\n*2009 \u2013 [[Voice of the Listener & Viewer]] Award for Individual Contribution to Radio\n*2010 \u2013 Honorary [[Doctor of Letters]] [[University of Portsmouth]]\n*2012 \u2013 Honorary Doctor of Letters [[York St John University]]\n*2012 \u2013 Honorary Doctor of Letters [[University of Surrey]]\n*2012 \u2013 Honorary Fellowship [[Lucy Cavendish College, Cambridge]]\n*2013 \u2013 Voice of the Listener & Viewer Award for Excellence in Broadcasting (Roberts Radio Special Award)\n*2014 \u2013 [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) for services to Broadcasting \n*2016 \u2013 Honorary Doctor of Letters [[University of Westminster]]\n*2016 \u2013 Honorary Fellowship [[Newnham College, Cambridge]]\n*2017 \u2013 CoScan (Confederation of Scandinavian Societies) International Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.coscan.org.uk/international-award/|title=CoScan \u2013 Confederation of Scandinavian Societies|last=|first=|date=|website=www.coscan.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-04-18}}</ref>\n*2018 \u2013 Honorary Doctor of Letters [[University of Leicester]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.le.ac.uk/offices/press/for-journalists/graduation-ceremonies-1/summer-2018/honorands/sandi-toksvig-obe|title=Sandi Toksvig OBE \u2014 University of Leicester|last=pt91|website=www2.le.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-07-17}}</ref>\n*2019 - Honorary Fellowship [[Girton College, Cambridge|Girton College Cambridge]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.girton.cam.ac.uk/news/uks-first-college-for-women-honours-five-pioneering-alumnae/|title=UK's First College for Women Honours Five Pioneering Alumnae - Girton College|website=www.girton.cam.ac.uk|access-date=2019-05-11}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Books for children===\n* {{cite book|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|title=The End of the Sky|date=2017|publisher=Doubleday Childrens|location=London|isbn=978-0-857-53192-6}}\n* {{cite book|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|title=A Slice of the Moon|date=2015|publisher=Doubleday Childrens|location=London|isbn=978-0-857-53191-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|title=Girls Are Best|date=2009|publisher=Red Fox|location=London|isbn=978-1-86230-429-1|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/girlsarebest0000toks}}\n* {{cite book|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|title=The Littlest Viking|date=2008|publisher=Yearling|location=London|isbn=978-0-440-86830-9}}\n* {{cite book|title=Hitlers Canary |last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Valerius uitgeverij |location=[[Vlaardingen]], Holland |date=2006 |isbn=90-78250-02-X}} (Dutch translation)\n* {{cite book|title=Hitler's Canary|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Doubleday|year=2005|isbn=0-385-60889-6}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Troublesome Tooth Fairy|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Transworld|year=2000|isbn=0-552-54663-1}}\n* {{cite book|title=Super-Saver Mouse to the Rescue|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Transworld|year=2000|isbn=0-552-54541-4}}\n* {{cite book|title=Super-Saver Mouse|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Transworld|year=1999|isbn=0-552-54540-6}}\n* {{cite book|title=If I Didn't Have Elbows|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Deagosti|year=1998|isbn=1-84089-048-7}}\n* {{cite book|title=Unusual Day|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Transworld/Corgi|year=1997|isbn=0-552-54539-2}}\n* {{cite book|title=Tales from the Norse's Mouth|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=BBC Books|year=1994|isbn=0-563-40358-6}}\n\n===Books for adults===\n* Toksvig, Sandi (2019) ''Between the Stops: The view of My Life from the Top of the number 12 Bus'', Virago, London, {{ISBN|978-0-349-00637-6}}.\n* Toksvig, Sandi (2012) ''Valentine Grey''. Virago. {{ISBN|9781844088317}}\n* {{cite book|title=Heroines & Harridans \u2013 A Fanfare of Fabulous Females|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi, (illustrated by Sandy Nightingale)|publisher=The Robson Press|year=2012|isbn=978-1849-54-3385}}\n* {{cite book|title=Melted into Air|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Little, Brown|year=2006|isbn=0-316-86117-0}}\n* {{cite book|title=Gladys Reunited: A Personal American Journey|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Little, Brown|year=2003|isbn=0-7515-3328-9}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Travels of Lady Bulldog Burton|last1=Toksvig|first1=Sandi|last2=Nightingale|first2=Sandy |publisher=Little, Brown|year=2002|isbn=0-316-86007-7|lastauthoramp=yes}}\n* {{cite book|title=Flying Under Bridges|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Little, Brown|year=2001|isbn=0-316-85635-5}}\n* {{cite book|title=Whistling for the Elephants|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Transworld|year=1999|isbn=0-593-04480-0}}\n* {{cite book|title=Island Race: an Improbable Voyage Round the Coast of Britain|first1=John|last1=McCarthy|authorlink=John McCarthy (journalist)|first2=Sandi|last2=Toksvig|publisher=BBC Books|year=1995|isbn=0-563-37053-X|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/islandraceimprob0000mcca}}\n* {{cite book|title=Great Journeys of the World|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=BBC Books|year=1994|isbn=0-563-37050-5|display-authors=et. al.|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/greatjourneysof000sand}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website}}\n*{{IMDb name}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-new|party}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Women's Equality Party|Co-founder of the Women's Equality Party]]|years=2015|with=[[Catherine Mayer]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sophie Walker]]<br /><small>as leader</small>}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William G. Stewart]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Host of ''[[Fifteen to One]]''|years=2014 \u2013 present}}\n{{s-aft|after=Incumbent}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephen Fry]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Host of ''[[QI]]''|years=2016 \u2013 present}}\n{{s-aft|after=Incumbent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{subject bar|portal1 = Biography |portal2 = LGBT | portal3 = Politics | portal6 = Comedy | portal7 = Theatre | portal8 = Television | portal9 = Radio | portal10 = BBC | portal11 = United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Toksvig, Sandi}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Girton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British humanists]]\n[[Category:British atheists]]\n[[Category:British radio personalities]]\n[[Category:British television presenters]]\n[[Category:British women comedians]]\n[[Category:British women in politics]]\n[[Category:Danish comedians]]\n[[Category:Danish women comedians]]\n[[Category:Danish emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:Danish humanists]]\n[[Category:Danish atheists]]\n[[Category:I'm Sorry I Haven't a Clue]]\n[[Category:LGBT producers]]\n[[Category:Lesbian actresses]]\n[[Category:Lesbian entertainers]]\n[[Category:Lesbian writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT broadcasters from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT comedians]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Denmark]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from Denmark]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Tormead School]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Political party founders]]\n[[Category:Danish people of British descent]]\n[[Category:Women's Equality Party people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from London]]\n[[Category:QI]]\n[[Category:University of Portsmouth]]\n[[Category:Women television presenters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Danish-British comedian, writer and activist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sandi Toksvig\n| honorific_suffix   = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100|OBE}}\n| image              = Sandi Toksvig - Secret Comedy Podcast - 2013 (9468814916) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Sandi Toksvig in 2013\n| birth_name         = Sandra Birgitte Toksvig\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1958|5|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| citizenship        = [[Denmark|Danish]] (1958\u2013present) <br /> [[United Kingdom|British]] (2013\u2013present)\n| alma_mater         = [[Girton College, Cambridge]]\n| residence          = [[Wandsworth, London]], England \n| parents            = [[Claus Toksvig]]<ref name=FreeBMDmarriages>{{cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=xxUQIHdkk0koDBTrSGpSig&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=5 August 2015|work=FreeBMD. Marriage registered Q2 1954 in Surrey, England|publisher=ONS}}</ref><br /> Julie Anne Toksvig (n\u00e9e Brett)\n| occupation         = Author, radio and television presenter, co-founder of [[Women's Equality Party]] and Comedian. \n| party              = [[Women's Equality Party]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Debbie Toksvig|2007}}\n| children           = 3\n}}\n'''Sandra Birgitte Toksvig''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|t|\u0252|k|s|v|\u026a|\u0261}}, {{IPA-da|\u02c8s\u00e6nti \u02c8ts\u02b0\u028cks\u02ccvi\u02c0}}; born 3 May 1958)<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2007-12-01|title=Toksvig, Sandra Birgitte, (Sandi), (born 3 May 1958), writer and comedian|journal=Who's Who|language=en|publisher=Oxford University Press|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.37818}}</ref> is a [[Scandinavian_migration_to_Britain#Contemporary_migration|British-Danish]] writer, comedian, broadcaster, actor, and producer on British radio, stage, and television. She is also a political activist, having co-founded the [[Women's Equality Party]] in 2015. She has written plays, novels, and books for children. In 1994, she [[coming out|came out]] as a lesbian.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\">{{cite news |last1=Reporters |first1=Telegraph |title=Sandi Toksvig: 'Coming out was terrifying. We had death threats and had to go into hiding with the children for two weeks' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/life/sandi-toksvig-i-knew-from-the-earliest-time-that-i-was-gay/ |accessdate=17 January 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=1 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Toksvig took over from [[Stephen Fry]] as host of the BBC television quiz show ''[[QI]]'', having previously spent ten years hosting ''[[The News Quiz]]'' on [[BBC Radio 4]]. From 2017-2020 she was co-presenter of ''[[The Great British Bake Off]]'', alongside comedian [[Noel Fielding]]. In 2020, she stepped down and will be replaced by [[Matt Lucas]].<ref>{{cite news\n | last = Ross\n | first = Alice\n | title = Noel Fielding and Sandi Toksvig to host new Great British Bake Off\n | pages =\n | newspaper = The Guardian\n | location = London\n | date = 16 March 2017\n | url = https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2017/mar/16/noel-fielding-and-sandi-toksvig-to-host-new-great-british-bake-off}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |title=The Great British Bake Off: Sandi Toksvig to leave after three years |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-51133199 |accessdate=16 January 2020 |agency=BBC |date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nToksvig was installed as [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the [[University of Portsmouth]] in October 2012, and is the president of the [[Women of the Year Lunch]]. She was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[2014 New Year Honours]] for services to broadcasting.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=60728 |supp=y|page=14|date=31 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nToksvig was born in Denmark. Her father, [[Claus Toksvig]], was a Danish journalist, broadcaster, and foreign correspondent, so Toksvig spent most of her youth outside Denmark, mostly in New York City. Her mother, Julie Anne Toksvig (''[[n\u00e9e]]'' Brett), is British.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13127990.Sandi_Toksvig_minds_her_manners/|first=Rebecca|last=McQuillan|title=Sandi Toksvig minds her manners |work = The Herald Scotland |date=18 October 2013 |accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref> She has an older brother, Nick, who is a journalist, and a younger sister, Jenifer, a [[Libretto|librettist]], who was born when Sandi was 12. When Sandi was 24, she was appointed Jenifer's legal guardian.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Coleman |first1=Pamela |title=Relative values: Sandi Toksvig and her sister Jeni |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/relative-values-sandi-toksvig-and-her-sister-jeni-qm378b57hhp |accessdate=18 December 2019 |work=The Sunday Times |date=9 November 2003 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/how-we-met-1599365.html|title=HOW WE MET|date=1995-09-03|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-02-03}}</ref> In 1969, her father covered the [[Apollo 11|landing of the first man on the moon]] from mission control. Toksvig was holding the hand of [[Neil Armstrong|Neil Armstrong's]] secretary during the landing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2018-09-17/sandi-toksvig-qi-bake-off-mp-politics-gender-pay/|title=Sandi Toksvig: 'Standing as an MP? I'm not going to say no to anything'|website=Radio Times|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> She attended [[Tormead School]], an independent girls' school near [[Guildford]], when her father was based in London. Her first job, at the age of 18, was a position as a [[follow spot]] operator for the musical ''[[Jesus Christ Superstar]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|date=24 January 2013|title=The Chain Of Curiosity |url=https://books.google.com/?id=guobYpUxBj8C&pg=PT113&lpg=PT113&dq=sandi+toksvig+jesus+christ+superstar#v=onepage&q=sandi%20toksvig%20jesus%20christ%20superstar&f=false|location=London, UK|publisher=[[Hachette (publisher)|Hachette UK]]|isbn=9781405527231|accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/3670221/Sandi-Toksvig-All-the-worlds-backstage.html|title=Sandi Toksvig: All the world's backstage|last1=Tokvsig |first1=Sandi |date=30 December 2007 |work= [[The Sunday Telegraph]] |accessdate=25 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nShe read law, archaeology and anthropology at [[Girton College, Cambridge]], graduating with a [[first-class degree]] and receiving two prizes for outstanding achievement (The Raemakers and the Theresa Montefiore Awards).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2012/jan/23/sandi-toksvig-chancellor-portsmouth-university|title=Sandi Toksvig becomes chancellor of Portsmouth University|last=Press Association|date=23 January 2012|work=The Guardian|accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref> One of her law supervisors was [[Lord Denning]].<ref name=\"comedy\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/qi/episodes/9/8/|title=QI \u2013 Series I \u2013 Inequality \u2013 British Comedy Guide|publisher=comedy.co.uk|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{Quote box |quote=When I see comedian\u2014and \u2018comedienne\u2019, of course I hate it\u2014I think \u2018Oh, really?\u2019 because I think of myself as a writer and broadcaster. Sometimes it's funny but I\u2019ve just done a piece for [[BBC Radio 3|Radio 3]] all about [[Mary Wollstonecraft]], and there's not a joke in it. |source=''[[The Times]]''<ref name=dougary/>|width=25em |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |quoted=true |salign=center}}\n\n[[File:Toksvig 2008.jpg|thumb|right|Toksvig performing in 2008]]\n\n===Beginnings===\nToksvig began her comedy career at Girton, where she wrote and performed in the first all-woman show at the [[Footlights]]. She was there at the same time as fellow members [[Stephen Fry]], [[Hugh Laurie]], [[Tony Slattery]], and [[Emma Thompson]], and wrote additional material for the [[Perrier award]]-winning [[Cambridge Footlights Revue|Footlights Revue]]. She was also a member of the university's [[Cambridge University Light Entertainment Society|Light Entertainment Society]].\n\nShe started her television career on [[children's television|children's series]], presenting ''[[No. 73]]'' (1982\u20131986), the ''Sandwich Quiz'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vivienneclore.com/artist-details/sandi-toksvig/ |title=Artist Management |publisher=Vivienne Clore |date= |accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Saturday Starship]]'', ''[[Motormouth]]'', ''[[Gilbert the Alien|Gilbert's Fridge]]'', for [[Television South]], and  factual programmes such as ''Island Race'' and ''The Talking Show'', produced by [[Open Media]] for [[Channel 4]]. She also appeared as a guest presenter in 2000 on ''[[Time Team]]'' at a dig in York (season 7 episode 3).\n\n===Comedy===\nIn the comedy circuit, Toksvig performed at the first night of the [[The Comedy Store, London|Comedy Store]] in [[London]], and was once part of [[The Comedy Store Players|their Players]], an [[improvisational comedy]] team.<ref>[http://www.comedystoreplayers.com/history.html Comedy Store Players Official Site \u2013 History] -retrieved on 16 May 2008</ref>\n\nIn television, she appeared as a panellist in comedy shows such as ''[[Call My Bluff (UK game show)|Call My Bluff]]'' (a regular as a team captain), ''[[Whose Line Is It Anyway? (UK TV series)|Whose Line Is It Anyway?]]'', ''[[Mock the Week]]'', ''[[QI]]'', and ''[[Have I Got News for You]]'', where she appeared on the first episode in 1990.<ref>[http://www.tv.com/have-i-got-news-for-you/show/2627/episode_listings.html?season=1&tag=nav_bar;1 Have I Got News For You episode guide] at TV.com&nbsp;\u2014 retrieved on 16 May 2008</ref> She was also the host of ''[[What the Dickens]]'', a [[Sky Arts]] [[quiz show]].\n\nOn radio, she is a familiar voice for BBC Radio 4 listeners, having appeared on ''[[I'm Sorry I Haven't a Clue]]'', [[The Unbelievable Truth (radio show)|''The Unbelievable Truth'']], and as the chair of ''[[The News Quiz]]'', where she replaced [[Simon Hoggart]] in September 2006, but left in June 2015 in order to enter politics to champion women's rights. Her final show was first broadcast on 26 June. She presented Radio 4's travel programme ''Excess Baggage'' until it was axed in 2012.\n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wanderlust.co.uk/magazine/news/bbc-radio-4s-excess-baggage-decommissioned|first=|last=|title=Radio 4's Excess Baggage to be axed|work=Wanderlust|date=2012-03-20|accessdate=2016-01-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202101608/http://www.wanderlust.co.uk/magazine/news/bbc-radio-4s-excess-baggage-decommissioned|archivedate=2 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Drama and factual===\nIn 1993, Toksvig wrote a musical, ''Big Night Out at the Little Sands Picture Palace'', for [[Nottingham Playhouse]], co-starring with [[Anita Dobson]] and [[Una Stubbs]]. In 2002, it was re-written, with [[Dilly Keane]], for the [[Watford#Watford Palace Theatre|Watford Palace Theatre]], in which they appeared with [[Bonnie Langford]].<ref>[http://www.whatsonstage.com/index.php?pg=207&story=E8821025025538 Review of ''Big Night Out'' in What's On Stage] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616055325/http://www.whatsonstage.com/index.php?pg=207&story=E8821025025538 |date=16 June 2011 }}; retrieved 23 February 2009.</ref>\n\nToksvig and Elly Brewer wrote a Shakespeare deconstruction, ''The Pocket Dream'', which Toksvig performed at the [[Nottingham Playhouse]] and which transferred to the [[West End theatre|West End]] for a short run. The pair also wrote the 1992 TV series ''[[The Big One (TV series)|The Big One]]'', in which she also starred. She has appeared in a number of stage plays, including ''[[Androcles and the Lion (play)|Androcles and the Lion]]'', ''[[Much Ado About Nothing]]'', and ''[[The Comedy of Errors]]''.\n\nIn 1996, she narrated the ''Dragons!'' interactive CD-ROM published by Oxford University Press and developed by Inner Workings, along with [[Harry Enfield]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Television graphics around the world | url = http://www.meldrum.co.uk/mhp/testcard/around_world.html | website = meldrum.co.uk | date = 29 March 2000 | access-date = 26 April 2013 }}</ref> The software was primarily aimed at children and featured songs and poems about dragons. She also narrated the ''Winnie the Witch'' CD-ROM. She appeared in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' audio drama ''[[Red (Doctor Who audio)|Red]]'' by [[Big Finish Productions]], released in August 2006. In December 2006, she hosted and sang at the [[London Gay Men's Chorus]] sold-out Christmas show, ''Make the Yuletide Gay'', at the [[Barbican Arts Centre|Barbican Centre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barbican.org.uk/music/event-detail.asp?ID=4705|first=|last=|title=Music Event Detail|date=|accessdate=2016-01-26}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Over Christmas and New Year 2007/2008, she narrated the [[pantomime]] ''Cinderella'' at the [[Old Vic Theatre]]. In October 2011, she narrated the new musical ''[[Soho Cinders]]'' at the [[Queen's Theatre]], London. In 2011 she hosted a second season of [[BBC Two]]'s ''Antiques Master''.\n\nToksvig wrote a play entitled ''[[Bully Boy]]'' which focused on [[post-traumatic stress]] among British servicemen. The play premi\u00e8red at the [[University of Southampton#Highfield Campus|Nuffield Theatre]] in Southampton in May 2011, and starred [[Anthony Andrews]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Sandi Toksvig on Bully Boy|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/brighton-theatre/news/05-2011/sandi-toksvig-on-bully-boy_8993.html|website=WhatsOnStage|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref> The play then launched the debut season of [[The Other Palace|St James Theatre]] in September 2012, the first new West End theatre to open in 30 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=St James Theatre in London's West End opens|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-19636447|accessdate=17 March 2017|work=BBC News|date=18 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2013 Christmas Special of BBC's ''[[Call the Midwife]]'', Toksvig made a cameo appearance as grumpy ward nurse Sister Gibbs.<ref>{{cite news | last = O'Donovan | first = Gerard |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/10531223/Call-the-Midwife-Christmas-special-review.html |title=''Call the Midwife'', Christmas special, review |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=25 December 2013 |accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Walker-Arnott | first = Ellie |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-12-04/call-the-midwife-christmas-special---first-look-preview |title=''Call the Midwife'' Christmas special \u2014 first look preview |work=[[Radio Times]] |date=14 December 2013 |accessdate=31 December 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn 28 April 2015, it was announced that Toksvig would leave BBC Radio 4's ''The News Quiz'' in June at the end of the 28th series, which was scheduled to begin on 15 May of that year. She said: \"I have decided it is time to move on and, of course, I feel sad but I think it's the right moment. The show is in great shape and, like a good house guest, you should always depart when people still wish you'd stay a bit longer.\" The BBC said Toksvig had made the \"difficult decision\" to leave in order \"to embark on a new and exciting stage of her career\".<ref name=\"BBC News 28 April 2015\">{{cite news |title= Sandi Toksvig steps down from Radio 4's ''News Quiz'' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-32495153 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 28 April 2015 |work=[[BBC News Online]] | publisher = BBC |accessdate=12 May 2015}}</ref> On 30 April 2015, Toksvig announced that her decision to quit ''The News Quiz'' had been made in order to allow her to help set up a new political party named the [[Women's Equality Party]].<ref name=\"Topping\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/apr/30/sandi-toksvig-quit-radio-4-news-quiz-set-up-womens-rights-political-party |title=Sandi Toksvig reveals she quit Radio 4 to set up women's rights political party |last1=Topping |first1=Alexandra |date=30 April 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=30 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Furness\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/bbc/11574333/Sandi-Toksvig-quit-The-News-Quiz-for-Womens-Equality-Party.html|title=Sandi Toksvig quit ''The News Quiz'' for Women's Equality Party |first=Hannah |last=Furness |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=30 April 2015 |accessdate=3 May 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, Toksvig was a guest of [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]''. Her choices included [[Joe Nichols]] (\"[[What's a Guy Gotta Do]]\"), [[Gustav Winckler]], [[The Weather Girls]], [[Barbra Streisand]], and [[Bonnie Langford]]. Her book choice was ''[[The Ashley Book of Knots]]'', and her luxury item was an endless supply of the ''[[Daily Mail]]''.<ref name=island>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06qg1ls |title=BBC Radio 4 \u2013 Desert Island Discs, Sandi Toksvig |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=29 November 2015|accessdate=4 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nHer most recent play ''[[Silver Lining (play)|Silver Lining]]'' opened at the Rose Theatre Kingston on 11 February 2017, before touring to Portsmouth, Oxford, Cambridge, Ipswich, Keswick, York, and Salford. It centres around five elderly ladies and a young carer in a retirement home which is about to be flooded by a storm. It stars [[Rachel Davies]], [[Keziah Joseph]], Maggie McCarthy, [[Joanna Monro]], [[Sheila Reid]], and [[Amanda Walker]]. Toksvig's son, [[Theo Toksvig-Stewart]], made his professional stage debut in the play.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sandy Toksvig's Silver Lining|url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/first-look-sandi-toksvig-silver-lining_42841.html|website=WhatsOnStage|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 June 2019, Toksvig appeared on former Prime Minister of Australia [[Julia Gillard]]'s podcast. Notably, Toksvig states \"Wikipedia is a marvelous idea and the idea is that it is a crowd sourced encyclopedia of knowledge, what a fantastic notion. But what's happening is that women are disappearing so 90% of Wikipedia's content is about ''men'' and their achievements and 9% is about ''women''. 1% are still making up their mind. So that proportion is completely out of kilter and we desperately need to do something about it. Part of the problem is that it is edited by volunteers but there are about 350,000 \"uber\" volunteers that tend, no offence to them, to be the same kind of guy who has the time to sit and do it and doesn't have laundry to do and are actively editing women out. There are two issues: 1) women's achievements are not being inputted and 2) women are actively being edited out... I am intent on trying to change this if we can.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://podcasts.apple.com/au/podcast/a-podcast-of-ones-own-with-julia-gillard/id1466658814|title=A Podcast of One's Own with Julia Gillard on Apple Podcasts|website=Apple Podcasts|language=en-au|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n\n===Writing===\nShe has written more than twenty fiction and non-fiction books for children and adults, starting in 1994 with ''Tales from the Norse's Mouth'', a fiction tale for children. In 1995, she sailed around the coast of Britain with [[John McCarthy (journalist)|John McCarthy]], who had been held hostage in [[Beirut]]. In 2003, she published ''Gladys Reunited: A Personal American Journey'', about her travels in the USA retracing her childhood. She writes regular columns for ''[[Good Housekeeping]]'', the ''[[Sunday Telegraph]]'' and ''[[The Lady (magazine)|The Lady]]''. In October 2008, she published ''Girls Are Best'', a [[women's history|history book for girls]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/sandi-toksvig-interview-the-history-woman-1-1148798|title=Sandi Toksvig interview: The history woman|work = The Scotsman|date=27 November 2008|accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, her collected columns for ''The Sunday Telegraph'' were published in book form as ''The Chain of Curiosity''. In 2012, she published her book, ''Valentine Grey'', an historical novel set in the [[Boer War]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/fictionreviews/9558294/Valentine-Grey-by-Sandi-Toksvig-review.html|first=Lucy|last=Beresford|title=Valentine Grey by Sandi Toksvig: review |work = The Telegraph |date=27 September 2012 |accessdate=26 January 2016}}</ref> Her 2015 young adult book, ''Hitler's Canary''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/feb/20/hitlers-canary-sandi-toksvig-review|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=www.amazon.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> is a Holocaust story told by a boy named Bamse and his family. The characters are based on Toksvig's own father and grandmother; the heroism of the story closely resembles the story's own experiences during the war.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kveller.com/great-british-baking-show-host-sandi-toksvigs-grandparents-were-holocaust-heroes/|title='Great British Baking Show' Host Sandi Toksvig's Grandparents Were Holocaust Heroes|date=2020-01-09|website=Kveller|language=en|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref> Her memoir \"Between the Stops: The View of My Life from the Top of the Number 12 Bus\" was published on October 29, 2019.\n\n===Television presenter===\nIn 2012\u201313 Toksvig presented ''[[1001 Things You Should Know]]'' for [[Channel 4]] daytime. Toksvig began presenting the revival edition of the daytime game show ''[[Fifteen-to-One]]'' in April 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-04-02/fifteen-to-one-returns-behind-the-scenes-with-sandi-toksvig|title=Fifteen to One returnos: behind the scenes with Sandi Toksvig|first=Emma|last=Daly|work=Radio Times|date=2 April 2014|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> It is an hour long instead of the original half-hour edition presented by [[William G. Stewart]]. After two series had been broadcast, in June 2015, Channel 4 announced that a further three would be made, hosted by Toksvig.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsonnews.com/story/080615-620|title=Channel 4 Commits to Sandi Toksvig's Fifteen to One|website=News on News|date=8 June 2015|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nToksvig took over from [[Stephen Fry]] as host of ''[[QI]]'', making her \"the first female presenter of a British mainstream TV comedy panel show\", a fact she found extraordinary in 2016.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Julia Llewellyn |title=Sandi Toksvig: 'Women support each other in comedy, men worry about the size of their manhoods' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2016/10/09/sandi-toksvig-women-support-each-other-in-comedy-men-worry-about/ |accessdate=17 January 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=9 October 2016}}</ref> She hosted the first episode of the show's series \"N\", which was broadcast on 21 October 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/tv/2016/10/21/qi-sandi-toksvig-triumphs-in-her-first-appearance-as-host|title=QI Sandi Toksvig triumphs in her first appearance as host|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=21 October 2016|accessdate=21 October 2016|last1=Power|first1=Ed}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March 2017 she was announced as the new co-presenter of ''[[The Great British Bake Off]]'' on [[Channel 4]], alongside [[Noel Fielding]]. They replaced the previous hosts, [[Sue Perkins]] and [[Mel Giedroyc]]. In January 2020, she announced she was leaving the show to focus on other work commitments.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\n==Politics and activism==\nToksvig first came to wider public prominence in 1994, when the charity [[Save the Children]] dropped her services as compere of its 75th anniversary celebrations after she [[Coming out|came out]],<ref name=dougary/> but following a direct action protest by the [[Lesbian Avengers]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/lesbians-protest-over-charity-ban-1440911.html|title=Lesbians protest over charity ban|work=The Independent|date=5 October 1994|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> the charity apologised.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/charity-apologises-to-comic-1444805.html |title=Charity apologises to comic |date=25 October 1994 |work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=David|first=Smith|title=Comedian and actress Sandi Toksvig, a well-known face on the popular comedy improvisation TV show, ''Whose Line is it Anyway'', came out as a lesbian in the pages of the Sunday Times and Daily Mirror|work=Gay Times|issue=194|publisher=Millivres|date=November 1994|issn=0950-6101}}</ref>\n\nToksvig supports the charity and pressure group [[Liberty (pressure group)|Liberty]], hosting its 2012 awards ceremony.<ref>{{cite web | title = Liberty honours inspirational human rights leaders | url = http://www.liberty-human-rights.org.uk/media/press/2012/liberty-honours-inspirational-human-rights-leaders-in-an.php | website = liberty-human-rights.org.uk | date = 20 November 2012 | access-date = 26 April 2013 }}</ref> She was appointed president of the [[Women of the Year Lunch]].<ref name=\"Women of the Year\">{{cite web | title= The President | url= http://www.womenoftheyear.co.uk/the-board-council/the-presidents-message/ | author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | website= Women of the Year | accessdate= 7 May 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150125075401/http://www.womenoftheyear.co.uk/the-board-council/the-presidents-message/ | archivedate= 25 January 2015 | df= dmy-all }}</ref> An atheist and [[secular humanism|humanist]], Toksvig is a patron of [[Humanists UK]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://humanism.org.uk/about/our-people/patrons/sandi-toksvig/ | title = Sandi Toksvig | website = humanism.org.uk | publisher = [[Humanists UK]] | accessdate = 13 December 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn October 2012, as the scale of the [[Jimmy Savile sexual abuse scandal]] became apparent, and amid claims that during the 1960s, 1970s, and 1980s, there was a culture within the BBC which [[Criticism of the BBC#Jimmy Savile sexual abuse allegations|tolerated sexual harassment]], Toksvig stated that she was groped by a \"famous individual\" on air in the 1980s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-19861688 |title=Sandi Toksvig claims she was groped while broadcasting |date=7 October 2012 |work=[[BBC News Online]] |accessdate=9 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/oct/07/sandi-toksvig-i-was-groped-on-air |title=Sandi Toksvig: 'I was groped on air in the 1980s' |date=7 October 2012 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=9 October 2012 }}</ref> Toksvig said the allegations of inappropriate behaviour at the BBC \"did not surprise me at all\". In September 2018, as the [[BBC gender pay gap controversy]] continued to unfold, Toksvig reported that she was only paid 40% of what Fry, her predecessor, had received. Toksvig had earlier told the ''[[Radio Times]]'' it would be \u201cabsurd\u201d if she did not receive the same salary as him  for chairing ''QI.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/sep/08/sandi-toksvig-reveals-60-qi-pay-gap-from-stephen-fry|title=Sandi Toksvig sparks new gender pay row over QI fee|last=Thorpe|first=Vanessa|last2=Graham-Harrison|first2=Emma|date=2018-09-08|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-09-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003 she stood as a candidate in the election for the [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]]ship of the [[University of Oxford]], supporting a campaign against [[Top-up fees|student fees]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/education/2793657.stm | title= Toksvig enters chancellor race |work=[[BBC News]] | publisher = BBC | date=24 February 2003|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> She was defeated in the first round of voting, achieving 1,179 first-place votes out of about 8,000 cast.<ref name=\"urlPatten wins Oxford prize| higher news|EducationGuardian.co.uk\">{{cite news | last = Curtis | first = Polly | title = Patten wins Oxford prize | url = http://education.guardian.co.uk/higher/news/story/0,9830,915896,00.html?=rss | date = 17 March 2003 | work = [[The Guardian]] | accessdate = 24 May 2008| location = London, UK }}</ref> The election was won by [[Chris Patten]]. Almost a decade later she succeeded [[Sheila Hancock]] as Chancellor of the [[University of Portsmouth]].<ref>{{cite news | title = BBC News \u2013 Sandi Toksvig made Portsmouth University Chancellor | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-hampshire-20141782 | work = [[BBC News]] | publisher = BBC | date = 31 October 2012 | access-date = 26 April 2013 }}</ref>\n\nToksvig's party-political sympathies have developed over the years. She was part of [[Red Wedge]]'s comedy tour in the 1980s, which supported the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] Party. By [[2004 United Kingdom elections|the 2004 elections]], she was a high-profile celebrity supporter of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]].<ref name=\"liberalengland.blogspot.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://liberalengland.blogspot.co.uk/2013/02/time-for-sandi-toksvig-to-give-up-news.html | title = Liberal England: Time for Sandi Toksvig to give up The News Quiz | website = liberalengland.blogspot.co.uk | publisher = Liberal England (blog) | accessdate=13 April 2015| date = 2 February 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Screen stars join election race | work = [[BBC News]] | publisher = BBC | date = 25 May 2004 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3745121.stm | accessdate = 16 October 2008 | quote = The celebrity bug has bitten the other major parties with the Lib Dems claiming the support of [...] broadcaster Sandi Toksvig. }}</ref> She has received some criticism for joking about the Tories in 2011 (they've \"[[Cunt#Linguistic variants and derivatives|put the 'N' into cuts]]\" to [[child benefit]]),<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite news | last = Blake | first = Heidi | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/bbc/8557822/BBC-in-decency-row-over-obscene-joke-by-Sandi-Toksvig.html | title = BBC in decency row over obscene joke by Sandi Toksvig | work = Daily Telegraph |accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref> but has said Prime Minister [[Theresa May]] is \"a good person\".<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> She has also joked about [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]] leader [[Nigel Farage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2015/05/sandi-toksvig-makes-hitler-jibe-about-nigel-farage/|title=Sandi Toksvig makes Hitler jibe about Nigel Farage - Coffee House|date=26 May 2015|work=The Spectator}}</ref> In 2012, she said in an interview that \"I don't think there's a party that represents anything I believe in\".<ref>{{cite news | last = Saner | first = Emine | title = Sandi Toksvig: 'I don't understand boredom' | work = The Guardian | date = 26 August 2012 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/aug/26/sandi-toksvig-interview | accessdate = 26 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\n===Women's Equality Party===\nIn April 2015, Toksvig chaired the first, informal, conference of a new political party, the [[Women's Equality Party]],<ref>{{cite news | last = Cocozza | first = Paula | title = Women's Equality party founders: 'It needed doing. So we said, \"Let's do it\"' | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/aug/28/womens-equality-party-founders-it-needed-doing-so-we-said-lets-do-it-sandi-toksvig | work = [[The Guardian]] | publisher = [[Guardian Media Group]] | date = 28 August 2015 | accessdate = 21 September 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/londoners-diary-womens-party-is-ready-to-be-a-player-10189809.html | title = Londoner's Diary: Women's party is ready to be a player | work = [[London Evening Standard]] | date = 20 April 2015 | accessdate = 23 April 2015}}</ref> and then left her job as presenter of ''The News Quiz'' to formally co-found it.<ref name=Topping/><ref name=Furness/> She later explained that she had decided that it was \"not too late to fight the good fight, after all\".<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/may/25/sandi-toksvig-trolls-womens-equality-party-bbc-abuse | title = Sandi Toksvig: trolls are already out over plans to form Women's Equality party | work = [[The Guardian]] | first = Jessica | last = Elgot | publisher = [[Guardian Media Group]] | date = 25 May 2015 | accessdate = 27 May 2015 }}</ref> In September the same year she announced the dates for a comedy tour to raise funds for the party.<ref>{{cite news | last = Duffy | first = Nick | title = Sandi Toksvig launches comedy tour to raise funds for new political party | url = https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/09/29/sandi-toksvig-launches-comedy-tour-to-raise-funds-for-new-political-party/ | work = [[PinkNews]] | publisher = | date = 29 September 2015 | access-date = 29 September 2015 }}</ref><ref name=Times_290915>{{cite news | last = Nixey | first = Catherine | title = Sandi Toksvig on swapping The News Quiz for the Women's Equality Party | url = http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/article4570067.ece | work = [[The Times]] | publisher = [[News UK]] | url-access = subscription | date = 29 September 2015 | access-date = 29 September 2015 }}</ref> The party's full set of policies were launched at [[Conway Hall]], 20 October 2015.<ref name=Policy_launch>{{cite web | title = Women's Equality Party announces first policies and campaigns | url = http://www.womensequality.org.uk/policy_launch_announcement | publisher = [[Women's Equality Party]] | date = 20 October 2015 | accessdate = 21 October 2015 }}</ref><ref name=Guardian_211015a>{{cite news | last = Minter | first = Harriet | title = The Women's Equality Party launch is not a moment too soon | url = https://www.theguardian.com/women-in-leadership/2015/oct/21/the-womens-equality-party-launch-is-not-a-moment-too-soon | work = [[The Guardian]] | publisher = [[Guardian Media Group]] | date = 21 October 2015 | accessdate = 21 October 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAs an eleven-year-old, Toksvig was present with her father, a leading Danish foreign affairs journalist, at [[NASA]] [[Christopher C. Kraft Jr. Mission Control Center|Mission Control Center]] in Houston, Texas during the [[Apollo 11|first Moon landing]].<ref>QI XL. Series N;10. Nature/Nurture, BBC. UK Broadcast 30 Dec 2016</ref><ref>Kerr, Alison (29 November 2008). \"Sandi Toksvig interview: The history woman\". ''[[The Scotsman]]''. Retrieved 4 Jan 2017</ref> In an appearance on BBC 1 show ''[[The TV That Made Me]]'', she stated she held the hand of [[Neil Armstrong]]'s nervous secretary to calm the woman down during the final moments. She also said she had a lifetime fear of children's television puppet [[Basil Brush]], so she wrote a 2002 episode of ''[[The Basil Brush Show]]'' entitled \"Molly Christmas\".\n\n{{Quote box |quote=I wouldn\u2019t care if they came from Tesco. I don\u2019t care about the blood thing. They call me Mummy and I earned it. We love each other. You can\u2019t do better than that. Lots of families don\u2019t.|source=Toksvig commenting on her children<br>in ''[[The Times]]''<ref name=\"no secrets\">{{cite news | url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article1169426.ece | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110604214412/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article1169426.ece | archivedate = 4 June 2011 | work = [[The Times]]|location=London | title = I have no secrets | date = 11 October 2002 | accessdate =16 March 2012 | first = Penny | last = Wark }}</ref>|width=25em |bgcolor=#FFFFF0 |quoted=true |salign=center }}\n\nToksvig is the mother of two daughters (Megan and Jesse) and a son (Theo).<ref name=timeslife>{{cite news | url = http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/the_way_we_live/article3040129.ece | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110615194302/http://women.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/women/the_way_we_live/article3040129.ece | archivedate = 15 June 2011 | work = [[The Times]] | title = A Life in the Day: Sandi Toksvig | last = Scott | first = Caroline | date=16 December 2007|location=London, UK|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://thescotsman.scotsman.com/features/Sandi-Toksvig-interview-The-history.4737671.jp|title=Sandi Toksvig interview: The history woman|date=29 November 2008| work= [[The Scotsman]] |last=Kerr|first=Alison}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2016/feb/20/jesse-toksvig-stewart-my-two-mums-were-trailblazers|title=Jesse Toksvig-Stewart: My two mums were trailblazers|last=Moorhead|first=Joanna|date=2016-02-20|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref> The children were carried by her then-partner, Peta Stewart, from whom she separated in 1997,<ref name=\"no secrets\"/> and were conceived through [[artificial insemination]] by [[Sperm donor|donor]] Christopher Lloyd-Pack,<ref name=dougary>{{cite news |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/stage/comedy/article6942389.ece|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615084301/http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/stage/comedy/article6942389.ece|archivedate=15 June 2011|title=Sandi Toksvig on her Christmas cracker|work =[[The Times]]|author=Ginny Dougary|date=5 December 2009|location=London, UK|accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> younger brother of the actor [[Roger Lloyd-Pack]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=DgGjrBYSdR2j54Ol8PP2wg&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=1 December 2013|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Michael Coveney |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jan/16/roger-lloyd-pack |title=Roger Lloyd Pack obituary &#124; Television & radio |newspaper=The Guardian |date=2014-01-16 |accessdate=2016-08-07}}</ref>\n\nIt was having three young children that made her decide to [[Coming out|come out]], because, to the best of her knowledge, there were no out lesbians in British public life, and she did not want her children to grow up ashamed of [[LGBT parenting|having two mothers]]. Toksvig was warned she might never work again, and the family faced [[death threat]]s and had to go into hiding.<ref name=\"The Telegraph\"/>\n\nShe lives on a [[houseboat]] in [[London Borough of Wandsworth|Wandsworth]]<ref name=\"Rucki\">{{cite news | last = Rucki | first = Alexandra | url = http://www.wandsworthguardian.co.uk/news/10904614.Eighteen_people_make_New_Year_s_Honours_list_in_Wandsworth/?ref=nt | title=Eighteen people make New Year's Honours list in Wandsworth | work = Wandsworth Guardian |date=31 December 2013 |accessdate=31 December 2013 | location = London, UK}}</ref> with psychotherapist Debbie Toksvig,<ref name=timeslife/> whom she joined in a [[civil partnership in the United Kingdom|civil partnership]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | url = http://www.itv.com/news/update/2014-03-29/sandi-toksvig-renews-wedding-vows-in-public-event | title = Sandi Toksvig renews wedding vows in public event | work = ITV news |publisher=ITV | date=29 March 2014 | accessdate=1 April 2014}}</ref> They renewed their vows on 29 March 2014, the day [[same-sex marriage in the United Kingdom|same-sex marriage]] was introduced in England and Wales,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/04/01/sandi-toksvig-gay-marriage-this-morning_n_5069139.html | title = Sandi Toksvig Praises New Gay Marriage Legislation On 'This Morning': 'It's About Love And Equality' | work = [[The Huffington Post|Huffington Post]] | date = 1 April 2014 | accessdate = 1 April 2014 }}</ref> and in December 2014, their [[civil partnership]] was converted into a marriage.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/sandi-toksvig-marries-partner-debbie-in-third-ceremony-tomorrow-i-will-love-her-even-more-9918231.html | title = Sandi Toksvig marries partner Debbie in third ceremony: 'Tomorrow, I will love her even more' | work = The Independent | date = 11 December 2014 | accessdate = 12 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nToksvig became a British citizen in 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/uk/article3843025.ece | title = Citizen Dane | first = Patrick |last=Kidd |work=The Times|date=15 August 2013|accessdate=5 August 2015}}</ref> She describes her \"[[Received Pronunciation|posh]]\" accent as being the result of a deliberate attempt to copy the voice of [[Celia Johnson]] in ''[[Brief Encounter]]'', after being ostracised at boarding school for having an American accent.<ref name=island/>\n\nIn her late 50s, she lost a significant amount of weight on medical advice, and credits this with giving her the confidence to go back to television.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\n*1997 \u2013 The [[Grand Order of Water Rats]] Show Business Personality of the Year\n*2007 \u2013 Political Humourist of the Year at the [[Channel 4]] Political Awards<ref>{{cite web | title = Behind the scenes at the Channel Four Political Awards | url = http://admin.channel4.com/blogs/page/newsroom?entry=behind_the_scenes_at_the | publisher = Channel 4 Newsroom Blog | access-date = 16 May 2008 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://archive.is/20120527004938/http://admin.channel4.com/blogs/page/newsroom?entry=behind_the_scenes_at_the | archivedate = 27 May 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> and 2007 \u2013 Radio Broadcaster of the Year by the [[Broadcasting Press Guild]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.broadcastingpressguild.org/?page_id=101 | title = 2007 Broadcasting Press Guild Awards | publisher = Broadcasting Press Guild | access-date = 16 May 2008 }}</ref>\n*2007 \u2013 Read it or Else Award from Coventry Inspiration Book Awards for ''Hitler's Canary''\n*2008 \u2013 Broadcaster of the Year at the [[Stonewall Awards]]\n*2009 \u2013 [[Voice of the Listener & Viewer]] Award for Individual Contribution to Radio\n*2010 \u2013 Honorary [[Doctor of Letters]] [[University of Portsmouth]]\n*2012 \u2013 Honorary Doctor of Letters [[York St John University]]\n*2012 \u2013 Honorary Doctor of Letters [[University of Surrey]]\n*2012 \u2013 Honorary Fellowship [[Lucy Cavendish College, Cambridge]]\n*2013 \u2013 Voice of the Listener & Viewer Award for Excellence in Broadcasting (Roberts Radio Special Award)\n*2014 \u2013 [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) for services to Broadcasting \n*2016 \u2013 Honorary Doctor of Letters [[University of Westminster]]\n*2016 \u2013 Honorary Fellowship [[Newnham College, Cambridge]]\n*2017 \u2013 CoScan (Confederation of Scandinavian Societies) International Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.coscan.org.uk/international-award/|title=CoScan \u2013 Confederation of Scandinavian Societies|last=|first=|date=|website=www.coscan.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-04-18}}</ref>\n*2018 \u2013 Honorary Doctor of Letters [[University of Leicester]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.le.ac.uk/offices/press/for-journalists/graduation-ceremonies-1/summer-2018/honorands/sandi-toksvig-obe|title=Sandi Toksvig OBE \u2014 University of Leicester|last=pt91|website=www2.le.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2018-07-17}}</ref>\n*2019 - Honorary Fellowship [[Girton College, Cambridge|Girton College Cambridge]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.girton.cam.ac.uk/news/uks-first-college-for-women-honours-five-pioneering-alumnae/|title=UK's First College for Women Honours Five Pioneering Alumnae - Girton College|website=www.girton.cam.ac.uk|access-date=2019-05-11}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Books for children===\n* {{cite book|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|title=The End of the Sky|date=2017|publisher=Doubleday Childrens|location=London|isbn=978-0-857-53192-6}}\n* {{cite book|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|title=A Slice of the Moon|date=2015|publisher=Doubleday Childrens|location=London|isbn=978-0-857-53191-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|title=Girls Are Best|date=2009|publisher=Red Fox|location=London|isbn=978-1-86230-429-1|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/girlsarebest0000toks}}\n* {{cite book|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|title=The Littlest Viking|date=2008|publisher=Yearling|location=London|isbn=978-0-440-86830-9}}\n* {{cite book|title=Hitlers Canary |last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Valerius uitgeverij |location=[[Vlaardingen]], Holland |date=2006 |isbn=90-78250-02-X}} (Dutch translation)\n* {{cite book|title=Hitler's Canary|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Doubleday|year=2005|isbn=0-385-60889-6}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Troublesome Tooth Fairy|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Transworld|year=2000|isbn=0-552-54663-1}}\n* {{cite book|title=Super-Saver Mouse to the Rescue|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Transworld|year=2000|isbn=0-552-54541-4}}\n* {{cite book|title=Super-Saver Mouse|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Transworld|year=1999|isbn=0-552-54540-6}}\n* {{cite book|title=If I Didn't Have Elbows|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Deagosti|year=1998|isbn=1-84089-048-7}}\n* {{cite book|title=Unusual Day|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Transworld/Corgi|year=1997|isbn=0-552-54539-2}}\n* {{cite book|title=Tales from the Norse's Mouth|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=BBC Books|year=1994|isbn=0-563-40358-6}}\n\n===Books for adults===\n* Toksvig, Sandi (2019) ''Between the Stops: The view of My Life from the Top of the number 12 Bus'', Virago, London, {{ISBN|978-0-349-00637-6}}.\n* Toksvig, Sandi (2012) ''Valentine Grey''. Virago. {{ISBN|9781844088317}}\n* {{cite book|title=Heroines & Harridans \u2013 A Fanfare of Fabulous Females|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi, (illustrated by Sandy Nightingale)|publisher=The Robson Press|year=2012|isbn=978-1849-54-3385}}\n* {{cite book|title=Melted into Air|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Little, Brown|year=2006|isbn=0-316-86117-0}}\n* {{cite book|title=Gladys Reunited: A Personal American Journey|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Little, Brown|year=2003|isbn=0-7515-3328-9}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Travels of Lady Bulldog Burton|last1=Toksvig|first1=Sandi|last2=Nightingale|first2=Sandy |publisher=Little, Brown|year=2002|isbn=0-316-86007-7|lastauthoramp=yes}}\n* {{cite book|title=Flying Under Bridges|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Little, Brown|year=2001|isbn=0-316-85635-5}}\n* {{cite book|title=Whistling for the Elephants|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=Transworld|year=1999|isbn=0-593-04480-0}}\n* {{cite book|title=Island Race: an Improbable Voyage Round the Coast of Britain|first1=John|last1=McCarthy|authorlink=John McCarthy (journalist)|first2=Sandi|last2=Toksvig|publisher=BBC Books|year=1995|isbn=0-563-37053-X|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/islandraceimprob0000mcca}}\n* {{cite book|title=Great Journeys of the World|last=Toksvig|first=Sandi|publisher=BBC Books|year=1994|isbn=0-563-37050-5|display-authors=et. al.|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/greatjourneysof000sand}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website}}\n*{{IMDb name}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-new|party}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Women's Equality Party|Co-founder of the Women's Equality Party]]|years=2015|with=[[Catherine Mayer]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sophie Walker]]<br /><small>as leader</small>}}\n{{s-media}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[William G. Stewart]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Host of ''[[Fifteen to One]]''|years=2014 \u2013 present}}\n{{s-aft|after=Incumbent}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephen Fry]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Host of ''[[QI]]''|years=2016 \u2013 present}}\n{{s-aft|after=Incumbent}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{subject bar|portal1 = Biography |portal2 = LGBT | portal3 = Politics | portal6 = Comedy | portal7 = Theatre | portal8 = Television | portal9 = Radio | portal10 = BBC | portal11 = United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Toksvig, Sandi}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Girton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British humanists]]\n[[Category:British atheists]]\n[[Category:British radio personalities]]\n[[Category:British television presenters]]\n[[Category:British women comedians]]\n[[Category:British women in politics]]\n[[Category:Danish comedians]]\n[[Category:Danish women comedians]]\n[[Category:Danish emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:Danish humanists]]\n[[Category:Danish atheists]]\n[[Category:I'm Sorry I Haven't a Clue]]\n[[Category:LGBT producers]]\n[[Category:Lesbian actresses]]\n[[Category:Lesbian entertainers]]\n[[Category:Lesbian writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT broadcasters from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT comedians]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Denmark]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from England]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from Denmark]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Naturalised citizens of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Tormead School]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Political party founders]]\n[[Category:Danish people of British descent]]\n[[Category:Women's Equality Party people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from London]]\n[[Category:QI]]\n[[Category:University of Portsmouth]]\n[[Category:Women television presenters]]\n", "name_user": "Drmargi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWriting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sandi_Toksvig"}
{"title_page": "Body Double", "text_new": "{{about|the film|the novel by Tess Gerritsen|Body Double (novel)|the job in visual-media production|Body double}}\n{{short description|1984 film directed by Brian De Palma}}\n{{Infobox film\n|name           = Body Double\n|image          = DePalma body double.jpg\n|caption        = Theatrical release poster\n|director       = [[Brian De Palma]]\n|screenplay     = Brian De Palma<br />[[Robert J. Avrech]]\n|story          = Brian De Palma\n|producer       = Brian De Palma\n|starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Craig Wasson]]\n* [[Gregg Henry]]\n* [[Melanie Griffith]]\n}}\n|music          = [[Pino Donaggio]]\n|cinematography = [[Stephen H. Burum]]\n|editing        = [[Gerald B. Greenberg]]<br />[[Bill Pankow]]\n|released       = {{Film date|1984|10|26}}\n|runtime        = 114 minutes\n|studio         = Delphi II Productions\n|distributor    = [[Columbia Pictures]]\n|country        = United States\n|language       = English\n|budget         = $10 million or $6 million<ref>Hollywood Lays an Egg\nJacobson, Harlan. Film Comment; New York Vol. 18, Iss. 3,  (May/Jun 1982): 49-52. </ref>\n|gross          = $8.8 million \n}}\n\n'''''Body Double''''' is a 1984 American [[neo-noir]] [[erotic thriller]] film co-written and directed by [[Brian De Palma]] and starring [[Craig Wasson]], [[Gregg Henry]], [[Melanie Griffith]], and [[Deborah Shelton]]. The original musical score was composed by [[Pino Donaggio]].\n\nThe film was a direct homage to the films of [[Alfred Hitchcock]], specifically ''[[Rear Window]]'' (1954), ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]'' (1958), and ''[[Dial M for Murder]]'' (1954) taking plot lines and themes (such as [[voyeurism]] and obsession) from the first two films.<ref>{{cite book|last=Williams |first=Linda |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=6pL0AUb5BHUC&pg=PA86&lpg=PA86#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Erotic Thriller in Contemporary Cinema|page=86|year=2005|publisher=[[Indiana University Press]]|location=Bloomington}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Ann |last=Cvetkovich |chapter-url=http://english.illinoisstate.edu/strickland/rsvtxt/cvetko.htm |chapter=Postmodern Vertigo: The Sexual Politics of Allusion in De Palma's Body Double |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130211060858/http://english.illinoisstate.edu/strickland/rsvtxt/cvetko.htm |archivedate=February 11, 2013 |url-status=dead |editor-last1=Raubicheck |editor-first1=Walter |editor-first2=Walter |editor-last2=Srebnick |title=Hitchcock's Rereleased Films: From Rope to Vertigo |location=Detroit |publisher=[[Wayne State University Press]] |year=1991}}</ref>\n\nThe film received a lukewarm result at the box office and mixed reviews, but has subsequently become a [[cult film]]. When [[Twilight Time (DVD label)|Twilight Time]] released the film on Blu-ray in the United States in 2013, it quickly sold out.<ref>https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/61564/body-double-blu-ray/</ref><ref>http://www.hometheaterforum.com/community/threads/body-double-blu-ray-review.325785/</ref><ref>http://www.rupertpupkinspeaks.com/2013/08/twilight-timey-body-double-on-blu-ray.html</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nJake Scully ([[Craig Wasson]]) is a struggling actor who has lost his role as a [[vampire]] in a low-budget [[horror film]] after his [[claustrophobia]] thwarts shooting. After returning home to discover his girlfriend ([[Barbara Crampton]]) cheating on him, he splits and is left without a place to stay (the residence belongs to her). At a [[method acting]] class, he meets Sam Bouchard ([[Gregg Henry]]) who closely monitors Scully's revelation of his fears and the childhood cause of his claustrophobia. They go to a bar where Scully is offered a place to stay; Sam's rich friend has gone on a trip to Europe and needs a house-sitter for his ultra-modern home in the [[Hollywood Hills]].\n\nDuring the tour of the house with Scully, Sam is especially enthusiastic about showing Scully one feature: a [[telescope]], and through it a female neighbor, Gloria Revelle ([[Deborah Shelton]]), who erotically dances at a specific time each night. Scully voyeuristically watches Gloria each night until he sees her being abused by a man she appears to know. The next day he follows her when she goes shopping. Gloria makes calls to an unknown person promising to meet them. Scully also notices a disfigured \"Indian\", a man he had noticed was watching Gloria a few days prior. Scully follows her to a seaside [[motel]] where apparently Gloria has been stood up by the person she was there to meet. On the beach the Indian suddenly snatches her purse. Scully pursues him into a nearby tunnel but is overcome by his claustrophobia. Gloria walks him out of it. They impulsively and passionately kiss before she retreats. That night Scully is again watching through the telescope when the Indian returns and breaks into Gloria's home. Scully races to save her but is attacked by Gloria's vicious dog. Gloria is brutally murdered by the Indian with a huge handheld [[drill]].\n\n[[File:John Lautner's Chemosphere (8189866290).jpg|thumb|left|[[Chemosphere]], the ultramodern house used in ''Body Double'']]\nScully alerts the police, who determine it was a botched robbery. However, Detective McLean ([[Guy Boyd (actor)|Guy Boyd]]) becomes suspicious after finding a pair of Gloria's panties in Scully's pocket. Although McLean does not arrest him, he tells Scully that his voyeuristic behavior, as well as not alerting the police sooner, helped cause Gloria's murder. Unable to sleep, Scully watches a pornography TV channel. He observes that the actress, Holly Body ([[Melanie Griffith]]), dances in exactly the same sensual manner that Gloria did. To meet Holly, he pretends to be a porn producer hiring for a new film.\n\nScully learns from Holly that Sam hired her to impersonate Gloria each night, dancing in the window, knowing Scully would be watching and later witness the real Gloria's murder. Offended at the suggestion she was involved in a killing, Holly storms out of the house. She is picked up by the Indian who knocks her unconscious and drives her away. Scully follows them to an aqueduct where the Indian is digging a grave. During their fight, Scully discovers the Indian is Sam in heavy make-up. Scully was a scapegoat providing Sam, who was Gloria's abusive husband, with an alibi during the murder. Scully is overpowered and thrown into the grave and is incapacitated by his claustrophobia. However, he overcomes his fear and climbs out as Sam is knocked into the aqueduct and drowned.\n\nDuring the ending credits, Scully is shown having been recast in his previous vampire role as Holly watches from the sidelines.\n\n==Cast==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n* [[Craig Wasson]] as Jake Scully\n* [[Gregg Henry]] as Sam Bouchard\n* [[Melanie Griffith]] as Holly Body\n* [[Deborah Shelton]] as Gloria Revelle\n* [[Guy Boyd (actor)|Guy Boyd]] as Detective Jim McLean\n* [[Dennis Franz]] as Rubin\n* [[David Haskell]] as Will\n* [[Al Israel]] as Corso\n* [[Douglas Warhit]] as Video Salesman\n* B.J. Jones as Douglas\n* [[Russ Marin]] as Frank\n* [[Lane Davies]] as Billy\n* [[Barbara Crampton]] as Carol\n* [[Larry \"Flash\" Jenkins]] as Assistant Director\n* [[Monte Landis]] as Sid Goldberg\n* [[Slavitza Jovan]] as Saleslady\n* [[Rob Paulsen]] as Cameraman\n}}\n==Production==\nAfter the success of ''Scarface'' De Palma was offered a three-picture deal by Columbia of which ''Body Double'' was to be the first. (Reception to the film would be such that Columbia elected not to make the next two films.)<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/09/24/body-double-why-brian-de-palmas-pornographic-fiasco-is-worth-ano/|title=Body Double: why Brian De Palma's pornographic fiasco is worth another peek |first=Robbie|last=Collin|date=24 September 2016}}</ref> The director made it immediately after ''Scarface''. \"I like to work,\" he said.<ref>Tempo: Director tames image of violence\nBeck, Marilyn. Chicago Tribune 12 Jan 1984: n_b10.</ref>\n\nDe Palma had endured a fight with the censorship board over ''Scarface'' - they rated it X and he had to battle to make it R. \"I'll show them,\" he said at the time. \"I'm going to give them everything they hate and more of it than they've ever seen. They think ''Scarface'' was violent? They think my other movies were erotic? Wait until they see Body Double.\" <ref name=\"de\">BRIAN DE PALMA THINKS WE NEED MORE VIOLENCE IN OUR LIVES\nLyman, Rick. Philadelphia Inquirer; Philadelphia, Pa. [Philadelphia, Pa]12 Feb 1984: 12. </ref>\n===Scripting===\nThe film was based on an idea of Brian de Palma. He says he got it when interviewing [[Angie Dickinson]]'s body doubles for ''Dressed to Kill''.<ref name=\"de\"/> \" I started thinking about the whole idea of the body double,\" he said. \"I wondered what I would do if I wanted to make sure to get somebody's attention, to have them looking at a certain place at a certain time.\"<ref name=\"define\">DE PALMA: A DEFINITION OF SUSPENSE\nLyman, Rick. Philadelphia Inquirer 28 Oct 1984: I.1. </ref> \n\n\"This is going to be a movie in the De Palma style and tradition,\" he said. \"An erotic thriller. It has a voyeuristic theme, about people being sucked into the things they're watching. A wild, erotic roller-coaster ride, so many twists and turns. I've watched audiences jump before, or seen them sit bolt upright in their seats. But I can't wait to watch an audience when they see this movie. They've never seen anything like this before.\"<ref name=\"de\"/>\n\nDe Palma had admired a script written by Robert Avrech and hired Avrech to write the script. Avrech later said \"Both Brian and I were, and are, huge fans of Alfred Hitchcock's movies. Together we screened Rear Window and Vertigo, and discussed the narrative strategies Hitch used in both films. So in a sense, I was working off of De Palma's ideas of Hitchcock's ideas.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opednews.com/populum/page.php?f=Behind-the-Scenes-with-Hol-by-Joan-Brunwasser-American-Jews_Hollywood_Interviews_Judaism-Jewish-131219-897.html|website=Op Ed News|date=21 December 2013|title=\nBehind the Scenes with Hollywood Screenwriter, Robert Avrech|first=Joan|last= Brunwasser  }}</ref>\n\nDe Palma said he decided to use a drill as a murder instrument because \"I do a lot of murder mysteries, and after a while you get tired of the usual instruments. You can use a knife, a rope, but now we have electrical instruments, which are truly terrifying.\" He added a drill was big enough to be seen by the character across a canyon. \"It was not my intention to create a sexual image with the drill, although it could be construed that way.\"<ref name=\"people\">{{cite magazine| magazine=People|url=https://people.com/archive/despite-his-critics-director-brian-de-palma-says-body-double-is-neither-too-violent-nor-too-sexy-vol-22-no-25/|title=\nDespite His Critics, Director Brian De Palma Says Body Double Is Neither Too Violent nor Too Sexy|first= William |last=Plummer|date= December 17, 1984}}</ref>\n\nThe film was criticised for its violence towards women. \"Women in peril work better in the suspense genre,\" said De Palma. \"It all goes back to the Perils of Pauline... I don\u2019t think morality applies to art. It\u2019s a ludicrous idea. I mean, what is the morality of a still life? I don\u2019t think there\u2019s good or bad fruit in the bowl.\"<ref name=\"people\"/>\n\n\"If this one doesn't get an X, nothing I ever do is going to,\" he said at the time. \"This is going to be the most erotic and surprising and thrilling movie I know how to make.\"<ref name=\"de\"/> \n===Casting===\nDirector Brian De Palma originally considered [[Annette Haven]] to play the lead female role. Before filming he commented, \"I'm already thinking of casting. I don't know if there're any good young porno stars out here, but the older ones - Annette Haven, [[Seka (actress)|Seka]] - some of them can really act. And Annette Haven has a terrific body.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Brian De Palma: Interviews|publisher=[[University Press of Mississippi]]|first1=Brian |last1=De Palma |first2=Laurence F. |last2=Knapp |year=2003|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nZpkTAxWu4EC|isbn=1-57806-516-X|pages=91}}</ref>\n\nHowever he changed his mind and cast Melanie Griffith. \"I discovered that using a real person to play a fictional counterpart doesn't necessarily make the character more real,\" he said.<ref name=\"mel\">FILM CLIPS: 'BETRAYAL': SHOWDOWN IN THE COMMERCE CORRAL\nLondon, Michael. Los Angeles Times ]25 Jan 1984: g1. </ref>\n\nDe Palma later said that Haven \"was an enormous amount of help\" to him in his understanding of the adult film industry and what Holly's background might be \"But in the end I looked at her screen test and at Melanie's and there was really no comparison\" as Griffith brougt \"a comic edge that I wanted to be a major part of the tone of the second half of the movie.\"<ref name=\"define\"/>\n\n\"I think I gave her a great amount of intelligence,\" said Griffith. \"I used to think I didn't want any more nymphet roles, but now I think I can bring a lot of life to that kind of character.\"<ref name=\"griff\">AT THE MOVIES; 'Top Secret' rock star aims to be lovable.\nMaslin, Janet. New York Times 22 June 1984: C.10..</ref>\n\n[[Slavitza Jovan]], who appeared as Gozer the Gozerian in ''[[Ghostbusters]]'' the same year, [[1984 in film|1984]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Ghostbusters (1984): Acting Credits|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/19671/Ghostbusters/cast |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=June 18, 2018|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325034129/http://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/19671/Ghostbusters/cast|archivedate=March 25, 2016}}</ref> briefly appears as a saleslady.<ref name=cast/>\n\nProlific voice actor [[Rob Paulsen]] appears in the film as a cameraman for a pornographic film.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/55526/Rob-Paulsen/filmography|title=Rob Paulsen: Filmography|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117042310/https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/55526/Rob-Paulsen/filmography/|archivedate=November 17, 2015|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Body Double'' contains a [[film within a film]] sequence in which pop band [[Frankie Goes to Hollywood]] performs their song \"[[Relax (song)|Relax]]\"<ref name=DT>{{cite web|work=[[DVD Talk]]|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/23720/body-double-special-edition/|title=Body Double: Special Edition|date=September 9, 2006|last=Gibron |first=Bill |accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref> on the set of a [[porn]] film,{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} and in which [[scream queen]] [[Brinke Stevens]],<ref name=cast>{{cite web|title=Body Double (1984): Acting Credits|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/6485/Body-Double/cast|work=[[The New York Times]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117034244/http://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/6485/Body-Double/cast|archivedate=November 17, 2015|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref> and [[adult actress]]es [[Cara Lott]] and [[Annette Haven]] appear.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n===Locations===\nFilming started January 30, 1984.<ref>FILM CLIPS: CUBA-BORN ACTOR A 'SCARFACE' HIT FILM CLIPS: BAUER SCORES IN 'SCARFACE'\nLondon, Michael. Los Angeles Times 16 Dec 1983: m1. </ref>\n\nThe film was shot in the Los Angeles area and includes such locations as [[Tail o' the Pup]], the [[Beverly Center]], [[Barney's Beanery]], the LA [[Farmers Market (Los Angeles)|Farmer's Market]], the Rodeo Collection mall on [[Rodeo Drive]], the [[Spruce Goose]] dome in Long Beach, the [[Hollywood Tower]] and adjacent [[Hollywood Freeway]], [[Tower Records (music retailer)|Tower Records]], and the [[Chemosphere]] futuristic house.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|title=Landmark House: John Lautner's Chemosphere|last=Timberg |first=Scott|date=July 23, 2011|url=https://www.latimes.com/home/la-hm-landmark-houses-john-lautner-chemosphere-htmlstory.html|accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref>\n==Ratings==\nDe Palma says that Columbia Pictures executives were at first enthusiastic about the film until it was previewed in Van Nuys. Response from the audience was not strong \"and the studio started to get really worried,\" he said. \"The only people crazier than the people who criticize me for violence are the people at the studios. I can't stand that sort of cowardice.\"<ref name=\"bad\"/> \n\nGriffith called the film \"a parody of Hollywood more than anything, and it only has one murder... There's no way it could get an X.\"<ref name=\"griff\"/>\n\nThe film was given an X by the Motion Picture Association of America Rating Board. Since many theaters refused to show X-rated films, De Palma had to re-edit the film as he did on ''Dressed to Kill'' and ''Scarface''. De Palma cut what he called \"a few minor things from the porno movie scene\" and got an R. De Palma said the studio would not support him. \"Do you think the guys who run Coca-Cola (Columbia Pictures' parent company) want publicity about violence? They are very aware of their public images, and when they start seeing articles in the ''New York Times'' about their product and violence, they go crazy. They're not showmen, they're corporation types.\"<ref name=\"bad\">BAD BOY BRIAN DE PALMA EXPLAINS HIMSELF \nBlowen, Michael. Boston Globe 28 Oct 1984: A8. </ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical===\nThe film was highly controversial due to its sex and violence.<ref>{{cite news|title=ON BRIAN DE PALMA-CROSSING THE LINE BETWEEN ART AN PORNOGRAPHY?|first=Nina |last=Darnton|date=November 18, 1984|newspaper=New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/11/18/movies/on-brian-de-palma-crossing-the-line-between-art-an-pornography.html}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] praised the film, giving it three and a half out of four stars and calling it \"an exhilarating exercise in pure filmmaking, a thriller in the Hitchcock tradition in which there's no particular point except that the hero is flawed, weak, and in terrible danger -- and we identify with him completely.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/body-double-1984 |title=Body Double |work=RogerEbert.com |publisher=Ebert Digital LLC |first=Roger |last=Ebert |authorlink=Roger Ebert |accessdate=July 30, 2019 }}</ref> [[Vincent Canby]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that De Palma \"again goes too far, which is the reason to see it. It's sexy and explicitly crude, entertaining and sometimes very funny. It's his most blatant variation to date on a Hitchcock film ('Vertigo'), but it's also a De Palma original, a movie that might have offended Hitchcock's wryly avuncular public personality, while appealing to his darker, most private fantasies.\"<ref>Canby, Vincent (October 26, 1984). [https://www.nytimes.com/1984/10/26/movies/film-depalma-evokes-vertigo-in-body-double.html \"Film: De Palma Evokes 'Vertigo' in 'Body Double'\".] ''[[The New York Times]]''. C8.</ref> [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' stated, \"To his credit, DePalma moves his camera as beautifully as any director in the business today and on a purely physical level 'Body Double' often proves quite seductive as the camera tracks, swirls, cranes and zooms towards and around the objects of DePalma's usually sinister contemplation. Unfortunately, most of the film consists of visual riffs on Alfred Hitchcock, particularly 'Vertigo' and 'Rear Window.'\"<ref>McCarthy, Todd (October 17, 1984). \"Film Reviews: Body Double\". ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''. 15.</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film two-and-a-half stars out of four and wrote, \"When the drill came onto the screen, De Palma lost me and control of his movie. At that point 'Body Double' ceased to be a homage to Hitchcock and instead became a cheap splatter film, and not a very good one at that.\"<ref>Siskel, Gene (October 26, 1984). \"Gore overshadows artistry in De Palma's 'Body Double'\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. 7J.</ref> [[Sheila Benson]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' panned the film as \"elaborately empty, silly and desperately derivative,\" and suggested that De Palma \"finally may have exhausted the patience of even his most tenacious admirers.\"<ref>Benson, Sheila (October 26, 1984). \"Elevating Voyeurism to New Lows\". ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Part VI, p. 26.</ref> [[Paul Attanasio]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote, \"A lewd, gory, twisty-turny murder mystery swirling around Hollywood's porn industry, 'Body Double' finds Brian De Palma at the zenith of his cinematic virtuosity. The movie has been carefully calculated to offend almost everyone\u2014and probably will. But, like Hitchcock, De Palma makes the audience's reaction the real subject; 'Body Double' is about the dark longings deep inside us.\"<ref>Attanasio, Paul (October 26, 1984). [https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1984/10/26/double-boiler/b3c86102-b9ed-43d7-8806-6655ee025dc2/ \"'Double' Boiler\".] ''[[The Washington Post]]''. C1.</ref>\n\n\"''Body Double'' was reviled when it came out,\" said De Palma. \"Reviled. It really hurt. I got slaughtered by the press right at the height of the women\u2019s liberation movement... I thought it was completely unjustified. It was a suspense thriller, and I was always interested in finding new ways to kill people.\u201d <ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/jun/07/brian-de-palma-carrie-scarface-retrospective-documentary|date=7 June 2016|title= Brian de Palma: 'Film lies all the time \u2026 24 times a second'|first=Ashley|last= Clark}}</ref>\n\nThe London Clinic for Battered Women asked Columbia Pictures for  a percentage of the profits from the film claiming it was \"blood money\" for using \"the victimization of women as a source of massive profit.\"<ref>Women's clinic seeks share of film profits\nThe Globe and Mail; 15 Dec 1984: M.8. </ref>\n===Box office===\nThe film opened at number three at the box office earning $2.8 million.<ref>New films in top three\nScott, Jay. The Globe and Mail 1 Nov 1984: E.1. </ref>\n\n===Cult reputation===\nThe film developed a cult following, perhaps due to its directorial and aesthetic indulgences, its early 1980s [[New wave music|new wave]] soundtrack, and the use of iconic Los Angeles locations.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} Review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 78% of critics have given the film a positive review based on 32 reviews, with an average rating of 6.31/10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/body_double/ |title=Body Double Movie (1984) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |accessdate=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe film's [[Trailer (film)|trailer]] won a [[Clio Awards|Clio Award]] in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35752/saturday-nightmares-body-double-1984 |title=Saturday Nightmares: Body Double (1984) |work=[[Dread Central]]|first=Scott|last=Hallam|date=July 25, 2012|accessdate=June 18, 2018|publisher=Dread Central Media}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Subject\n! Result\n|-\n|[[Golden Globe Award]]\n|[[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture]]\n|rowspan=3|[[Melanie Griffith]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[National Society of Film Critics|National Society of Film Critics Award]]\n|[[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[New York Film Critics Circle|New York Film Critics Circle Award]]\n|Best Supporting Actress\n|{{won|2nd place}}\n|-\n|[[Golden Raspberry Award]]\n|[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]]\n|[[Brian De Palma]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Cultural impact===\n''Body Double'' is referenced repeatedly throughout the [[Bret Easton Ellis]] novel ''[[American Psycho]]'' as the favorite film of the [[protagonist]] [[serial killer]] [[Patrick Bateman]].{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} He mentions that he has seen the film 37 times and rents the tape of it from a video store several times in the story. He also repeats scenes from the film to the reader or to other characters.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n==Remake==\n''Body Double'' was remade in 1993 in [[India]] as ''[[Pehla Nasha]]''. The film was directed by [[Ashutosh Gowariker]] in his directorial debut. [[Deepak Tijori]] plays the lead role alongside [[Pooja Bhatt]], [[Raveena Tandon]] and [[Paresh Rawal]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film}}\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* ''[[Videodrome]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Mulholland Drive (film)|Mulholland Drive]]'' (2001)\n* [[List of films featuring surveillance]]\n* [[List of American films of 1984]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0086984|Body Double}}\n* {{Amg title|6485|Body Double}}\n* {{Mojo title|bodydouble}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|body_double}}\n*[https://cinephiliabeyond.org/brian-de-palmas-body-double-hitchcockian-thriller-executed-completely-original-style/ ''Body Double''] at Cinephelia and Beyond\n{{Brian De Palma}}\n\n[[Category:1984 films]]\n[[Category:1980s erotic thriller films]]\n[[Category:1980s mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:1980s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:1980s slasher films]]\n[[Category:American erotic thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:American neo-noir films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American slasher films]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films about actors]]\n[[Category:Films about pornography]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Brian De Palma]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Pino Donaggio]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the film|the novel by Tess Gerritsen|Body Double (novel)|the job in visual-media production|Body double}}\n{{short description|1984 film directed by Brian De Palma}}\n{{Infobox film\n|name           = Body Double\n|image          = DePalma body double.jpg\n|caption        = Theatrical release poster\n|director       = [[Brian De Palma]]\n|screenplay     = Brian De Palma<br />[[Robert J. Avrech]]\n|story          = Brian De Palma\n|producer       = Brian De Palma\n|starring       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Craig Wasson]]\n* [[Gregg Henry]]\n* [[Melanie Griffith]]\n}}\n|music          = [[Pino Donaggio]]\n|cinematography = [[Stephen H. Burum]]\n|editing        = [[Gerald B. Greenberg]]<br />[[Bill Pankow]]\n|released       = {{Film date|1984|10|26}}\n|runtime        = 114 minutes\n|studio         = Delphi II Productions\n|distributor    = [[Columbia Pictures]]\n|country        = United States\n|language       = English\n|budget         = $10 million or $6 million<ref>Hollywood Lays an Egg\nJacobson, Harlan. Film Comment; New York Vol. 18, Iss. 3,  (May/Jun 1982): 49-52. </ref>\n|gross          = $8.8 million \n}}\n\n'''''Body Double''''' is a 1984 American [[neo-noir]] [[erotic thriller]] film co-written and directed by [[Brian De Palma]] and starring [[Craig Wasson]], [[Gregg Henry]], [[Melanie Griffith]], and [[Deborah Shelton]]. The original musical score was composed by [[Pino Donaggio]].\n\nThe film was a direct homage to the films of [[Alfred Hitchcock]], specifically ''[[Rear Window]]'' (1954), ''[[Vertigo (film)|Vertigo]]'' (1958), and ''[[Dial M for Murder]]'' (1954) taking plot lines and themes (such as [[voyeurism]] and obsession) from the first two films.<ref>{{cite book|last=Williams |first=Linda |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=6pL0AUb5BHUC&pg=PA86&lpg=PA86#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Erotic Thriller in Contemporary Cinema|page=86|year=2005|publisher=[[Indiana University Press]]|location=Bloomington}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Ann |last=Cvetkovich |chapter-url=http://english.illinoisstate.edu/strickland/rsvtxt/cvetko.htm |chapter=Postmodern Vertigo: The Sexual Politics of Allusion in De Palma's Body Double |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130211060858/http://english.illinoisstate.edu/strickland/rsvtxt/cvetko.htm |archivedate=February 11, 2013 |url-status=dead |editor-last1=Raubicheck |editor-first1=Walter |editor-first2=Walter |editor-last2=Srebnick |title=Hitchcock's Rereleased Films: From Rope to Vertigo |location=Detroit |publisher=[[Wayne State University Press]] |year=1991}}</ref>\n\nThe film received a lukewarm result at the box office and mixed reviews, but has subsequently become a [[cult film]]. When [[Twilight Time (DVD label)|Twilight Time]] released the film on Blu-ray in the United States in 2013, it quickly sold out.<ref>https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/61564/body-double-blu-ray/</ref><ref>http://www.hometheaterforum.com/community/threads/body-double-blu-ray-review.325785/</ref><ref>http://www.rupertpupkinspeaks.com/2013/08/twilight-timey-body-double-on-blu-ray.html</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nJake Scully ([[Craig Wasson]]) is a struggling actor who has lost his role as a [[vampire]] in a low-budget [[horror film]] after his [[claustrophobia]] thwarts shooting. After returning home to discover his girlfriend ([[Barbara Crampton]]) cheating on him, he splits and is left without a place to stay (the residence belongs to her). At a [[method acting]] class, he meets Sam Bouchard ([[Gregg Henry]]) who closely monitors Scully's revelation of his fears and the childhood cause of his claustrophobia. They go to a bar where Scully is offered a place to stay; Sam's rich friend has gone on a trip to Europe and needs a house-sitter for his ultra-modern home in the [[Hollywood Hills]].\n\nDuring the tour of the house with Scully, Sam is especially enthusiastic about showing Scully one feature: a [[telescope]], and through it a female neighbor, Gloria Revelle ([[Deborah Shelton]]), who erotically dances at a specific time each night. Scully voyeuristically watches Gloria each night until he sees her being abused by a man she appears to know. The next day he follows her when she goes shopping. Gloria makes calls to an unknown person promising to meet them. Scully also notices a disfigured \"Indian\", a man he had noticed was watching Gloria a few days prior. Scully follows her to a seaside [[motel]] where apparently Gloria has been stood up by the person she was there to meet. On the beach the Indian suddenly snatches her purse. Scully pursues him into a nearby tunnel but is overcome by his claustrophobia. Gloria walks him out of it. They impulsively and passionately kiss before she retreats. That night Scully is again watching through the telescope when the Indian returns and breaks into Gloria's home. Scully races to save her but is attacked by Gloria's vicious dog. Gloria is brutally murdered by the Indian with a huge handheld [[drill]].\n\n[[File:John Lautner's Chemosphere (8189866290).jpg|thumb|left|[[Chemosphere]], the ultramodern house used in ''Body Double'']]\nScully alerts the police, who determine it was a botched robbery. However, Detective McLean ([[Guy Boyd (actor)|Guy Boyd]]) becomes suspicious after finding a pair of Gloria's panties in Scully's pocket. Although McLean does not arrest him, he tells Scully that his voyeuristic behavior, as well as not alerting the police sooner, helped cause Gloria's murder. Unable to sleep, Scully watches a pornography TV channel. He observes that the actress, Holly Body ([[Melanie Griffith]]), dances in exactly the same sensual manner that Gloria did. To meet Holly, he pretends to be a porn producer hiring for a new film.\n\nScully learns from Holly that Sam hired her to impersonate Gloria each night, dancing in the window, knowing Scully would be watching and later witness the real Gloria's murder. Offended at the suggestion she was involved in a killing, Holly storms out of the house. She is picked up by the Indian who knocks her unconscious and drives her away. Scully follows them to an aqueduct where the Indian is digging a grave. During their fight, Scully discovers the Indian is Sam in heavy make-up. Scully was a scapegoat providing Sam, who was Gloria's abusive husband, with an alibi during the murder. Scully is overpowered and thrown into the grave and is incapacitated by his claustrophobia. However, he overcomes his fear and climbs out as Sam is knocked into the aqueduct and drowned.\n\nDuring the ending credits, Scully is shown having been recast in his previous vampire role as Holly watches from the sidelines.\n\n==Cast==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n* [[Craig Wasson]] as Jake Scully\n* [[Gregg Henry]] as Sam Bouchard\n* [[Melanie Griffith]] as Holly Body\n* [[Deborah Shelton]] as Gloria Revelle\n* [[Guy Boyd (actor)|Guy Boyd]] as Detective Jim McLean\n* [[Dennis Franz]] as Rubin\n* [[David Haskell]] as Will\n* [[Al Israel]] as Corso\n* [[Douglas Warhit]] as Video Salesman\n* B.J. Jones as Douglas\n* [[Russ Marin]] as Frank\n* [[Lane Davies]] as Billy\n* [[Barbara Crampton]] as Carol\n* [[Larry \"Flash\" Jenkins]] as Assistant Director\n* [[Monte Landis]] as Sid Goldberg\n* [[Slavitza Jovan]] as Saleslady\n* [[Rob Paulsen]] as Cameraman\n}}\n==Production==\nAfter the success of ''Scarface'' De Palma was offered a three-picture deal by Columbia of which ''Body Double'' was to be the first. (Reception to the film would be such that Columbia elected not to make the next two films.)<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/films/2016/09/24/body-double-why-brian-de-palmas-pornographic-fiasco-is-worth-ano/|title=Body Double: why Brian De Palma's pornographic fiasco is worth another peek |first=Robbie|last=Collin|date=24 September 2016}}</ref> The director made it immediately after ''Scarface''. \"I like to work,\" he said.<ref>Tempo: Director tames image of violence\nBeck, Marilyn. Chicago Tribune 12 Jan 1984: n_b10.</ref>\n\nDe Palma had endured a fight with the censorship board over ''Scarface'' - they rated it X and he had to battle to make it R. \"I'll show them,\" he said at the time. \"I'm going to give them everything they hate and more of it than they've ever seen. They think ''Scarface'' was violent? They think my other movies were erotic? Wait until they see Body Double.\" <ref name=\"de\">BRIAN DE PALMA THINKS WE NEED MORE VIOLENCE IN OUR LIVES\nLyman, Rick. Philadelphia Inquirer; Philadelphia, Pa. [Philadelphia, Pa]12 Feb 1984: 12. </ref>\n===Scripting===\nThe film was based on an idea of Brian de Palma. He says he got it when interviewing [[Angie Dickinson]]'s body doubles for ''Dressed to Kill''.<ref name=\"de\"/> \" I started thinking about the whole idea of the body double,\" he said. \"I wondered what I would do if I wanted to make sure to get somebody's attention, to have them looking at a certain place at a certain time.\"<ref name=\"define\">DE PALMA: A DEFINITION OF SUSPENSE\nLyman, Rick. Philadelphia Inquirer 28 Oct 1984: I.1. </ref> \n\n\"This is going to be a movie in the De Palma style and tradition,\" he said. \"An erotic thriller. It has a voyeuristic theme, about people being sucked into the things they're watching. A wild, erotic roller-coaster ride, so many twists and turns. I've watched audiences jump before, or seen them sit bolt upright in their seats. But I can't wait to watch an audience when they see this movie. They've never seen anything like this before.\"<ref name=\"de\"/>\n\nDe Palma had admired a script written by Robert Avrech and hired Avrech to write the script. Avrech later said \"Both Brian and I were, and are, huge fans of Alfred Hitchcock's movies. Together we screened Rear Window and Vertigo, and discussed the narrative strategies Hitch used in both films. So in a sense, I was working off of De Palma's ideas of Hitchcock's ideas.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opednews.com/populum/page.php?f=Behind-the-Scenes-with-Hol-by-Joan-Brunwasser-American-Jews_Hollywood_Interviews_Judaism-Jewish-131219-897.html|website=Op Ed News|date=21 December 2013|title=\nBehind the Scenes with Hollywood Screenwriter, Robert Avrech|first=Joan|last= Brunwasser  }}</ref>\n\nDe Palma said he decided to use a drill as a murder instrument because \"I do a lot of murder mysteries, and after a while you get tired of the usual instruments. You can use a knife, a rope, but now we have electrical instruments, which are truly terrifying.\" He added a drill was big enough to be seen by the character across a canyon. \"It was not my intention to create a sexual image with the drill, although it could be construed that way.\"<ref name=\"people\">{{cite magazine| magazine=People|url=https://people.com/archive/despite-his-critics-director-brian-de-palma-says-body-double-is-neither-too-violent-nor-too-sexy-vol-22-no-25/|title=\nDespite His Critics, Director Brian De Palma Says Body Double Is Neither Too Violent nor Too Sexy|first= William |last=Plummer|date= December 17, 1984}}</ref>\n\nThe film was criticised for its violence towards women. \"Women in peril work better in the suspense genre,\" said De Palma. \"It all goes back to the Perils of Pauline... I don\u2019t think morality applies to art. It\u2019s a ludicrous idea. I mean, what is the morality of a still life? I don\u2019t think there\u2019s good or bad fruit in the bowl.\"<ref name=\"people\"/>\n\n\"If this one doesn't get an X, nothing I ever do is going to,\" he said at the time. \"This is going to be the most erotic and surprising and thrilling movie I know how to make.\"<ref name=\"de\"/> \n===Casting===\nDirector Brian De Palma originally considered [[Annette Haven]] to play the lead female role. Before filming he commented, \"I'm already thinking of casting. I don't know if there're any good young porno stars out here, but the older ones - Annette Haven, [[Seka (actress)|Seka]] - some of them can really act. And Annette Haven has a terrific body.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Brian De Palma: Interviews|publisher=[[University Press of Mississippi]]|first1=Brian |last1=De Palma |first2=Laurence F. |last2=Knapp |year=2003|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nZpkTAxWu4EC|isbn=1-57806-516-X|pages=91}}</ref>\n\nHowever he changed his mind and cast Melanie Griffith. \"I discovered that using a real person to play a fictional counterpart doesn't necessarily make the character more real,\" he said.<ref name=\"mel\">FILM CLIPS: 'BETRAYAL': SHOWDOWN IN THE COMMERCE CORRAL\nLondon, Michael. Los Angeles Times ]25 Jan 1984: g1. </ref>\n\nDe Palma later said that Haven \"was an enormous amount of help\" to him in his understanding of the adult film industry and what Holly's background might be \"But in the end I looked at her screen test and at Melanie's and there was really no comparison\" as Griffith brougt \"a comic edge that I wanted to be a major part of the tone of the second half of the movie.\"<ref name=\"define\"/>\n\n\"I think I gave her a great amount of intelligence,\" said Griffith. \"I used to think I didn't want any more nymphet roles, but now I think I can bring a lot of life to that kind of character.\"<ref name=\"griff\">AT THE MOVIES; 'Top Secret' rock star aims to be lovable.\nMaslin, Janet. New York Times 22 June 1984: C.10..</ref>\n\n[[Slavitza Jovan]], who appeared as Gozer the Gozerian in ''[[Ghostbusters]]'' the same year, [[1984 in film|1984]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Ghostbusters (1984): Acting Credits|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/19671/Ghostbusters/cast |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=June 18, 2018|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325034129/http://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/19671/Ghostbusters/cast|archivedate=March 25, 2016}}</ref> briefly appears as a saleslady.<ref name=cast/>\n\nProlific voice actor [[Rob Paulsen]] appears in the film as a cameraman for a pornographic film.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/55526/Rob-Paulsen/filmography|title=Rob Paulsen: Filmography|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117042310/https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/55526/Rob-Paulsen/filmography/|archivedate=November 17, 2015|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Body Double'' contains a [[film within a film]] sequence in which pop band [[Frankie Goes to Hollywood]] performs their song \"[[Relax (song)|Relax]]\"<ref name=DT>{{cite web|work=[[DVD Talk]]|url=https://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/23720/body-double-special-edition/|title=Body Double: Special Edition|date=September 9, 2006|last=Gibron |first=Bill |accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref> on the set of a [[porn]] film,{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} and in which [[scream queen]] [[Brinke Stevens]],<ref name=cast>{{cite web|title=Body Double (1984): Acting Credits|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/6485/Body-Double/cast|work=[[The New York Times]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117034244/http://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/6485/Body-Double/cast|archivedate=November 17, 2015|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref> and [[adult actress]]es [[Cara Lott]] and [[Annette Haven]] appear.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n===Locations===\nFilming started January 30, 1984.<ref>FILM CLIPS: CUBA-BORN ACTOR A 'SCARFACE' HIT FILM CLIPS: BAUER SCORES IN 'SCARFACE'\nLondon, Michael. Los Angeles Times 16 Dec 1983: m1. </ref>\n\nThe film was shot in the Los Angeles area and includes such locations as [[Tail o' the Pup]], the [[Beverly Center]], [[Barney's Beanery]], the LA [[Farmers Market (Los Angeles)|Farmer's Market]], the Rodeo Collection mall on [[Rodeo Drive]], the [[Spruce Goose]] dome in Long Beach, the [[Hollywood Tower]] and adjacent [[Hollywood Freeway]], [[Tower Records (music retailer)|Tower Records]], and the [[Chemosphere]] futuristic house.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|title=Landmark House: John Lautner's Chemosphere|last=Timberg |first=Scott|date=July 23, 2011|url=https://www.latimes.com/home/la-hm-landmark-houses-john-lautner-chemosphere-htmlstory.html|accessdate=June 18, 2018}}</ref>\n==Ratings==\nDe Palma says that Columbia Pictures executives were at first enthusiastic about the film under it was previewed in Van Nuys. Response from the audience was not strong \"and the studio started to get really worried,\" he said. \"The only people crazier than the people who criticize me for violence are the people at the studios. I can't stand that sort of cowardice.\"<ref name=\"bad\"/> \n\nGriffith called the film \"a parody of Hollywood more than anything, and it only has one murder... There's no way it could get an X.\"<ref name=\"griff\"/>\n\nThe film was given an X by the Motion Picture Association of America Rating Board. Since many theaters refused to show X-rated films, De Palma had to re-edit the film as he did on ''Dressed to Kill'' and ''Scarface''. De Palma cut what he called \"a few minor things from the porno movie scene\" and got an R. De Palma said the studio would not support him. \"Do you think the guys who run Coca-Cola (Columbia Pictures' parent company) want publicity about violence? They are very aware of their public images, and when they start seeing articles in the ''New York Times'' about their product and violence, they go crazy. They're not showmen, they're corporation types.\"<ref name=\"bad\">BAD BOY BRIAN DE PALMA EXPLAINS HIMSELF \nBlowen, Michael. Boston Globe 28 Oct 1984: A8. </ref> \n==Reception==\n===Critical===\nThe film was highly controversial due to its sex and violence.<ref>{{cite news|title=ON BRIAN DE PALMA-CROSSING THE LINE BETWEEN ART AN PORNOGRAPHY?|first=Nina |last=Darnton|date=November 18, 1984|newspaper=New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/11/18/movies/on-brian-de-palma-crossing-the-line-between-art-an-pornography.html}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] praised the film, giving it three and a half out of four stars and calling it \"an exhilarating exercise in pure filmmaking, a thriller in the Hitchcock tradition in which there's no particular point except that the hero is flawed, weak, and in terrible danger -- and we identify with him completely.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/body-double-1984 |title=Body Double |work=RogerEbert.com |publisher=Ebert Digital LLC |first=Roger |last=Ebert |authorlink=Roger Ebert |accessdate=July 30, 2019 }}</ref> [[Vincent Canby]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote that De Palma \"again goes too far, which is the reason to see it. It's sexy and explicitly crude, entertaining and sometimes very funny. It's his most blatant variation to date on a Hitchcock film ('Vertigo'), but it's also a De Palma original, a movie that might have offended Hitchcock's wryly avuncular public personality, while appealing to his darker, most private fantasies.\"<ref>Canby, Vincent (October 26, 1984). [https://www.nytimes.com/1984/10/26/movies/film-depalma-evokes-vertigo-in-body-double.html \"Film: De Palma Evokes 'Vertigo' in 'Body Double'\".] ''[[The New York Times]]''. C8.</ref> [[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' stated, \"To his credit, DePalma moves his camera as beautifully as any director in the business today and on a purely physical level 'Body Double' often proves quite seductive as the camera tracks, swirls, cranes and zooms towards and around the objects of DePalma's usually sinister contemplation. Unfortunately, most of the film consists of visual riffs on Alfred Hitchcock, particularly 'Vertigo' and 'Rear Window.'\"<ref>McCarthy, Todd (October 17, 1984). \"Film Reviews: Body Double\". ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''. 15.</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film two-and-a-half stars out of four and wrote, \"When the drill came onto the screen, De Palma lost me and control of his movie. At that point 'Body Double' ceased to be a homage to Hitchcock and instead became a cheap splatter film, and not a very good one at that.\"<ref>Siskel, Gene (October 26, 1984). \"Gore overshadows artistry in De Palma's 'Body Double'\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. 7J.</ref> [[Sheila Benson]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' panned the film as \"elaborately empty, silly and desperately derivative,\" and suggested that De Palma \"finally may have exhausted the patience of even his most tenacious admirers.\"<ref>Benson, Sheila (October 26, 1984). \"Elevating Voyeurism to New Lows\". ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Part VI, p. 26.</ref> [[Paul Attanasio]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote, \"A lewd, gory, twisty-turny murder mystery swirling around Hollywood's porn industry, 'Body Double' finds Brian De Palma at the zenith of his cinematic virtuosity. The movie has been carefully calculated to offend almost everyone\u2014and probably will. But, like Hitchcock, De Palma makes the audience's reaction the real subject; 'Body Double' is about the dark longings deep inside us.\"<ref>Attanasio, Paul (October 26, 1984). [https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1984/10/26/double-boiler/b3c86102-b9ed-43d7-8806-6655ee025dc2/ \"'Double' Boiler\".] ''[[The Washington Post]]''. C1.</ref>\n\n\"''Body Double'' was reviled when it came out,\" said De Palma. \"Reviled. It really hurt. I got slaughtered by the press right at the height of the women\u2019s liberation movement... I thought it was completely unjustified. It was a suspense thriller, and I was always interested in finding new ways to kill people.\u201d <ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/jun/07/brian-de-palma-carrie-scarface-retrospective-documentary|date=7 June 2016|title= Brian de Palma: 'Film lies all the time \u2026 24 times a second'|first=Ashley|last= Clark}}</ref>\n\nThe London Clinic for Battered Women asked Columbia Pictures for  a percentage of the profits from the film claiming it was \"blood money\" for using \"the victimization of women as a source of massive profit.\"<ref>Women's clinic seeks share of film profits\nThe Globe and Mail; 15 Dec 1984: M.8. </ref>\n===Box office===\nThe film opened at number three at the box office earning $2.8 million.<ref>New films in top three\nScott, Jay. The Globe and Mail 1 Nov 1984: E.1. </ref>\n\n===Cult reputation===\nThe film developed a cult following, perhaps due to its directorial and aesthetic indulgences, its early 1980s [[New wave music|new wave]] soundtrack, and the use of iconic Los Angeles locations.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} Review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 78% of critics have given the film a positive review based on 32 reviews, with an average rating of 6.31/10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/body_double/ |title=Body Double Movie (1984) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango Media]] |accessdate=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe film's [[Trailer (film)|trailer]] won a [[Clio Awards|Clio Award]] in 1984.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35752/saturday-nightmares-body-double-1984 |title=Saturday Nightmares: Body Double (1984) |work=[[Dread Central]]|first=Scott|last=Hallam|date=July 25, 2012|accessdate=June 18, 2018|publisher=Dread Central Media}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Award\n! Category\n! Subject\n! Result\n|-\n|[[Golden Globe Award]]\n|[[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture]]\n|rowspan=3|[[Melanie Griffith]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[National Society of Film Critics|National Society of Film Critics Award]]\n|[[National Society of Film Critics Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[New York Film Critics Circle|New York Film Critics Circle Award]]\n|Best Supporting Actress\n|{{won|2nd place}}\n|-\n|[[Golden Raspberry Award]]\n|[[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Director|Worst Director]]\n|[[Brian De Palma]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===Cultural impact===\n''Body Double'' is referenced repeatedly throughout the [[Bret Easton Ellis]] novel ''[[American Psycho]]'' as the favorite film of the [[protagonist]] [[serial killer]] [[Patrick Bateman]].{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} He mentions that he has seen the film 37 times and rents the tape of it from a video store several times in the story. He also repeats scenes from the film to the reader or to other characters.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}}\n\n==Remake==\n''Body Double'' was remade in 1993 in [[India]] as ''[[Pehla Nasha]]''. The film was directed by [[Ashutosh Gowariker]] in his directorial debut. [[Deepak Tijori]] plays the lead role alongside [[Pooja Bhatt]], [[Raveena Tandon]] and [[Paresh Rawal]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film}}\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* ''[[Videodrome]]'' (1983)\n* ''[[Mulholland Drive (film)|Mulholland Drive]]'' (2001)\n* [[List of films featuring surveillance]]\n* [[List of American films of 1984]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0086984|Body Double}}\n* {{Amg title|6485|Body Double}}\n* {{Mojo title|bodydouble}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|body_double}}\n*[https://cinephiliabeyond.org/brian-de-palmas-body-double-hitchcockian-thriller-executed-completely-original-style/ ''Body Double''] at Cinephelia and Beyond\n{{Brian De Palma}}\n\n[[Category:1984 films]]\n[[Category:1980s erotic thriller films]]\n[[Category:1980s mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:1980s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:1980s slasher films]]\n[[Category:American erotic thriller films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:American neo-noir films]]\n[[Category:American psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:American slasher films]]\n[[Category:Columbia Pictures films]]\n[[Category:Films about actors]]\n[[Category:Films about pornography]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Brian De Palma]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Pino Donaggio]]\n[[Category:Films set in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n", "name_user": "Rickremember", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRatings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Body_Double"}
{"title_page": "David Benioff", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American author and producer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = David Benioff\n| image              = David Benioff by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| birth_name         = David Friedman\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1970|09|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], New York, U.S.\n| education          = [[Dartmouth College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Trinity College Dublin]]<br>[[University of California, Irvine]] ([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])\n| occupation         = [[Screenwriter]], [[television producer]], [[television writer]], [[television director|director]], [[novelist]]\n| years_active       = 2002\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Amanda Peet]]|2006}}\n| children           = 3\n| mother             = Barbara Benioff\n| father             = [[Stephen Friedman (PFIAB)|Stephen Friedman]]\n}}\n'''David Benioff''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u025b|n|i|\u0252|f}}; [[n\u00e9]] '''Friedman''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|f|r|i\u02d0|d|m|\u0259|n}}; born September 25, 1970) is an American screenwriter and television producer, writer, and director. Along with his collaborator [[D. B. Weiss]], he is best-known as co-creator, [[showrunner]], and writer of ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' (2011\u20132019), the [[HBO]] adaptation of [[George R. R. Martin]]'s series of books ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire]]''. He is also known for writing ''[[Troy (film)|Troy]]'' (2004) and co-writing ''[[X-Men Origins: Wolverine]]'' (2009).\n\n==Early life==\nBenioff was born David Friedman in [[New York City]], to a [[Jews|Jewish]] family who emigrated from Austria, Romania, Germany, Poland and Russia.<ref name=\"dkamin\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/the-jewish-legacy-behind-game-of-thrones/ |title=The Jewish legacy behind 'Game of Thrones' |last=Kamin |first=Debra |date=May 20, 2014 |work=[[The Times of Israel]] |access-date=March 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.clevelandjewishnews.com/archives/jewish-stars-genealogy-and-fairy-tales/article_a7c3999a-7904-11e1-8dd2-0019bb2963f4.html |title=Jewish Stars: genealogy and fairy tales |last=Bloom |first=Nate |date=February 2, 2012 |work=[[Cleveland Jewish News]]}}</ref> He is the son of Barbara (Benioff) and [[Stephen Friedman (PFIAB)|Stephen Friedman]], who is a former head of [[Goldman Sachs]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/08/28/classified/paid-notice-deaths-benioff-florence.html |title=Deaths: Benioff, Florence |date=August 28, 2000 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 28, 2016}}</ref> He is a distant cousin of [[Salesforce]] founder [[Marc Benioff]].<ref name=\"Bort2015\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/how-these-famous-benioffs-are-related-2015-4 |title=How these famous Benioffs are related |last=Bort |first=Julie |date=April 12, 2015 |work=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=March 28, 2016}}</ref> As an adult, he uses the last name Benioff, his mother's [[Maiden and married names|maiden name]], to avoid confusion with other writers named David Friedman.<ref name=Bort2015/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/03/19/goldmans-former-leader-appears-among-warriors-and-dragons/ |title=Former Goldman Chief Walks Among Warriors and Dragons |last=Alden |first=William |date=March 19, 2014 |website=[[DealBook]]}}</ref> He is the youngest of three children; his sisters are Suzy and Caroline.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://gawker.com/550966/stephen-friedman |title=Stephen Friedman |last=cityfile |website=gawker.com |access-date=19 March 2018}}</ref> and grew up in Manhattan, first in [[Stuyvesant Town\u2013Peter Cooper Village|Peter Cooper Village]], then on [[86th Street (Manhattan)|86th Street]] where he spent most of his childhood, before eventually moving near the [[Headquarters of the United Nations|U.N. headquarters]] when he was 16.<ref name=\"vanity fair\" />\n\nBenioff is an alumnus of [[The Collegiate School]] and of [[Dartmouth College]]. While at Dartmouth he was a member of [[Dartmouth College Greek organizations#Phi Delta Alpha (\u03a6\u0394\u0391)|Phi Delta Alpha Fraternity]] and the [[Sphinx (senior society)|Sphinx Senior Society]]. After graduating in 1992, he worked in a number of jobs: for a time as a [[Bouncer (doorman)|club bouncer]] in [[San Francisco]], and as a high school [[English studies|English]] teacher at [[Poly Prep]] in [[Brooklyn, New York City]] for two years, where he served as the school's wrestling coach.<ref name=\"vanity fair\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://chalkboardchampions.org/education/novelist-hollywood-personality-david-benioff-hes-former-english-teacher/ |title=Novelist and Hollywood Personality David Benioff: He\u2019s a Former English Teacher |date=December 18, 2013 |website=Chalkboard Champions}}</ref>\n\nBenioff became interested in pursuing an academic career and went to [[Trinity College Dublin]] in 1995, for a one-year program to study Irish literature. While in Dublin he met [[D. B. Weiss]], who would later become his collaborator.<ref name=\"dkamin\" /> Benioff wrote a thesis on [[Samuel Beckett]] while at Trinity College, but decided against a career in academia after writing the thesis.<ref name=\"vanity fair\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2014/03/game-of-thrones-benioff-weiss-interview |title=The Surprising Connection Between Game of Thrones and Monty Python |date=March 24, 2014 |work=Vanity Fair}}</ref> He worked as a radio DJ in [[Moose, Wyoming]] for a year\u2014mostly as a side job, which he mainly accepted to take a year in the countryside at a writer's retreat.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://metro.co.uk/2009/10/27/david-benioff-636358/ |title=David Benioff |last=Ellis |first=James |date=October 27, 2009 |work=Metro}}</ref> He then applied to join the Creative Writing Program at the [[University of California, Irvine]] after reading ''[[The Mysteries of Pittsburgh]]'' by [[Michael Chabon]] (an alumnus there),<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/sep/02/local/me-writing2/2 |title=Program Gives Writers a Professional Polish |last=Gottlieb |first=Jeff |date=September 2, 2002 |work=The Los Angeles Times |access-date=July 14, 2017 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930062313/http://articles.latimes.com/2002/sep/02/local/me-writing2/2 |archive-date=September 30, 2016}}</ref> and received a [[Master of Fine Arts]] degree in creative writing there in 1999.<ref name=\"dartmouth\">{{Cite news |url=http://thedartmouth.com/2011/05/12/benioff-92-embraces-storytelling-in-surreal-career/ |title=Benioff \u201992 embraces storytelling in \u2018surreal\u2019 career |last=Katie Kilkenny |date=May 12, 2011 |work=The Dartmouth |access-date=June 12, 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816111920/http://thedartmouth.com/2011/05/12/benioff-92-embraces-storytelling-in-surreal-career |archive-date=August 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, ''People'' magazine included Benioff on its list of America's Top 50 Most Eligible Bachelors.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://people.com/archive/cover-story-americas-top-50-bachelors-vol-56-no-1/ |title=America's Top 50 Bachelors |work=People}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Writing career===\nBenioff spent two years writing his first published novel ''[[The 25th Hour]]'',<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/may/13/news/cl-62730 |title=How to Write a Powerful First Novel in a Bland Age |last=Jalon |first=Allan M. |date=May 13, 2001 |work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/dec/02/entertainment/et-gottlieb2 |title=His Finest Hour |last=Gottlieb |first=Jeff |date=December 2, 2002 |work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> originally titled ''Fireman Down'', and completed the book as his thesis for his master's degree at Irvine.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://news.uci.edu/feature/crowning-achievement/ |title=Crowning achievement |date=August 12, 2014 |work=UCI News}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/may/03/featuresreviews.guardianreview6 |title=One more hour |last=Benioff |first=David |date=May 3, 2003 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> He was asked to adapt the book into a screenplay after [[Tobey Maguire]] read a preliminary trade copy and became interested in making a film of the book.<ref name=\"dartmouth\" /> The film adaptation, titled ''[[25th Hour]]'' and starring [[Edward Norton]], was directed by [[Spike Lee]].<ref name=Guardian /><ref name=\"herald\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/11901820.Q__What_do_Brad_Pitt__Spike_Lee_and_the_Iliad_have_in_common____A__David_Benioff__Hollywood_apos_s_latest__wonder_kid/ |title=Q: What do Brad Pitt, Spike Lee and the Iliad have in common? A: David Benioff, Hollywood's latest wonder kid |date=March 29, 2003 |work=Herald Scotland}}</ref> Benioff then wrote a collection of short stories titled ''When the Nines Roll Over (And Other Stories)'' (2004).<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://books.usatoday.com/book/david-benioff--when-the-nines-roll-over/r106816 |title=Screenwriter's short stories shine |last=Stephenson |first=Anne |date=August 30, 2004 |work=USA TODAY}}</ref>\n\nHe drafted a screenplay of the [[Greek mythology|mythological]] epic ''[[Troy (film)|Troy]]'' (2004), for which Warner Bros. pictures paid him $2.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://chalkboardchampions.org/education/novelist-hollywood-personality-david-benioff-hes-former-english-teacher/ |title=Novelist and Hollywood Personality David Benioff: He's a Former English Teacher |date=December 18, 2013 |website=Chalkboard Champions |access-date=March 28, 2016}}</ref> He also wrote the script for the psychological thriller ''[[Stay (2005 film)|Stay]]'' (2005), which was directed by [[Marc Forster]], and stars [[Ewan McGregor]] and [[Naomi Watts]]. His screenplay for ''[[The Kite Runner (film)|The Kite Runner]]'' (2007), adapted from the novel of the same name, marked his second collaboration with director Marc Forster.\n\nBenioff was hired in 2004 to write the screenplay for the ''X-Men'' spin-off ''[[X-Men Origins: Wolverine]]'' (2009). He based his script on [[Barry Windsor-Smith]]'s \"[[Weapon X]]\" story, [[Chris Claremont]] and [[Frank Miller (comics)|Frank Miller]]'s [[Wolverine (comic book)|1982 limited series on the character]],<ref name=\"real\">{{Cite journal |last=Mishler, James |date=June 2005 |title=David Benioff, Screenwriter of Wolverine: He's One of Us |journal=[[Comics Buyer's Guide]] |pages=18\u201320}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://suicidegirls.com/interviews/David+Benioff/ |title=David Benioff |last=Daniel Robert Epstein |date=December 28, 2004 |work=[[SuicideGirls]] |access-date=February 9, 2008}}</ref> as well as the 2001 limited series ''[[Origin (comics)|Origin]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/film/article6191387.ece |title=Chris Claremont, Len Wein: the men who created Wolverine |last=Vaughan |first=Owen |date=April 29, 2009 |work=The Times |access-date=May 12, 2009 |location=UK}}</ref> [[Hugh Jackman]] collaborated on the script, which he wanted to be more of a character piece compared with the previous ''X-Men'' films.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.canmag.com/news/4/3/5413 |title=Interview \u2013 Hugh Jackman |date=October 15, 2006 |work=CanMag |access-date=October 15, 2006}}</ref> [[Skip Woods]] was later hired by Fox to revise and rewrite Benioff's script.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/823/823830p1.html |title=New Wolverine Screenwriter |last=Stax |date=September 28, 2007 |website=IGN |access-date=July 9, 2009}}</ref> Benioff had aimed for a \"darker and a bit more brutal\" story, writing it with an [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system#Ratings|R rating]] in mind, although he acknowledged the film's final tone would rest with the producers and director.<ref name=real/>\n\nIn 2006, Benioff became interested in adapting [[George R.R. Martin]]'s novel series, ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire]]'', and began working with [[D. B. Weiss]] on a proposed television series, ''[[Game of Thrones]]''.<ref name=\"upclose\">{{Cite news |url=https://soundcloud.com/kcrw/upclose-game-of-thrones-with |title=UpClose: Game of Thrones with David Benioff and D.B. Weiss (FULL LENGTH) |last=Mitchell |first=Elvis |date=May 8, 2013 |work=[[KCRW]] |access-date=May 15, 2013 |publisher=AVMedia}}</ref> The pilot, \"[[Winter Is Coming]]\", was put into development by HBO in 2007 and the series greenlit in 2010. Benioff and Weiss acted as the executive producers, [[showrunners]], and writers of the show, which began airing on [[HBO]] in 2011. Benioff and Weiss had previously worked together on a script for a horror film titled ''The Headmaster'', but it was never made.<ref name=\"vanity fair\" />\n\nIn October 2007, [[Universal Pictures]] hired Benioff to write an adapted screenplay of the [[Charles R. Cross]] biography of [[Kurt Cobain]], but the screenplay was not used.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1635411/kurt-cobain-biopic-in-the-works-16-years-after-his-death/ |title=Kurt Cobain Biopic 'In The Works,' 16 Years After His Death |last=Rosenberg |first=Adam |date=April 5, 2010 |work=MTV News |access-date=March 28, 2016}}</ref> In 2008, Benioff's second novel, ''[[City of Thieves (Novel)|City of Thieves]]'', was published.\n\nOn April 10, 2014, Benioff announced he and Weiss had taken on their first feature film project to write, produce, and direct ''[[Dirty White Boys]]'', a novel by the Pulitzer prize-winning author [[Stephen Hunter]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/04/game-of-thrones-david-benioff-d-b-weiss-plan-dirty-white-boys-as-first-feature |title='Game Of Thrones' David Benioff & D.B. Weiss Plan 'Dirty White Boys' As First Movie |last=Fleming |first=Mike |date=April 10, 2014 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=March 28, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pulitzer.org/citation/2003-Criticism |title=The 2003 Pulitzer Prize Winners (Criticism) |website=Pulitzer.org |access-date=24 April 2014}}</ref> On July 19, 2017, Benioff announced that he and Weiss would produce another HBO series, titled ''[[Confederate (TV series)|Confederate]]'', after the final season of ''Game of Thrones''. Benioff and Weiss said, \"We have discussed ''Confederate'' for years, originally as a concept for a feature film, but our experience on ''Thrones'' has convinced us that no one provides a bigger, better storytelling canvas than HBO.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://ew.com/tv/2017/07/19/game-of-thrones-showrunners-confederate/ |title=Game of Thrones showrunners reveal their next epic HBO series |last=Hibberd |first=James |date=July 19, 2017 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=July 19, 2017}}</ref> The announcement of ''Confederate'' was met with public animosity, and as of August 2019 (when Benioff and Weiss' deal with Netflix deal was announced) would not be moving forward.<ref name=\"NetflixDeal\">{{cite web |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |date=August 7, 2019 |title='Game of Thrones' Creators Close $200M Netflix Overall Deal |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/game-thrones-creators-close-200m-netflix-deal-1230119 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=8 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn February 6, 2018, [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] announced that both Benioff and Weiss would write and produce a new series of ''[[Star Wars]]'' films after the final season of ''Game of Thrones'' is completed in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://ew.com/movies/2018/02/06/game-of-thrones-creators-developing-new-star-wars-films/ |title=Game of Thrones creators developing new Star Wars films |last=Brenican |first=Anthony |date=February 6, 2018 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=February 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nTowards the end of the final season of ''Game of Thrones'', a petition to [[HBO]] was started on [[Change.org]]. It described showrunners Benioff and Weiss as \"woefully incompetent writers\", and thus demanded \"competent writers\" to remake the eighth season of ''Game of Thrones'' in a manner \"that makes sense\".<ref>Multiple sources:\n#{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-48303921 |title=Game of Thrones petition: 500,000 demand series eight remake |date=May 16, 2019 |website=[[BBC News]] |access-date=May 17, 2019}}\n#{{cite web |last1=McCarthy |first1=Tyler |title='Game of Thrones' fans are petitioning HBO to remake the last season 'with competent writers' |url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/game-of-thrones-petition-remake-last-season |website=[[Fox News]] |date=May 16, 2019 |accessdate=May 20, 2019}}\n#{{cite web |title=\u2018This was abysmal\u2019: Nearly 1 million disgruntled \u2018Game of Thrones\u2019 fans demand a final season remake |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/05/17/game-thrones-petition-remake-season |website=[[The Washington Post]] |date=May 17, 2019 |accessdate=May 26, 2019}}\n#{{cite web |last1=Fieldstadt |first1=Elisha |title=Nearly 800,000 'Game of Thrones' fans sign petition for remake of season 8 |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/pop-culture/tv/over-370-000-game-thrones-fans-sign-petition-remake-season-n1006326 |website=[[NBC News]] |date=May 16, 2019 |accessdate=May 17, 2019}}\n#{{cite web |last1=Jancelewicz |first1=Chris |title=More than 1 million upset \u2018Game of Thrones\u2019 fans sign petition to remake Season 8 |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/5280447/game-of-thrones-season-8-petition/ |website=[[Global News]] |date=May 15, 2019 |accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref> The petition eventually amassed over 1.<!-- THIS SOURCE SAYS 1.5 MILLION. IF YOU WANT TO UPDATE THE NUMBER ABOVE 1 MILLION, FIND AN UPDATED SOURCE PLEASE. CHANGE.ORG IS BLACKLISTED FROM WIKIPEDIA, WE CANNOT USE THAT-->5&nbsp;million signatures.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/features/game-of-thrones-final-tv-show-endings-breaking-bad-mad-men-lost-a8929186.html |title=Game of Thrones, The Sopranos, Lost \u2013 why is it so hard for TV shows to pull off the perfect ending? |last=Staples |first=Louis |website=[[The Independent]] |access-date=May 26, 2019}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]], writing for the ''[[Chicago Sun Times]]'', described that the backlash to the eighth season was so great that in his 25+ years of reviewing movies and television, he doubts that he has \"ever seen the level of fan (and to a lesser degree, critical) vitriol leveled at\" ''Game of Thrones''.<ref name=\"ChicagoS8E6\">{{Cite web |url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/2019/5/19/18632010/game-of-thrones-finale-review-daenerys-tyrion-hbo |title=\u2018Game of Thrones\u2019 finale review: Enthralling series comes to a satisfying end |last=Roeper |first=Richard |date=May 19, 2019 |website=[[Chicago Sun Times]] |access-date=May 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn early August 2019, Benioff and Weiss negotiated an exclusive multi-year film and television deal with [[Netflix]] worth US$200&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Munzenrieder |first1=Kyle |title=What Will David Benioff and D.B. Weiss Bring to Netflix For $200 Million? |url=https://www.wmagazine.com/story/david-benioff-db-weiss-netflix-deal |accessdate=3 November 2019 |work=[[W (magazine)|W]] |date=8 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Statt |first1=Nick |title=Game of Thrones creators sign $200 million Netflix deal to make exclusive shows and films |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/8/7/20761099/game-of-thrones-david-benioff-db-weiss-netflix-deal-200-million-disney-stars |accessdate=3 November 2019 |work=[[The Verge]] |date=7 August 2019}}</ref> Due to their commitments to Netflix, Benioff and Weiss exited their contract to produce ''Star Wars'' films for Disney and [[Lucasfilm]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/10/star-wars-setback-game-of-thrones-duo-david-benioff-d-b-weiss-exit-trilogy-1202771184/ |title=\u2018Star Wars\u2019 Setback: \u2018Game Of Thrones\u2019 Duo David Benioff & D.B. Weiss Exit Trilogy |last=Boucher |first=Geoff |date=October 29, 2019 |website=Deadline Hollywood |url-status=live |access-date=October 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Game of Thrones creators Benioff and Weiss drop Star Wars movies for Netflix |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/oct/29/game-of-thrones-creators-benioff-and-weiss-drop-star-wars-movies-for-netflix |accessdate=29 October 2019 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=29 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Byford |first1=Sam |title=Game of Thrones showrunners quit Star Wars trilogy to work on Netflix projects |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/10/29/20937689/benioff-weiss-star-wars-trilogy-cancelled-netflix |accessdate=29 October 2019 |work=[[The Verge]] |date=29 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Directing career===\nBenioff and Weiss together directed two episodes of ''Game of Thrones'', but used a coin-flip to decide who would get the credit on the show. Benioff was given the credit for [[Game of Thrones (season 3)|season 3]] episode 3, \"[[Walk of Punishment]]\", while Weiss was credited with [[Game of Thrones (season 4)|season 4]] episode 1, \"[[Two Swords (Game of Thrones)|Two Swords]]\".<ref name=\"vanity fair\" /> Benioff and Weiss co-directed the series finale.<ref name=\"Game of Thrones season 8 directors revealed: Fan favorites return\">{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2017/09/26/game-thrones-season-8-directors/|title=\u2018Game of Thrones season 8 directors revealed: Fan favorites return|last=Hibberd |first=James |date=September 26, 2017 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=September 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBenioff and Weiss's first project on Netflix were as directors of the [[stand-up comedy]] special ''Leslie Jones: Time Machine''.<ref name=\"Leslie Jones gets a Game of Thrones-themed trailer for Netflix special Time Machine\">{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/12/19/leslie-jones-time-machine-trailer-game-of-thrones/|title=\u2018Leslie Jones gets a Game of Thrones-themed trailer for Netflix special Time Machine|last=Bucksbaum|first=Sydney|date=December 19, 2019 |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |access-date=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn September 30, 2006, Benioff married actress [[Amanda Peet]] in [[New York City]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1224905,00.html |title=Amanda Peet Weds Screenwriter Beau |last=Messer |first=Lesley |date=September 30, 2006 |work=[[People (magazine)|People]] |access-date=April 9, 2011 |last2=Herbst |first2=Diane}}</ref> Together they have three children.<ref name=\"latimes.com\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-amanda-peet-baby-boy-henry-david-benioff-20141208-story.html |title=Amanda Peet, 'Game of Thrones' producer David Benioff welcome baby boy |last=Saad |first=Nardine |work=Los Angeles Times |access-date=19 March 2018}}</ref> The family lives in [[Manhattan]] and [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]].\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Author===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Year !! Type !! Note\n|-\n| ''[[The 25th Hour]]'' || 2001 || [[Novel]] || Paperback: 224 pages<br/>Publisher: [[Plume (publishing)|Plume]]; Reissue edition (January 29, 2002)<br/>Language: English<br/>{{ISBN|0-452-28295-0}}\n|-\n| ''[[When the Nines Roll Over|When the Nines Roll Over (and Other Stories)]]'' || 2004 || Short Story Collection || Hardcover: 223 pages<br/>Publisher: [[Viking Books]] (August 19, 2004)<br/>Language: English<br/>{{ISBN|0-670-03339-1}}\n|-\n| ''[[City of Thieves (novel)|City of Thieves]]'' || 2008 || Novel || Hardcover: 281 pages<br/>Publisher: [[Viking Books]] (May 15, 2008)<br/>Language: English<br/>{{ISBN|0-670-01870-8}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! width=\"33\" | Year !!  Title !! width=\"65\" |[[Screenwriter|Writer]]!! width=\"65\" |[[film producer|Producer]]\n![[Film director|Director]]!! | Notes\n|-\n|-\n| 2002\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''[[25th Hour]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|[[Spike Lee]]\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| Nominated\u2014[[Boston Society of Film Critics Award for Best Screenplay]] (2002)\n|-\n| 2004\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''[[Troy (film)|Troy]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|[[Wolfgang Petersen]]\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2005\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''[[Stay (2005 film)|Stay]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|[[Marc Forster]]\n| style=\"text-align:left\"|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''When the Nines Roll Over''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|Himself\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| Short film based on a story from ''[[When the Nines Roll Over]]''\n|-\n| 2007\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''[[The Kite Runner (film)|The Kite Runner]]'' \n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|Marc Forster\n| style=\"text-align:left\"|[[Christopher Award]] for Best Feature Film (2007)<br>Nominated\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for Best Foreign Language Film]] (2008)<br>Nominated\u2014[[BAFTA Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]] (2008)<br>Nominated\u2014[[Satellite Award for Best Adapted Screenplay]] (2007)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2009\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''[[X-Men Origins: Wolverine]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|[[Gavin Hood]]\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| Co-wrote with [[Skip Woods]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''[[Brothers (2009 film)|Brothers]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|[[Jim Sheridan]]\n| style=\"text-align:left\"|\n|-\n| 2019\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''[[Gemini Man (film)|Gemini Man]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n|[[Ang Lee]]\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| Co-wrote with [[Billy Ray (screenwriter)|Billy Ray]] and [[Darren Lemke]]\n|- \n| TBA\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| ''Lovecraft''\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n|TBA\n| style=\"text-align:left\"| Co-produce with [[D.B. Weiss]]\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! width=\"56\" | Year !!  