{"title_page": "UAAP Season 66 men's basketball tournament", "text_new": "{{Infobox PhilCollFinals\n|host=[[Ateneo de Manila University]]\n|title = UAAP Season 66\n|higherseed ={{UAAPteam|Ateneo}}\n|lowerseed = '''{{UAAPteam|FEU}}'''\n\n|higherseed_game1 = 65\n|higherseed_game2 =53\n|higherseed_series = 0\n\n|lowerseed_game1 = '''83'''\n|lowerseed_game2 = '''69'''\n|lowerseed_series = 2\n\n|duration = October 1 to 5\n|arena = [[Araneta Coliseum]]\n|MVP = [[Arwind Santos]]\n|coach = [[Koy Banal]]\n|network = [[Studio 23]] and [[The Filipino Channel|TFC]]\n|semis = {{UAAPteam|UE}}<br>{{UAAPteam|La Salle}}\n\n|prevlink=UAAP Season 65 men's basketball tournament\n|prev=65\n|seasonlink=UAAP Season 66\n|year=2003\n|nextlink=UAAP Season 67 men's basketball tournament\n|next=67\n}}\nThe''' UAAP Season 66 men's basketball tournament''' refers to the men's basketball tournament of [[UAAP Season 66]] (2003\u201304 season) of the [[University Athletic Association of the Philippines]] (UAAP). The tournament was hosted by [[Ateneo de Manila University]]. [[ABS-CBN]] covered the games on [[Studio 23]].\n\nAfter a UAAP Board decision that upheld the [[UE Red Warriors]]' protest against the [[De La Salle Green Archers]], three teams ended tied for first after the elimination round. By virtue of having the superior point differential from games among the tied teams, the defending champions [[Ateneo Blue Eagles]] secured the #1 seed; the [[FEU Tamaraws]] defeated UE in the second-seed playoff in a virtual game one of a best-of-3 series. Ateneo needed their twice-to-beat advantage to outlast La Salle in a fight-marred series to advance to the Finals, while FEU needed one game to eliminate a stubborn UE team. In the Finals, FEU coach Koy Banal led the team to victory over a tired Ateneo team coached by his brother Joel to win FEU's first UAAP men's basketball championship since 1997.\n\nUE's [[James Yap]] was named Most Valuable Player (MVP) of the season. [[Arwind Santos]] was named Finals MVP.\n\n==Elimination round==\n<section begin=\"Men's standings\" />{{UAAPteam standings |source=[https://sports.abs-cbn.com/uaap ABS-CBN Sports]\n|tm1 = Ateneo   |tm1-w = 11|tm1-l = 3 |bg1=2X |hth1=Head-to-head goal averages: Ateneo +21, UE \u20135, FEU \u201316; second-seed playoff: FEU 80\u201375 UE\n|tm2 = FEU      |tm2-w = 11|tm2-l = 3 |bg2=2X |hth2=TEAM1 |status2=host\n|tm3 = UE       |tm3-w = 11|tm3-l = 3 |bg3=SF |hth3=TEAM1\n|tm4 = La Salle |tm4-w = 7 |tm4-l = 7 |bg4=SF\n|tm5 = Adamson  |tm5-w = 5 |tm5-l = 9 |hth5=Overall point differential: Adamson &minus;59, UST &minus;62\n|tm6 = UST      |tm6-w = 5 |tm6-l = 9 |hth6=TEAM5\n|tm7 = UP       |tm7-w = 3 |tm7-l = 11\n|tm8 = NU       |tm8-w = 1 |tm8-l = 13\n}}<section end=\"Men's standings\" />\n\nUE put the result of their 65\u201364 second round game loss against La Salle under protest as UE contended that [[Junjun Cabatu]]'s last-second three-point [[buzzer beater]] for La Salle was made after the end-game buzzer sounded. After the UAAP Technical Committee, citing a review of the tapes that showed the ball was until in Cabatu's fingertips as time expired, concluded that indeed the ball was released after time expired, the UAAP Board upheld UE's protest and awarded UE the 64\u201362 victory. This earned them a playoff for the second seed against FEU as they ended up in a three-way tie for first place. Ateneo, with the superior point differential, won the #1 seed.<ref>{{cite news|title=UE protest upheld; Ateneo vs La Salle in semis |first=Nick |last=Giongco |work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |date=2003-09-13 |accessdate=2010-10-10 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/manila-bulletin/mi_7968/is_2003_Sept_19/ue-protest-upheld-ateneo-la/ai_n33554775/?tag=content;col1}}</ref>\n\n==Bracket==\n<section begin=\"Men's bracket\" />{{RPFinalFourbracket-ko| KO=Second-seed playoff\n| 2seed-team1={{UAAPteam|UE|short}}\n| 2seed-score1=75\n| 2seed-team2='''{{UAAPteam|FEU|short}}'''\n| 2seed-score2='''80'''\n| RD1-seed1='''1'''\n| RD1-team1='''{{UAAPteam|Ateneo|short}}'''\n| RD1-score1A=72*\n| RD1-score1B='''74'''\n| RD1-seed2=4\n| RD1-team2={{UAAPteam|La Salle|short}}\n| RD1-score2A='''76'''\n| RD1-score2B=68\n| RD1-seed3='''2'''\n| RD1-team3='''{{UAAPteam|FEU|short}}'''\n| RD1-score3A='''67'''\n| RD1-seed4=3\n| RD1-team4={{UAAPteam|UE|short}}\n| RD1-score4A=63\n| RD2-seed1=1\n| RD2-team1={{UAAPteam|Ateneo|short}}\n| RD2-score1A=65\n| RD2-score1B=53\n| RD2-seed2='''2'''\n| RD2-team2='''{{UAAPteam|FEU|short}}'''\n| RD2-score2A='''83'''\n| RD2-score2B='''69'''\n| RD2-note=Number of asterisks denotes the number of overtimes.\n}}<section end=\"Men's bracket\" />\n\n==Second\u2013seed playoff==\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=September 20 |place=[[Araneta Coliseum]], [[Quezon City]] |TV=[[Studio 23]]\n|teamA='''{{UAAPteam-rt|FEU}}''' |scoreA='''80'''\n|teamB={{UAAPteam|UE}} |scoreB=75\n}}\nUE fell behind by as much as 18 points in the fourth quarter, but caught up with FEU due to their trapping defense. Olan Omiping hit a shot to start a 21\u20134 UE run, that was ended by RJ Masbang when he scored on a three-point play to cut FEU's lead to one point. [[Denok Miranda]] and [[Mark Isip]] initiated a 5\u20130 FEU run when UE coach Boyzie Zamar benched Masbang for shooter Charles Tan, who turned the ball over and fouled Santos that caused a three-point play to put FEU up by eight points. Up by three points, Santos tipped-in a Miranda miss to seal the win for FEU and the #2 seed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamaraws strike |work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |date=2003-09-21 |accessdate=2010-10-10 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/manila-bulletin/mi_7968/is_2003_Sept_21/tamaraws-strike/ai_n33554870/?tag=content;col1}}</ref>\n\n==Semifinals==\n===FEU\u2013UE series===\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=September 24 |place=[[Araneta Coliseum]], [[Quezon City]] |TV=[[Studio 23]]\n|teamA='''{{UAAPteam-rt|FEU}}''' |scoreA='''67'''\n|teamB={{UAAPteam|UE}} |scoreB=63\n|series=FEU wins series in one game\n}}\nFEU and UE were locked in a close game until the final minutes. [[Paul Artadi]] scored a three-pointer to put the Red Warriors up 61\u201360. [[RJ Rizada]] and Gerald Jones scored baskets late in the game to eliminate the Red Warriors anew.<ref name=\"semis 1\">{{cite news|title=DLSU forces do-or-die |work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |first=Nick |last=Giongco |date=2003-09-25 |accessdate=2010-10-10 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/manila-bulletin/mi_7968/is_2003_Sept_21/tamaraws-strike/ai_n33554870/?tag=content;col1}}</ref>\n\n===Ateneo\u2013La Salle series===\n====Game 1====\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=September 24 |place=[[Araneta Coliseum]], [[Quezon City]] |TV=[[Studio 23]] |overtime=OT\n|teamA={{UAAPteam-rt|Ateneo}} |scoreA=72\n|teamB='''{{UAAPteam|La Salle}}''' |scoreB='''76'''\n|series=La Salle extends series\n}}\nWith former [[Chicago Bulls]] player [[Scott Burrell]] at court side, Ateneo led for much of the game; La Salle top scorer [[Mark Cardona]] was injured. La Salle's [[Joseph Yeo]] led the Archers back into the game; [[Jerwin Gaco]] scored on a put-back after a La Salle miss to force [[Overtime (sports)#Basketball|overtime]]. With 1:31 left in the overtime period, a bench-clearing brawl erupted after Gaco bumped [[LA Tenorio]] after a loose-ball scramble. Slo-mo replays later showed Tenorio sneaked in a punch to Gaco's side. After commissioner [[Joe Lipa]] and [[Araneta Coliseum]] personnel restored order, referees thrown out Ateneo's [[Magnum Membrere]] and La Salle's [[Ryan Ara\u00f1a]]. Yeo, who scored 31 points, and JV Casio led La Salle at the end of overtime to extend the series.<ref name=\"semis 1\"/>\n\n====Game 2====\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=September 30 |place=[[Araneta Coliseum]], [[Quezon City]] |TV=[[Studio 23]]\n|teamA='''{{UAAPteam-rt|Ateneo}}''' |scoreA='''74'''\n|teamB={{UAAPteam|La Salle}} |scoreB=68\n|series=Ateneo wins series in two games\n}}\nAfter the fracas at their first semifinals game, Tenorio was suspended. This gave [[Macky Escalona]] Tenorio's starting point-guard spot. Cardona, who was dressed to play, was not fielded in by La Salle coach Franz Pumaren. At the end of the first half, a commotion broke out between the two teams in the Araneta Coliseum tunnel as they went to their respective locker rooms. At the stands, there were at least three incidents of shoving, punching and debris-throwing involving officials and supporters. Lipa ordered a certain fan to be expelled after having a word war with the Ateneo supporters. Midway through the third quarter, Ateneo led 47\u201333 but La Salle crept up. At the fourth quarter, as Ateneo's shot clock was running out, center [[Paolo Bugia]] made an improbable three-pointer to pad their lead 63\u201359. [[Larry Fonacier]] scored six straight points in the final 61 seconds to put Ateneo up for good; after [[Joseph Yeo]] scored on a three-pointer to cut Ateneo's lead 71\u201368, Fonacier made two free-throws off Cabatu's unsportsmanlike foul to put them up by five points. A last-ditch foul from Casio on [[Macky Escalona]] settled the final score as Escalona split his free-throws.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ateneo going to the dance |work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |first=Nick |last=Giongco |date=2003-09-30 |accessdate=2010-10-10 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/manila-bulletin/mi_7968/is_2003_Sept_21/tamaraws-strike/ai_n33554870/?tag=content;col1}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the game, another scuffle between the supporters broke out, and included former Ateneo players [[Enrico Villanueva]], Rainier Sison and Andrew Cruz; both Sison and Cruz suffered bruises. Uniformed policemen, including the SWAT team, and Araneta Coliseum security guards restored order.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hooliganism mars KO game |work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |first=Tito  |last=Talao |date=2003-09-30 |accessdate=2010-10-10 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/manila-bulletin/mi_7968/is_2003_Sept_30/hooliganism-mars-ko-game/ai_n33561125/}}</ref>\n\n==Finals==\nIn the finals, defending champion Ateneo coach Joel Banal faced his brother, FEU coach Koy.\n===Game 1===\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=October 2 |place=[[Araneta Coliseum]], [[Quezon City]] |TV=[[Studio 23]]\n|teamA='''{{UAAPteam-rt|FEU}}''' |scoreA='''83'''\n|teamB={{UAAPteam|Ateneo}} |scoreB=65\n|series=FEU leads series 1\u20130\n}}\nAteneo threatened to blow the game wide open in the first quarter, but FEU responded with defense that gave Ateneo few easy points. The Tamaraws grabbed rebounds that led into easy fast break points to cruise to an easy win to lead the best-of-3 series 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tired Eagles fall prey to Tams|work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |first=Nick |last=Giongco |date=2003-10-02 |accessdate=2010-10-10 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/manila-bulletin/mi_7968/is_2003_Oct_2/tired-eagles-fall-prey-tams/ai_n33562491/?tag=content;col1}}</ref>\n\n===Game 2===\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=October 5 |place=[[Araneta Coliseum]], [[Quezon City]] |TV=[[Studio 23]]\n|teamA='''{{UAAPteam-rt|FEU}}''' |scoreA='''69'''\n|teamB={{UAAPteam|Ateneo}} |scoreB=53\n|series=FEU wins series 2\u20130\n}}\nFEU led for most of the game, with [[Cesar Catli]], [[RJ Rizada]] and Rhagnee Singco scoring baskets to increase FEU's lead 39\u201326. Ateneo cut the lead 46\u201339 near the end of the third quarter thanks to [[Larry Fonacier]]'s free-throws. However, [[Jeffrei Chan]] scored on a three-point shot to increase FEU's lead to ten to end the quarter. At the start of the fourth quarter, FEU led for good, 56\u201339, after a Gerald Jones shot. The Eagles threatened anew late in the fourth, but [[Dennis Miranda]] converted a three-point shot with 2:31 left to put the Eagles away, 63\u201350. FEU won their first UAAP men's basketball championship since 1997.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamaraws all the way |work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |first=Nick |last=Giongco |date=2003-10-05 |accessdate=2010-10-10 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/manila-bulletin/mi_7968/is_2003_Oct_5/tamaraws/ai_n33564135/?tag=content;col1}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast notes==\n===UAAP Final Four===\nSeptember 25, 2003\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!Game !! [[Play-by-play]] !! [[Color commentator|Analyst]] !! Team\n|-\n|Game 1 || Boom Gonzalez || Randy Sacdalan || FEU vs. UE\n|-\n|Game 1 || Jude Turcuato || [[Ryan Gregorio]] || [[Ateneo - La Salle rivalry|DLSU vs. ADMU]]\n|}\n\nSeptember 30, 2003\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!Game !! [[Play-by-play]] !! [[Color commentator|Analyst]] !! Team\n|-\n|Game 2 || Boom Gonzalez || Randy Sacdalan || [[Ateneo - La Salle rivalry|DLSU vs. ADMU]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===UAAP Finals===\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!Game !! [[Play-by-play]] !! [[Color commentator|Analyst]]\n|-\n|Game 1 || Jude Turcuato || Randy Sacdalan\n|-\n|Game 2 || Jude Turcuato || [[Ryan Gregorio]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{start box}}\n{{succession box\n|before = [[UAAP Season 65 men's basketball tournament|Season 65 (2002)]]\n|after = [[UAAP Season 67 men's basketball tournament|Season 67 (2004)]]\n|title = [[UAAP]] men's basketball seasons\n|years = [[UAAP Season 66|Season 66 (2003)]] [[UAAP Season 66 basketball tournaments|basketball]] |\n}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{UAAP men's basketball}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uaap}}\n[[Category:UAAP men's basketball tournament|66]]\n[[Category:2003 in Philippine basketball]]\n[[Category:UAAP Season 66]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox PhilCollFinals\n|host=[[Ateneo de Manila University]]\n|title = UAAP Season 66\n|higherseed ={{UAAPteam|Ateneo}}\n|lowerseed = '''{{UAAPteam|FEU}}'''\n\n|higherseed_game1 = 65\n|higherseed_game2 =53\n|higherseed_series = 0\n\n|lowerseed_game1 = '''83'''\n|lowerseed_game2 = '''69'''\n|lowerseed_series = 2\n\n|duration = October 1 to 5\n|arena = [[Araneta Coliseum]]\n|MVP = [[Arwind Santos]]\n|coach = [[Koy Banal]]\n|network = [[Studio 23]] and [[The Filipino Channel|TFC]]\n|semis = {{UAAPteam|UE}}<br>{{UAAPteam|La Salle}}\n\n|prevlink=UAAP Season 65 men's basketball tournament\n|prev=65\n|seasonlink=UAAP Season 66\n|year=2003\n|nextlink=UAAP Season 67 men's basketball tournament\n|next=67\n}}\nThe''' UAAP Season 66 men's basketball tournament''' refers to the men's basketball tournament of [[UAAP Season 66]] (2003\u201304 season) of the [[University Athletic Association of the Philippines]] (UAAP). The tournament was hosted by [[Ateneo de Manila University]]. [[ABS-CBN]] covered the games on [[Studio 23]].\n\nAfter a UAAP Board decision that upheld the [[UE Red Warriors]]' protest against the [[De La Salle Green Archers]], three teams ended tied for first after the elimination round. By virtue of having the superior point differential from games among the tied teams, the defending champions [[Ateneo Blue Eagles]] secured the #1 seed; the [[FEU Tamaraws]] defeated UE in the second-seed playoff in a virtual game one of a best-of-3 series. Ateneo needed their twice-to-beat advantage to outlast La Salle in a fight-marred series to advance to the Finals, while FEU needed one game to eliminate a stubborn UE team. In the Finals, FEU coach Koy Banal led the team to victory over a tired Ateneo team coached by his brother Joel to win FEU's first UAAP men's basketball championship since 1997.\n\nUE's [[James Yap]] was named Most Valuable Player (MVP) of the season. [[Arwind Santos]] was named Finals MVP.\n\n==Elimination round==\n<section begin=\"Men's standings\" />{{UAAPteam standings |source=[https://sports.abs-cbn.com/uaap ABS-CBN Sports]\n|tm1 = Ateneo   |tm1-w = 11|tm1-l = 3 |bg1=2X |hth1=Head-to-head goal averages: Ateneo +21, UE \u20135, FEU \u201316; second-seed playoff: FEU 80\u201375 UE\n|tm2 = FEU      |tm2-w = 11|tm2-l = 3 |bg2=2X |hth2=TEAM1 |status2=host\n|tm3 = UE       |tm3-w = 11|tm3-l = 3 |bg3=SF |hth3=TEAM1\n|tm4 = La Salle |tm4-w = 7 |tm4-l = 7 |bg4=SF\n|tm5 = Adamson  |tm5-w = 5 |tm5-l = 9 |hth5=Overall point differential: Adamson &minus;59, UST &minus;62\n|tm6 = UST      |tm6-w = 5 |tm6-l = 9 |hth6=TEAM5\n|tm7 = UP       |tm7-w = 3 |tm7-l = 11\n|tm8 = NU       |tm8-w = 1 |tm8-l = 13\n}}<section end=\"Men's standings\" />\n\nUE put the result of their 65\u201364 second round game loss against La Salle under protest as UE contended that [[Junjun Cabatu]]'s last-second three-point [[buzzer beater]] for La Salle was made after the end-game buzzer sounded. After the UAAP Technical Committee, citing a review of the tapes that showed the ball was until in Cabatu's fingertips as time expired, concluded that indeed the ball was released after time expired, the UAAP Board upheld UE's protest and awarded UE the 64\u201362 victory. This earned them a playoff for the second seed against FEU as they ended up in a three-way tie for first place. Ateneo, with the superior point differential, won the #1 seed.<ref>{{cite news|title=UE protest upheld; Ateneo vs La Salle in semis |first=Nick |last=Giongco |work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |date=2003-09-13 |accessdate=2010-10-10 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/manila-bulletin/mi_7968/is_2003_Sept_19/ue-protest-upheld-ateneo-la/ai_n33554775/?tag=content;col1}}</ref>\n\n==Bracket==\n<section begin=\"Men's bracket\" />{{RPFinalFourbracket-ko| KO=Second-seed playoff\n| 2seed-team1={{UAAPteam|UE|short}}\n| 2seed-score1=75\n| 2seed-team2='''{{UAAPteam|FEU|short}}'''\n| 2seed-score2='''80'''\n| RD1-seed1='''1'''\n| RD1-team1='''{{UAAPteam|Ateneo|short}}'''\n| RD1-score1A=72*\n| RD1-score1B='''74'''\n| RD1-seed2=4\n| RD1-team2={{UAAPteam|La Salle|short}}\n| RD1-score2A='''76'''\n| RD1-score2B=68\n| RD1-seed3='''2'''\n| RD1-team3='''{{UAAPteam|FEU|short}}'''\n| RD1-score3A='''67'''\n| RD1-seed4=3\n| RD1-team4={{UAAPteam|UE|short}}\n| RD1-score4A=63\n| RD2-seed1=1\n| RD2-team1={{UAAPteam|Ateneo|short}}\n| RD2-score1A=65\n| RD2-score1B=53\n| RD2-seed2='''2'''\n| RD2-team2='''{{UAAPteam|FEU|short}}'''\n| RD2-score2A='''83'''\n| RD2-score2B='''69'''\n| RD2-note=Number of asterisks denotes the number of overtimes.\n}}<section end=\"Men's bracket\" />\n\n==Second\u2013seed playoff==\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=September 20 |place=[[Araneta Coliseum]], [[Quezon City]] |TV=[[Studio 23]]\n|teamA='''{{UAAPteam-rt|FEU}}''' |scoreA='''80'''\n|teamB={{UAAPteam|UE}} |scoreB=75\n}}\nUE fell behind by as much as 18 points in the fourth quarter, but caught up with FEU due to their trapping defense. Olan Omiping hit a shot to start a 21\u20134 UE run, that was ended by RJ Masbang when he scored on a three-point play to cut FEU's lead to one point. [[Dennis Miranda|Denok Miranda]] and [[Mark Isip]] initiated a 5\u20130 FEU run when UE coach Boyzie Zamar benched Masbang for shooter Charles Tan, who turned the ball over and fouled Santos that caused a three-point play to put FEU up by eight points. Up by three points, Santos tipped-in a Miranda miss to seal the win for FEU and the #2 seed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamaraws strike |work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |date=2003-09-21 |accessdate=2010-10-10 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/manila-bulletin/mi_7968/is_2003_Sept_21/tamaraws-strike/ai_n33554870/?tag=content;col1}}</ref>\n\n==Semifinals==\n===FEU\u2013UE series===\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=September 24 |place=[[Araneta Coliseum]], [[Quezon City]] |TV=[[Studio 23]]\n|teamA='''{{UAAPteam-rt|FEU}}''' |scoreA='''67'''\n|teamB={{UAAPteam|UE}} |scoreB=63\n|series=FEU wins series in one game\n}}\nFEU and UE were locked in a close game until the final minutes. [[Paul Artadi]] scored a three-pointer to put the Red Warriors up 61\u201360. [[RJ Rizada]] and Gerald Jones scored baskets late in the game to eliminate the Red Warriors anew.<ref name=\"semis 1\">{{cite news|title=DLSU forces do-or-die |work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |first=Nick |last=Giongco |date=2003-09-25 |accessdate=2010-10-10 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/manila-bulletin/mi_7968/is_2003_Sept_21/tamaraws-strike/ai_n33554870/?tag=content;col1}}</ref>\n\n===Ateneo\u2013La Salle series===\n====Game 1====\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=September 24 |place=[[Araneta Coliseum]], [[Quezon City]] |TV=[[Studio 23]] |overtime=OT\n|teamA={{UAAPteam-rt|Ateneo}} |scoreA=72\n|teamB='''{{UAAPteam|La Salle}}''' |scoreB='''76'''\n|series=La Salle extends series\n}}\nWith former [[Chicago Bulls]] player [[Scott Burrell]] at court side, Ateneo led for much of the game; La Salle top scorer [[Mark Cardona]] was injured. La Salle's [[Joseph Yeo]] led the Archers back into the game; [[Jerwin Gaco]] scored on a put-back after a La Salle miss to force [[Overtime (sports)#Basketball|overtime]]. With 1:31 left in the overtime period, a bench-clearing brawl erupted after Gaco bumped [[LA Tenorio]] after a loose-ball scramble. Slo-mo replays later showed Tenorio sneaked in a punch to Gaco's side. After commissioner [[Joe Lipa]] and [[Araneta Coliseum]] personnel restored order, referees thrown out Ateneo's [[Magnum Membrere]] and La Salle's [[Ryan Ara\u00f1a]]. Yeo, who scored 31 points, and JV Casio led La Salle at the end of overtime to extend the series.<ref name=\"semis 1\"/>\n\n====Game 2====\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=September 30 |place=[[Araneta Coliseum]], [[Quezon City]] |TV=[[Studio 23]]\n|teamA='''{{UAAPteam-rt|Ateneo}}''' |scoreA='''74'''\n|teamB={{UAAPteam|La Salle}} |scoreB=68\n|series=Ateneo wins series in two games\n}}\nAfter the fracas at their first semifinals game, Tenorio was suspended. This gave [[Macky Escalona]] Tenorio's starting point-guard spot. Cardona, who was dressed to play, was not fielded in by La Salle coach Franz Pumaren. At the end of the first half, a commotion broke out between the two teams in the Araneta Coliseum tunnel as they went to their respective locker rooms. At the stands, there were at least three incidents of shoving, punching and debris-throwing involving officials and supporters. Lipa ordered a certain fan to be expelled after having a word war with the Ateneo supporters. Midway through the third quarter, Ateneo led 47\u201333 but La Salle crept up. At the fourth quarter, as Ateneo's shot clock was running out, center [[Paolo Bugia]] made an improbable three-pointer to pad their lead 63\u201359. [[Larry Fonacier]] scored six straight points in the final 61 seconds to put Ateneo up for good; after [[Joseph Yeo]] scored on a three-pointer to cut Ateneo's lead 71\u201368, Fonacier made two free-throws off Cabatu's unsportsmanlike foul to put them up by five points. A last-ditch foul from Casio on [[Macky Escalona]] settled the final score as Escalona split his free-throws.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ateneo going to the dance |work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |first=Nick |last=Giongco |date=2003-09-30 |accessdate=2010-10-10 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/manila-bulletin/mi_7968/is_2003_Sept_21/tamaraws-strike/ai_n33554870/?tag=content;col1}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the game, another scuffle between the supporters broke out, and included former Ateneo players [[Enrico Villanueva]], Rainier Sison and Andrew Cruz; both Sison and Cruz suffered bruises. Uniformed policemen, including the SWAT team, and Araneta Coliseum security guards restored order.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hooliganism mars KO game |work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |first=Tito  |last=Talao |date=2003-09-30 |accessdate=2010-10-10 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/manila-bulletin/mi_7968/is_2003_Sept_30/hooliganism-mars-ko-game/ai_n33561125/}}</ref>\n\n==Finals==\nIn the finals, defending champion Ateneo coach Joel Banal faced his brother, FEU coach Koy.\n===Game 1===\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=October 2 |place=[[Araneta Coliseum]], [[Quezon City]] |TV=[[Studio 23]]\n|teamA='''{{UAAPteam-rt|FEU}}''' |scoreA='''83'''\n|teamB={{UAAPteam|Ateneo}} |scoreB=65\n|series=FEU leads series 1\u20130\n}}\nAteneo threatened to blow the game wide open in the first quarter, but FEU responded with defense that gave Ateneo few easy points. The Tamaraws grabbed rebounds that led into easy fast break points to cruise to an easy win to lead the best-of-3 series 1\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tired Eagles fall prey to Tams|work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |first=Nick |last=Giongco |date=2003-10-02 |accessdate=2010-10-10 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/manila-bulletin/mi_7968/is_2003_Oct_2/tired-eagles-fall-prey-tams/ai_n33562491/?tag=content;col1}}</ref>\n\n===Game 2===\n{{basketballbox|bg=#eee |date=October 5 |place=[[Araneta Coliseum]], [[Quezon City]] |TV=[[Studio 23]]\n|teamA='''{{UAAPteam-rt|FEU}}''' |scoreA='''69'''\n|teamB={{UAAPteam|Ateneo}} |scoreB=53\n|series=FEU wins series 2\u20130\n}}\nFEU led for most of the game, with [[Cesar Catli]], [[RJ Rizada]] and Rhagnee Singco scoring baskets to increase FEU's lead 39\u201326. Ateneo cut the lead 46\u201339 near the end of the third quarter thanks to [[Larry Fonacier]]'s free-throws. However, [[Jeffrei Chan]] scored on a three-point shot to increase FEU's lead to ten to end the quarter. At the start of the fourth quarter, FEU led for good, 56\u201339, after a Gerald Jones shot. The Eagles threatened anew late in the fourth, but [[Dennis Miranda]] converted a three-point shot with 2:31 left to put the Eagles away, 63\u201350. FEU won their first UAAP men's basketball championship since 1997.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamaraws all the way |work=[[Manila Bulletin]] |first=Nick |last=Giongco |date=2003-10-05 |accessdate=2010-10-10 |url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/manila-bulletin/mi_7968/is_2003_Oct_5/tamaraws/ai_n33564135/?tag=content;col1}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast notes==\n===UAAP Final Four===\nSeptember 25, 2003\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!Game !! [[Play-by-play]] !! [[Color commentator|Analyst]] !! Team\n|-\n|Game 1 || Boom Gonzalez || Randy Sacdalan || FEU vs. UE\n|-\n|Game 1 || Jude Turcuato || [[Ryan Gregorio]] || [[Ateneo - La Salle rivalry|DLSU vs. ADMU]]\n|}\n\nSeptember 30, 2003\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!Game !! [[Play-by-play]] !! [[Color commentator|Analyst]] !! Team\n|-\n|Game 2 || Boom Gonzalez || Randy Sacdalan || [[Ateneo - La Salle rivalry|DLSU vs. ADMU]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===UAAP Finals===\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!Game !! [[Play-by-